<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wallach     06-14 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wallach,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese's Friend Says He Rejected Leniency Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E. Robert Wallach says he refused to
testify against his longtime friend, Attorney General Edwin Meese
III, in exchange for a government offer of leniency in the Wedtech
Corp. influence peddling case.
   Wallach, 54, made the statement in an interview broadcast
Tuesday night on KRON-TV, an NBC affiliate. KRON said the interview
was recorded earlier and that further portions would be broadcast
on a Wednesday night news program.
   The San Francisco trial lawyer called Meese ``an honorable man''
and said there ``is nothing to talk about'' with prosecutors
investigating allegations that Meese improperly used his influence
on Wallach's behalf in a proposed Iraqi pipeline deal.
   Wallach, who has known Meese since law school, made the
statement about leniency when asked if prosecutors had approached
his lawyers to work out a deal.
   ``Yes, they did,'' Wallach said.
   Wallach told KRON he learned he was about to be indicted on Dec.
22, when Baruch Weiss, an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern
District of New York, contacted Wallach's lawyer.
   ``(Weiss) notified my then-counsel that they had to give up the
arrangements they had entered into with him for a series of
meetings to discuss possible allegations against me,'' Wallach said.
   Instead, Wallach added, Weiss presented his lawyer with a draft
of the indictment.
   ``(He) gave me three days in which to plead guilty and cooperate
_ and then said if, in fact, I would give it some thought, perhaps
they wouldn't indict me on a racketeering charge,'' Wallach said.
   The station said Weiss replied, ``I cannot comment on that''
when asked if Wallach had been offered leniency in exchange for
testimony against the attorney general.
   Wallach said he was an unpaid adviser to Wedtech, a Bronx-based,
minority-owned defense contractor. He is under indictment on
federal racketeering charges for allegedly taking payoffs from
Wedtech officials to influence Meese and other public officials.
   Former Wedtech officials have testified they paid $800,000 to
Wallach to influence Meese. They have said Wallach told them he got
the attorney general to intercede on the company's behalf for a
series of contracts worth $143 million. Meese has denied any
wrongdoing.
   Wallach told KRON he expects to be acquitted of the racketeering
charges and said the indictment ``appears to be very contrived and
very contorted and extremely difficult to find a crime within it.''
</TEXT>
