<1ST_LINE>r i AMBritain-Amnesty     06-14 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM Britain-Amnesty,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty says 85 U.N. members violate human rights charter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Wednesday that 85 of
the 159 members of the United Nations violate the organization's
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   In a report covering the first four months of 1988, London-based
Amnesty International said it had identified 3,352 individual cases
of people jailed for the non-violent excercise of their rights as
defined by the U.N. document.
   The declaration, adopted by the U.N. General Assembly in 1948,
calls for civil, political, economic, social, and cultural rights
for all people.
   Amnesty International reported it had issued 115 appeals since
Jan. 1 to 45 countries involving more than 450 prisoners who the
human rights organization said it considers at risk of violations
of their rights including torture and death.
   The report said Amnesty International sent 18 missions to 15
countries from January-April and issued 98 documents on human
rights violations.
   ``None of these reports or initiatives should have been
necessary,'' it said. ``In the 40th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, such abuses should have become only a
ghost from the past.''
</TEXT>
