<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerPrizes     06-14 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Prizes,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Win Cancer Research Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four scientists will share three $130,000 prizes
for their work into breast cancer screening, the genetics of cancer
and a substance that helps cells communicate.
   The General Motors Cancer Research Foundation Prizes will be
presented Wednesday at the National Academy of Sciences in
Washington, D.C., the foundation said.
   Each prize includes $100,000 plus $30,000 to cover expenses for
a scientific conference or workshop.
   Sam Shapiro, professor emeritus of health policy and management
at the Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene and Public Health in
Baltimore, will share one award with Philip Strax, clinical
professor of oncology and radiology at the University of Miami
School of Medicine.
   They will be honored for conducting a massive study
demonstrating that using mammography, or breast X-rays, to detect
breast cancer in its early stages can save lives.
   Alfred Knudson, senior member of the Institute for Cancer
Research at the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia, will be
honored for proposing a theory of ``anti-cancer'' genes. Damage to
these genes can lead to cancer.
   Evidence for such genes has been found in some rare tumors and
in cancers of the breast, colon, and lung.
   The third prize will go to Yasutomi Nishizuka, professor and
chairman of biochemistry at the Kobe Univerisity School of Medicine
in Japan. He discovered and purified a substance called protein
kinase C, which plays a key role in handling chemical messages that
come to a cell.
   He also showed that environmental chemicals can act directly on
that substance to promote cancer.
</TEXT>
