<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     06-14 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War on Cocaine Moves into USDA Greenhouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department greenhouse has
become the site of a million-dollar battle to find some way to
stamp out the coca plants grown illicitly in South America and
processed into cocaine, USDA officials confirm.
   The greenhouse near Washington is one of two USDA research sites
where 400 to 600 coca plants are being produced under the project,
Dr. Edward B. Knipling of the Agriculture Research Service said
Monday.
   The other is an outdoor site at an undisclosed location in the
United States where the largely tropical plants will not be hit
with frost, he said.
   He said the plants used in the experiment are incinerated
afterward and that cocaine is never produced from them. The
objective is to test herbicides to determine which ones are
effective in killing the hardy coca plants.
   Researchers earlier had grown opium poppies in Thailand and
marijuana in the United States as part of USDA's research into ways
to stem narcotics. But the priority changed two years ago because
of growing use by Americans of both cocaine and crack, a cocaine
derivative, Knipling said.
   USDA's coca production was disclosed Sunday in The New York
Times.
   Knipling estimated the cost of the program at ``about $1 million
a year.'' He said some funds come from the research service's
regular budget and the rest from the State Department.
   Guards, alarms and wire fences are being used to keep out
intruders at the installations, Knipling said. He refused to
disclose the precise whereabouts of either of the growing sites.
   Coca seeds were brought to the United States from South America,
Knipling said. He said a number of herbicides have been tested for
use against coca.
   The chief herbicide recommended to the State Department is
tebutherion, a product manufactured by Eli Lilly & Co. of
Indianapolis under the trade name Spike. Knipling said it is used
in the United States to clear brush in areas where food crops do
not grow.
   The subject of USDA's testing surfaced when the former head of
the project, Walter Gentner, told reporters he had resigned in
April to protest what he called the failure of the Agriculture and
State departments to examine thoroughly enough the potential
dangers from use of the herbicide.
   Knipling said South American cocaine production is doing far
more to endanger the environment than would use of tebutherion. He
said there was little doubt that the coca leaves were being heavily
sprayed with pesticides, which could cause harm.
   Moreover, he said, sulfuric acid and other chemicals being used
to process the coca into cocaine undoubtedly are dumped into
streams when the manufacturing process is over.
   George Dunlop, assistant secretary of agriculture for natural
resources and the environment, said coca producers, ``in their
efforts to satiate the habits of American cocaine addicts, are
doing heavy and extreme environmental damage.''
   ``They are slashing and burning the tropical rain forest'' to
clear more ground for coca planting, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich emerged from a
visit with Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng and reported no
progress in getting the government to suspend conservation
restrictions to combat drought problems.
   ``I hope there'll be rain in the next two weeks,'' Perpich said
Monday after the session in Lyng's office.
   He said Lyng was encouraging about an emergency feed program to
help livestock producers whose hay and grazing land have been
scorched by drought but refused to lift curbs imposed under the
Conservation Reserve Program.
   That program, established in 1985, aims to take 45 million acres
out of crop production by 1990 and cover them instead with trees
and grasses. Farmers sign contracts to include such highly erodible
lands in the reserve and in exchange obtain government payments.
   USDA officials recently estimated the overall cost of the
reserve program to the taxpayers at $677 million for 1987, $1.864
billion for this year and $2.16 billion next year.
   Lyng has the power in an emergency to suspend program rules that
bar cutting hay and grazing livestock on such lands.
   Perpich said, however, that Lyng was reluctant to do so, saying
the lands involved are fragile and should remain in conservation
use.
   Under an emergency feed program, the federal government would
pay substantial costs for acquiring feed for livestock and bringing
it into the state. But local officials would have to apply for it.
   Lyng's office said he would have no comment on the session with
the Minnesotans.
   Earlier, Perpich met with Sen. Quentin Burdick, D-N.D. The
governor said he would discuss the situation later with Senate
Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
   Minnesota Agriculture Commissioner Jim Nichols said the drought
could wipe out as much as half of the state's crops and that the
cost to the hardest hit counties in that case would total $400
million.
   ``There just is no hay in Minnesota,'' he said. He said that
opening the Conservation Reserve Program acreage would cost the
taxpayers nothing while putting an emergency feed program in effect
would carry a price tag.
</TEXT>
