<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cuba-Angola     06-14 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Angola,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Builds Air Base in Southern Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has added a new dimension to the complex
conflict in southern Africa by constructing a military air base in
southern Angola just a few minutes flying time from South
African-controlled Namibia, according to U.S. officials.
   The construction of the base in support of increased Cuban troop
strength in southern Angola appears to have heightened the
possibility of an eventual clash between Cuban and South African
forces, the officials said.
   In addition to Namibia, South Africa also has forces in Angola
supporting a U.S.-backed anti-communist rebel group.
   The presence of the Cuban troops within 10 miles of the Namibian
border prompted South Africa to call up army reserves last week.
The South Africans say the Cuban forces, interspersed with Namibian
guerrillas fighting for independence, are spread across a 280-mile
front.
   According to the officials, who asked not to be identified, Cuba
appears to be jockeying for position as talks aimed at reaching a
negotiated settlement intensify.
   President Fidel Castro informed a gathering of Third World
foreign ministers meeting in Havana two weeks ago of the
construction of the air base.
   ``We now have air superiority and anti-air superiority,'' Cuban
news accounts of Castro's comments said.
   ``We have the means to confront any South African adventure,''
he said. U.S. officials said the air strip under construction
appears capable of handling MiG-23 jet fighters.
   In early May, South Africa joined the United States and a joint
Angolan-Cuban delegation in London for unprecedented peace talks.
   The U.S. objective is achieving an agreement that will lead to
South Africa's withdrawal from both Angola and Namibia and the
withdrawal of the estimated 43,000 to 45,000 Cuban troops from
Angola.
   Castro said South Africa's willingness to negotiate was the
result of the Cuban troop deployment near the Namibian border.
   Also part of the equation is the American-backed rebel movement
in Angola which has been fighting that country's Marxist government
for 13 years. But the United States considers that issue to be an
internal Angolan problem which should not be part of the
negotiating effort.
   All sides said the London talks were constructive and they
agreed to meet again. There has been no agreement as yet on a site.
   The parties to the conflict are far apart on a timetable for
reaching a settlement. Cuba and Angola have set out a four-year
timetable for the withdrawal of the Cuban troops while insisting on
a one-year process leading to black majority rule and independence
for Namibia as well as the withdrawal of South African occupation
forces from the territory. The independence process for Namibia is
spelled out in a U.N. Security Council resolution.
   Meanwhile, Vice President George Bush pledged on Monday that, if
elected, he will make ``no accommodations'' with Cuba.
   He made the statement at a ceremony formalizing an agreement
with the Cuban-American National Foundation that will permit the
immigration to the United States of about 1,500 Cubans living in
third countries.
   The Foundation, an anti-Castro group, has agreed to pay the
costs of resettling the Cubans in the United States.
</TEXT>
