<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pioneer10     06-14 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pioneer 10,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pioneer 10 Still Sending Back Data Five Years After Leaving Solar
System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 16 years and more than 4
billion miles, Pioneer 10 is still speeding toward interstellar
space and perhaps for the next decade should continue to provide
clues to some of the puzzles of the universe, scientists said.
   The little spacecraft, which left the solar system five years
ago, has literally and figuratively gone far beyond its original
mission to study Jupiter and the asteroid belt, scientists said.
   The 570-pound Pioneer 10 is relaying strong evidence to suggest
a mysterious Planet X or possibly two smaller planets exist beyond
Pluto, John D. Anderson of the National Aeronautics and Space
Adminstration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory said Monday.
   ``We have a 90 to 99 percent confidence that Uranus and Neptune
are being disturbed, and one candidate for that is a single Planet
X,'' he said.
   Anderson and other scientists reported on Pioneer 10 to observe
the fifth anniversary of the craft's leaving the known solar system.
   The probe was launched in 1972 and traveled an arc-shaped, 620
million mile path from Earth before making its closest approach to
Jupiter _ 82,000 miles _ on Dec. 3, 1973.
   Pioneer 10 was the first spacecraft to cross the Asteroid Belt,
between Mars and Jupiter, and fly by Jupiter and return pictures.
It also was the first to chart the giant planet's intense radiation
belts and measure the mass of its four planet-size moons. Data from
Pioneer 10 showed that Jupiter is predominantly liquid.
   Its twin, Pioneer 11, was launched in 1973, encountered Jupiter
a year later and reached Saturn in September 1979.
   Scientists said Pioneer 10 is expected to operate another seven
to 10 years and may run out of energy before it reaches
interstellar space.
   Until then, the spacecraft will keep looking for long gravity
waves proposed by Albert Einstein, and may give scientists clues to
the shape of the heliosphere, the boundary of the sun's influence.
   ``One of the principal current objectives is the observation of
cosmic rays and the flow of the solar wind at heretofore unexplored
distances from the sun,'' said physicist James Van Allen of the
University of Iowa, a principal investigator on the project.
   ``We now have a realistic expectation of finding the outer
boundary of the heliosphere ... and of penetrating into the nearby
interstellar media,'' said Van Allen, who discovered radiation
belts surrounding Earth.
   Pioneer 10 is now sending back radio signals from a distance 45
times the distance between the Earth and sun.
   The energy picked up by a 230-foot deep space antenna would have
to be stored for over 11 billion years to accumulate enough energy
to light a 7{-watt nightlight for one millisecond, said Richard O.
Fimmel, project manager at the NASA Ames Research Center.
   But the signals from Pioneer 10 and 11 are strong enough to send
high quality data on a daily basis, Van Allen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ProductLiability     06-14 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Product Liability,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Limiting Product Liability Nears Committee Approval</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Hearing begins at 10 a.m. EDT; will be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer groups are criticizing a compromise
bill fashioned by the House Energy and Commerce Committee, saying
the measure will make it harder for victims of unsafe products to
recover damages from manufacturers.
   Both sides in the protracted struggle between business and
consumer lobbyists agree, however, that there is virtually no
chance the so-called product liability bill will pass Congress in
this election year.
   The measure will go next to the House Judiciary Committee, which
shares jurisdiction over the issue but has balked at approving such
legislation in the past. Even if it manages to reach the House _
which many congressional observers doubt _ the Senate is considered
a graveyard for product liability bills.
   The measure, eagerly sought by corporations worried about
escalating liability costs, would impose a uniform federal standard
of liability pre-empting a wide variety of conflicting state laws.
   Consumer activists complain that the new proposed federal
standard would limit victims of hazardous products to six narrow
grounds for suing manufacturers for damages: negligence,
intentional wrongdoing, defect design, defective construction,
inadequate warnings and breach of written warranty.
   Another major feature contested by consumer advocates is the
``state of the art'' defense available to manufacturers.
   This provision says that a manufacturer can escape liability for
damages if it can prove it did not know _ or could not know _ of a
design defect with knowledge ``reasonably available to experts,''
or if there were no feasible alternative design.
   A pro-consumer ``escape hatch'' sponsored by Rep. Mike Synar,
D-Okla., would require only that the plaintiff prove that the
product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should
not have been marketed. The committee also accepted Synar's
proposal easing the standard of proof that plaintiffs must meet.
   The Synar provision also would put a burden of proof on the
manufacturer to show that a design defect could not be discovered
and that an alternative design was not feasible.
   Consumer lobbyists are unhappy, though, with Synar's proposal to
give a judge not a trial jury _ the responsibility for deciding
whether a product was so unsafe it should never have been marketed.
   Even with Synar's softening of the pro-business features of the
original bill, consumer groups say the measure undermines the legal
doctrine of ``strict liability'' used by 47 states and favored by
victim advocates.
   That doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the
manufacturer's alleged misconduct to the defective product itself,
relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or
should have known about its product.
   Consumer lobbyists argue that even though the bill makes strict
liability a national standard in deciding damage suits, it is
weakened by including a state-of-the-art defense against
manufacturers' liability, which currently is allowed in only eight
states.
   Not covered by the bill are tobacco, alcohol and asbestos. Those
products would continue to be subject to generally more stringent
state liability laws.
   The bill also includes a provision backed by anti-abortionists
that would deny special protection to any drug or contraceptive
device that induces abortions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PandaExhibit     06-14 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panda Exhibit,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Weighs Arguments In Panda Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge is deliberating whether to
shut down an exhibition of giant pandas at an Ohio zoo because of
complaints from a wilflife group the endangered animals are being
commercially exploited.
   U.S. District Judge Norma Johnson was urged Monday by the World
Wildlife Fund to issue a preliminary injunction shutting down the
exhibition at the Toledo Zoo.
   Since May 24, the zoo has been exhibiting two pandas on loan
from China after receiving a permit from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service.
   Bruce Berman, an attorney for the wildlife fund, argued the
federal agency should not have issued the permit because it failed
to find that the importation of the pandas was not primarily for
commercial purposes and that it would promote survival of the
species.
   James Kilbourne, an attorney for the wildlife service, said the
agency determined that import of the pandas would not be
detrimental to their survival and that while the exhibit would have
some commercial trappings, it was not primarily for commercial
purposes.
   Ellen Efros, an attorney for the zoo, said the separate
admission fee for the panda exhibit was established only for
financial accountability purposes.
   Ms. Efros said closing the exhibit would rob the public of a
chance to view an endangered species and learn something about
China. And she said it could have a potentially harmful effect on
U.S.-Chinese relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
