<DOCNO> AP880614-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HijackAnniversary     06-14 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack Anniversary,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Three Years, Vivid Memories Remain For TWA Flight's
Passengers, Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago today, two young men who could
have passed for well-dressed college students hijacked TWA flight
847 shortly after it took off from Athens. Their act launched a
dramatic episode that lasted for 17 days.
   By the time it was over, 39 men had been held hostage in Beirut
for two weeks, a young Navy diver was dead and the plane had logged
more than 8,500 miles between Greece, Lebanon and Algeria.
   For the 153 passengers and crew _ 104 of the American _ the
ordeal is something they will never forget, though many have tried.
   ``It wasn't a fun deal to go through,'' said Robert Peel, 36, of
Hutchinson, Kan. ``We really don't like to talk about it because
every time you do, it brings it up again.''
   John Mazurowski, 68, of Lancaster, N.Y., said the hijacking ``is
an issue we would like to forget.'' Mazurowski's daughter, Melissa,
a recent graduate of Barnard College, still has back trouble as a
result of the 30 hours they spent on the plane, her father said.
   William Cocoris, a restaurant owner from Boston, Mass., said he
no longer flies on American carriers when he visits his family in
Greece. ``I think we are targeted,'' he said.
   Memories have been evoked recently by a television film about
the flight, a book by the pilot and news reports about the upcoming
trial in Germany of one of the hijackers.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi is scheduled to be tried in Frankfurt July 5
on charges of air piracy and murder in the death of Robert D.
Stethem of Waldorf, Md.. The young Navy man was beaten and shot
during the hijacking.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite thought to have ties to the radical
group, Hezbollah, was arrested in January 1987 as he went through
customs with explosives in his luggage. The United States tried
unsuccessfully to extradite him.
   Court spokesman Falk Thomas said two of Stethem's relatives and
six former hostages will take part in the prosecution. Stethem's
parents could not be reached for comment.
   Another suspect, Hassan Izz-Al-Din, was identified by passengers
as one of the people who hijacked a Kuwaiti Airways plane earlier
this year, according to a State Department official who asked that
he not be named. The department does not have official
confirmation, he said.
   On May 2, NBC-TV aired a two-hour docudrama about the episode
entitled, ``The Taking of Flight 847: The Uli Derickson Story.''
Actress Lindsay Wagner played Derickson, the purser on the flight
who had close contact with the hijackers because she translated
their demands from German into English during the flight.
   Mazurowski said the movie was ``quite factual'' though it tended
to glamorize parts of the ordeal.
   Helen Sheahan, a TWA flight attendant who has a vivid
recollection of the events, said she was disappointed with what she
called distortions in the movie. For instance, she said none of the
passengers talked during the flight, but the film shows Stethem
discussing with a friend what to do.
   ``The truth would have been just as compelling,'' she said.
   Capt. John L. Testrake of Richmond, Mo., wrote a book last year
about the hijacking which he dedicated to Stethem.
   ``He looked at hate and death squarely and fearlessly, and no
cry was heard to come from him,'' Testrake wrote in ``Triumph Over
Terror on Flight 847,'' published by Fleming H. Revell Co.
   ``I cannot describe how I felt when Stethem was killed,'' he
said. ``There was just a heavy, heavy sadness that washed over me.''
   In the book, which deals heavily with Testrake's religious
faith, the retired TWA pilot said he knew little about the politics
of the Middle East until the hijacking.
   ``I was awakened from this typically American isolation by the
black bore of an automatic pistol in my face and by the angry eyes
behind it,'' he said. ``I have discovered that our country is
resented in this region...''
   TWA spokesman Bob Blattner in St. Louis, Mo., said he had no
information about any settlements offered to passengers on flight
847. One former hostage said in 1985 the company offered $35,000 to
passengers held until the end of the 17-day crisis, and $15,000 to
those released earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PCBs     06-14 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PCBs,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Measure On Middlemen's Handling Of Toxic PCBs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is moving to close a loophole in the
control of PCBs, the highly toxic polychlorinated biphenyls that
were banned in 1976.
   A bill passed by the House by voice vote Monday takes direct aim
at PCB brokers, the middlemen who collect the chemicals from their
use sites and arrange for their destruction.
   While the use and destruction of PCBs are heavily regulated,
there has been no governmental control over them between the time
brokers pick them up and when they deliver them to a destruction
facility, such as an incinerator.
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the bill that moved to the
Senate responds to reports that some brokers have improperly
handled PCBs and in some instances have gone bankrupt, leaving
power companies and communities to clean up storage sites.
   ``Literally, anyone with a truck can now get into the PCB
disposal business,'' said Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., a principal
sponsor of the bill. ``It's time to put an end to the sham these
PCB operators have put on us. It's time to put them out of
business.''
   PCBs are most frequently found as an insulation fluid in heavy
duty electrical equipment. Congress banned their manufacture in
1976, but an estimated 750 million pounds are still in use or in
storage.
   Luken said that as the electrical gear wears out over the next
few years, the nation will be faced with the task of safely
disposing of a growing amount of the chemicals.
   The bill would require PCB brokers to be registered, keep
records and demonstrate financial responsibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
