<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ReporterArrested     06-14 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reporter Arrested,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporter Accused of Taking Papers From Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter investigating allegations of
abuse at a jail was charged Monday with illegally taking papers
from prisoners.
   Karen E. Olson of the Tallahassee Democrat took papers from one
of four prisoners she interviewed Saturday and refused to hand them
over to jail officials, Leon County sheriff's officials charged.
   Removing contraband from a correctional facility is a
third-degree felony that carries a maximum penalty of five years in
prison, said sheriff's Maj. Larry Campbell.
   The newspaper said it had employed Ms. Olson, 34, as a reporter
since 1982, and that she has been investigating prisoners at the
jail since April.
   ``The Democrat fully supports her and has supported her with
legal counsel. We believe the judicial process will vindicate
her,'' Managing Editor Bill Fuller said Monday night in a statement.
   Ms. Olson surrendered at the sheriff's office Monday afternoon
and was charged, booked and released on her own recognizance.
   Gary Williams, one of two lawyers representing Ms. Olson, said
Monday that there are ``significant constitutional problems with
the statute'' under which the reporter was charged, raising
``significant First Amendment issues.''
   Williams said he tried to discuss those issues with Sheriff
Eddie Boone on Monday but Boone declined to do so.
   ``We're obviously going to have to discuss them in court now,
and that's where I feel Karen Olson will be fully vindicated,''
Williams said.
</TEXT>
