<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Budget     06-14 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Budget,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Budget Crunch Prompts Talk Of New Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just when the presidential campaign of Michael
Dukakis is trying to dampen any talk about Democrats raising taxes,
the Massachusetts governor is being forced to consider the
possibility at home.
   Dukakis met Monday with senior budget advisers and legislative
leaders to talk about his state's budget crunch, and one
participant in the meeting indicated the possibility of new taxes
was discussed.
   Senate President William Bulger and House Speaker George
Keverian both said spending and tax issues were discussed, but no
conclusions were drawn.
   Asked if the possibility of new taxes was talked about, Bulger
said, ``Every kind of idea is being discussed.''
   Dukakis, speaking to reporters briefly on his way out of the
Statehouse, also declined to provide any specifics.
   ``It will evolve, it will develop. We are talking about a number
of things,'' the governor said.
   Dukakis was asked about the growing belief by some that higher
taxes are inevitable.
   ``I don't know if that's true at this point. We've got lots of
things we are looking at and we are making good progress. And we
will have a good, solid balanced budget,'' he said.
   The governor also declined to say whether he has asked the
legislative leaders to support any new or higher taxes.
   With less than three weeks remaining in the fiscal year, the
Dukakis administration is facing a projected deficit of more than
$400 million. And budget experts in the administration and in the
legislature say the next fiscal year could hold more problems.
   The House has passed an $11.8 billion spending plan for next
year, and that budget is pending in the Senate. The new budget is
due on July 1.
   The legislative leaders said Monday's discussions with the
governor did not focus on any particular deadline, although they
acknowledged that the problem is urgent and more meetings are
planned this week.
   ``We're running against the clock, but I'm sure we will meet our
timetables,'' Keverian said. He, too, declined to reveal details of
what was discussed in the meeting.
   In recent weeks, Dukakis has spoken repeatedly with top
lawmakers, seeking to reach a broad agreement balancing the budget
for both this year and next, in time to meet the July 1 deadline.
   Finance Secretary Frank Keefe said there was no consensus yet on
where to cut spending or on which new taxes or fees might be needed.
   Keefe said he was urging Dukakis to sign a bill projected to
raise $40 million by imposing a sales tax on cigarettes, which
arrived on the governor's desk Monday. But he said he could not
predict what Dukakis will do.
   In the course of his presidential campaign, Dukakis has leaned
heavily on his reputation as a competent manager who has kept his
state's budget balanced.
   The Dukakis campaign has also resisted calls from Jesse Jackson
to raise taxes on the wealthy, a position Jackson would like to see
included in the Democratic platform.
   Dukakis has said tax hikes should be a last resort, and that a
crackdown on tax cheats should be a first step.
</TEXT>
