<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CriticizedNominee     06-14 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Criticized Nominee,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Nominee Hit for Placing Liens on Dying AIDS Victim's
Property</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Reagan administration judicial nominee is
under fire for placing liens on the property of a dying AIDS victim
and for his membership in a private club with a record of
discrimination.
   Vaughn R. Walker, nominee for a U.S. district judgeship in
northern California, was accused by another lawyer during a hearing
Monday of keeping property liens ``hanging over a dying man.''
   Walker also was questioned sharply by Sen. Patrick J. Leahy on
his continued membership in San Francisco's Olympic Club.
   Walker, a member of a large San Francisco law firm, said he
would resign unless more blacks were recruited and women members
were given voting rights.
   Leahy, D-Vt., who presided at the Judiciary Committee's
confirmation hearing, reminded the San Francisco lawyer that
Supreme Court Justice Anthony M. Kennedy quit the same club without
waiting for changes.
   But the most emotional issue at the hearing was Walker's
representation of the U.S. Olympic Committee in its successful suit
to stop an organizer for San Francisco's gay community from calling
an athletic competition the ``Gay Olympics.''
   As part of the suit, Walker placed liens on the property of the
late Tom Waddell, a 1968 Olympian in the decathlon who spent the
last years of his life fighting the USOC's lawsuit before dying of
AIDS.
   Attorney Mary Dunlap, who represented Waddell, said Walker
placed the liens on Waddell's property and refused to lift them
even when he knew Waddell was dying.
   Walker insisted there was ``nothing malicious'' in placing the
liens against Waddell's home and other property, an action that
followed a federal district judge's order that Waddell and a gay
organization pay the USOC's $96,000 in attorney's fees.
   Walker told the committee that a later federal appeals court
ruling during the case automatically vacated the liens.
   But Ms. Dunlap told the committee that she was unable to vacate
the liens without Walker's release, which he refused to give.
Walker eventually gave his agreement, but the liens were not
removed until six days after Waddell's death in July 1987.
   Ms. Dunlap said Walker left the liens ``hanging over a dying man
at the time he needed to know his daughter would inherit his
estate.''
   Discussing his club membership, Walker said he has been working
from within to get the Olympic Club to change its policies. He said
it now has an accelerated program to recruit minorities, and
discussions are under way to permit the 800 women members to vote _
a privilege they do not have now.
   The nominee first told senators that he would resign if the
committee asked him to do so. Told by Leahy that there were no
plans for such a request, Walker said that if the current efforts
stall and a ``hopeless situation'' results, ``then I would resign
regardless of whether the committee thought I should resign or
not.''
   But he added, ``I think the club is making progress.''
   Walker has drawn opposition from San Francisco's gay community
and the city's Board of Supervisors, which voted unanimously
against the nomination. His main supporter, Republican Sen. Pete
Wilson of California, urged the committee not to turn against
Walker because of the U.S. Olympic Committee case.
   ``What principle of American jurisprudence is more fundamental
than that due process of the law requires that however unpopular a
client, that client and that client's cause of action are entitled
to be represented by competent counsel?'' Wilson asked.
   Walker used similar language in defending himself, telling Leahy
``I was perfectly aware of how unpopular the position was.'' But he
added that the committee should be looking for judicial candidates
``willing to take stands'' that are legally correct ``even though
they may be unpopular.''
   Walker said the Olympic committee held firm on the lien, adding
it did so in the hope that the gay organization working with
Waddell _ San Francisco Arts and Athletics _ would raise the money
for the attorney fees.
   Leahy also used the hearing to respond to an accusation last
month by the committee's ranking Republican, Strom Thurmond of
South Carolina, that majority Democrats were intentionally delaying
13 current and former Reagan judicial nominees.
   Leahy, who is in charge of judicial confirmation hearings, said
the Justice Department caused some delays through tardiness in
responding to committee information requests on nominees.
   He said other delays resulted because Democrats want to
investigate nominees thoroughly ``before they are given a lifetime
charter to sit in judgment on the rights and liberties of the
American people, not afterwards.''
</TEXT>
