<DOCNO> AP880614-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Disarmament     06-14 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Disarmament,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Avoids Soviet Disarmament Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz told
the United Nations it will have no role in superpower nuclear
weapons reductions and he ignored the Soviet Union's invitation to
ban nuclear tests.
   Shultz, addressing a special U.N. session on disarmament Monday,
instead stressed the momentum for arms control achieved during the
Reagan administration.
   ``We have made major progress toward a treaty to cut U.S. and
Soviet strategic nuclear arsenals (long-range missiles) by 50
percent,'' he said. ``I do not know whether we will be able to
conclude such a treaty this year, but we will make our best effort.
   ``It is the United States' top arms control priority,'' he added.
   Shultz's speech underlined past accomplishments, including the
newly ratified U.S.-Soviet treaty to destroy intermediate-range
nuclear missiles and the verification procedures that go with it.
   Last week, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze used a
speech to the conference to call on the United States to take on
future disarmament challenges.
   He proposed abolishing all nuclear weapons by the year 2000, an
immediate mutual ban on nuclear tests and an immediate cut of
500,000 troops each from the Warsaw Pact and NATO.
   Shultz replied that the United States will ``concentrate on
results which will eliminate the disparities (in conventional arms
in Europe) that threaten stability, not schemes for `equal
reductions' which will have no such effect.''
   NATO claims the Soviets have an advantage in conventional arms
in Europe.
   In the speech, Shultz also ignored the Soviet call for a mutual
test ban.
   The United States similarly failed to join a 1{-year unilaterial
Soviet moratorium on testing that began in August 1985.
   Shultz also rejected the Soviet call for a U.N. arms reduction
verification agency to coordinate and monitor disarmament pacts.
   ``Some tasks, such as work to reduce nuclear arsenals, must be
strictly bilateral, in negotiation, verification, and
implementation.''
   ``But others,'' Shultz said, ``above all, the negotiations to
ban chemical weapons, and the need to control nuclear proliferation
_ are global problems.''
   Shultz offered no specific proposals on those problems.
   ``Ballistic missile proliferation is a new and urgent
challenge,'' particularly in the Middle East, said Shultz. His
advice to Iran and Iraq was to exercise ``mutual restraint'' and
not buy or launch such missiles.
   Shultz urged nations attending the Conference on Disarmament to
``apply themselves'' to a global ban on chemical weapons, which are
easily made in fertilizer and pesticide factories, but did not
suggest any solutions.
   The potential spread of nuclear weapons to other countries,
especially in South Asia, is a central topic in the U.N.'s session
on disarmament and Shultz urged rivals Pakistan and India to work
on the problem.
   Earlier in the day, Pakistan offered to sign the Nuclear
Non-proliferation Treaty if India does so simultaneously.
   Later this week, delegates to the 159-member General Assembly
will begin drafting resolutions on chemical, nuclear, conventional
and space-based weapons for this third special session on
disarmament in 10 years.
   The session, scheduled to end June 25, has been sharply divided.
Diplomatic observers said it will be difficult to draft a final
document.
   The United States and Western allies have called for pragmatic
steps in arms control, respect for nuclear deterrence, a limited
role for the United Nations and recognition that bilateral arms
talks must supersede multilateral efforts.
   Western diplomats also have said that conventional disarmament
is as important as nuclear disarmament, and urged poor developing
nations that clamor for nuclear disarmament to cut their own armies
and avoid sweeping and utopian disarmament proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MechamTrial     06-14 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Trial,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury To Begin Deliberating In Mecham Criminal Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Closing arguments scheduled to begin at 12:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham has lost a
mistrial bid on the eve of closing arguments in his trial on
charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Attorneys were to give closing arguments this morning, and the
jury was expected to begin deliberations in the afternoon.
   Mecham and his brother, Willard, are charged in the Maricopa
County Superior Court trial with concealing the $350,000 loan in
financial reports required by the state.
   In a motion for mistrial, defense attorney Michael Scott
contended that Judge Michael Ryan may have prejudiced the case by
expressing surprise when the prosecution and defense said Friday
they had no more witnesses.
   The defense rested its case without calling either Evan or
Willard Mecham to the stand. After the prosecution said it had no
rebuttal witnesses, Ryan told the jurors the sudden close of
testimony had taken him by surprise.
   Scott argued Monday that the judge's statement could be
interpreted by the jury as implying that the defense should have
presented more testimony or put the defendants on the stand.
   But Ryan said he made the comment in the context of the trial
schedule. In addition, he said he did not see how the defense could
be harmed since he made the remark afterthe prosecution said it had
no rebuttal witnesses.
   Ryan also denied a defense request Monday that he interview each
juror privately to find out if any had seen any publicity about the
case.
   Mecham was charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in
prison if convicted. Willard Mecham, who was his younger brother's
1986 campaign treasurer, faced three similar counts and up to 9{
years in prison if convicted.
   The defense has contended the $350,000 loan from developer Barry
Wolfson was properly reported as part of a $465,000 lump sum listed
as a contribution from Mecham, and that the failure to itemize the
loan was an innocent mistake.
   Former top Mecham aide Edith Richardson said the loan was common
knowledge among the former Republican governor's inner circle. But
two other former top aides, Donna Carlson and Mac Matheson, said
they did not know about it.
   The prosecution has said that Mecham badly needed the loan to
keep his gubernatorial campaign afloat but wanted to keep it secret
to avoid harming the candidate's theme of being ``beholden to no
one.''
   In addition, prosecutors said it didn't matter whether Mecham's
closest aides knew about the loan because it was not reported to
the public.
   Mecham took office in January 1987 and was removed April 4 when
the state Senate convicted him of two unrelated charges. He also
was impeached in connection with the loan, but the Senate decided
not to hear that charge for fear of prejudicing his criminal trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Children'sHome 2ndLd-Writethru a0813 06-14 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0813,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Asks Grand Jury to Look Into Minister's Actions</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HAT1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with police removing children
from church. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``On Friday...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State troopers removed dozens of children
from a church whose fundamentalist preacher was arrested twice
Monday after harboring youngsters in defiance of a court order.
   About 60 state troopers, local police and sheriff's deputies
moved into Bethel Baptist Church after a 4-hour standoff. At least
seven people, including the assistant pastor of the church, were
arrested.
   After interviews, 11 children were handed over to state welfare
officials. It was unclear if they had been residents of the Rev.
Herman Fountain's 28-acre Bethel Home for Children, where officials
charge youngsters have been abused through corporal punishment.
   Witnesses said at least three dozen children were taken from the
church. Authorities said they took all the youngsters away after
church officials refused to point out three who Fountain
acknowledged in court had returned to the home after it was
temporarily closed by a judge.
   As the children were being taken into the local courthouse,
Fountain got into a shoving match with a lawman and was re-arrested.
   He was arrested earlier along with two staff members and a
17-year-old when a fight broke out at the home, leading Chancery
Judge Robert Oswald to call for a grand jury to consider indicting
Fountain.
   Fountain had refused to answer the judge's questions about
runaways from the home in a hearing earlier Monday. The judge
issued 11 subpoenas to staff members of the home, apparently
leading somehow to the fight.
   On Friday, the judge had given state welfare officials temporary
custody of youngsters at the home, on the campus of the independent
Bethel Baptist Church near Lucedale. The state Department of Public
Welfare removed some 60 children, but many others fled.
   Oswald ruled that children, ages 10 to 17, had been subjected
``to physical abuse, medical neglect and detention amounting to
imprisonment.''
   ``This court's message is simple _ abuse and neglect of children
is not acceptable at any time or any place by any person,'' Oswald
said.
   Oswald said that Fountain was wrong to think that since his
school is part of his church he isn't subject to civil authorities.
   The judge said he would first decide the cases of 12 children
whose parents retained a lawyer and refused to sign an agreement
not to send their youngsters back to the home.
   During a morning break, Fountain said he believed his home
housed ``about 120 children.''
   Twenty-two of 64 children taken into custody by state workers
were released over the weekend to their parents or guardians, state
Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain said Monday outside the court.
   Brittain said some of the 42 had been brought to court Monday
but they never testified.
   Asked about the children unaccounted for, Fountain said:
   ``I don't know anything about them. If I had enough money to
hire a private investigator to find them, I would do that. I love
those kids.''
   Fountain said he feared for the safety of the missing youngsters
because most had a troubled history; he was worried, he said, some
might return to using drugs.
   About 50 people attended the court session, some wearing
pro-Fountain buttons that read ``Eternal Life Is a Free Gift.''
   After several outbursts in the court that included moans, crying
and comments that the judge was prejudicial, Oswald said: ``There
is a place for demonstrations, but it is not the courtroom. There
may be a place for outcries, but it is not the courtroom.''
   Outside court, several parents said they wanted their children
back in the home rather than in the state's custody.
   Pat Green of Boca Raton, Fla., who said she had a 16-year-old
son at Bethel, said she and her husband refused to pick him up
because they did not want to sign the agreement that would bar him
from return to Bethel.
   ``We chose to have our children in a religious facility that
works,'' she said. ``And the state has put their hands in it ...
the state is taking away our rights.
   ``Brother Fountain through Bethel saved our child's life. When a
child is on drugs, you need the help of religion to get off drugs.''
</TEXT>
