<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     06-14 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Hits Again At The Purse In New Effort To End Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a new effort to end the Palestinian
anti-occupation uprising, Israel plans to force Gaza Strip parents
to post cash bonds to free children detained in clashes with
Israeli troops.
   Police, meanwhile, announced that they would step up aerial
patrols to spot arsonists. A tenth Arab arson suspect was seized
Monday night as he fled a burning wooded area near Jerusalem,
Israeli radio reported.
   A military source said that to curb the daily violence in the
occupied Gaza Strip, authorities would make parents of detained
children deposit cash bonds rather than promissory notes to keep
their youngsters off the streets.
   The death count continued to mount in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, where Palestinians have for six months been revolting
against the 21-year Israeli occupation.
   Israeli soldiers fatally shot 43-year-old Mahmoud Hussein in the
West Bank village of Abwein near Ramallah on Monday when he did not
heed an order to halt, said Dr. Yasser Obeid, director of the
Ramallah hospital.
   The victim's family said Hussein was hard of hearing and
probably did not hear the order.
   A military spokesman said the army was checking into the death,
which brought the total number of Palestinian fatalities in the
uprising to 207. Two Israelis have been slain.
   The military source who reported the cash-bond plan said Gaza
City parents would have to pay 5,000 shekels, about $3,100, to
obtain the release of their children detained for the first time.
The money would be confiscated as a fine if the children were
detained a second time, he said.
   Previously, families could sign a document guaranteeing to pay
the amount if the suspects were arrested again after being released.
   ``It has to be seen in the context of a whole series of actions
we have taken to reduce violence,'' said the source, who was not
idenfitied in line with army regulations.
   An Arab resident of Gaza said new fines amounting to the
equivalent of $9,500 against homeowners whose houses were painted
with Palestine Liberation Organization slogans have virtually
eliminated such graffiti.
   ``When people see writing on the wall they take it off and do a
whitewash _ they're frightened and don't want to put themselves in
trouble,'' said the resident, who asked not to be named in fear of
reprisal.
   Officials reported more brush and forest fires Monday night in
central Israel, and they blamed Palestinian arsonists.
   Fires in recent weeks have destroyed at least 25,000 acres of
grazing areas, forests and nature reserves, according to
naturalists.
   Police reported the arrest Monday night of a 26-year-old Arab
suspected of committing arson in the Ben-Shemen park along the Tel
Aviv-Jerusalem highway.
   They said a second forest fire was set near the Orthodox Kefar
Habad Hassidic settlement, three miles from Tel Aviv, and residents
reported seeing two people fleeing the scene, according to Israel
radio.
   In earlier arrests over the weekend, police seized six Arabs for
allegedly setting fires in the Jerusalem area and three others in
connection with forest fires in the northern Galilee region.
   Foreign Minster Shimon Peres told Israelis Monday not to ``get
hysterical'' about the fires.
   He said Arab militants are ``always looking for new means and
new places. We must develop counter measures ... for this very
injurious assault.''
</TEXT>
