<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     06-14 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans Freed ANC Leader From Meeting With More Than 10 At
A Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned
African National Congress leader Govan Mbeki from being in the
company of more than 10 people at a time, his attorney said.
   Mbeki, 77, freed from a life prison term last year, is not
allowed to attend rallies or meetings, his attorney, Priscilla
Jana, said Monday.
   The congress is the main guerrilla group fighting the South
African government, whose apartheid system denies the country's 26
million blacks a voice in national affairs. The 5 million whites
control the economy and maintain separate schools, districts and
health services.
   Mbeki already had been prohibited from addressing meetings,
giving interviews or leaving the area near the city of Port
Elizabeth, where he lives. The new order limiting the number of
people he can be with is a common measure used by the government to
punish anti-apartheid activists.
   Ms. Jana said another of her clients, United Democratic Front
co-president Albertina Sisulu, was served with similar new orders.
   Mrs. Sisulu, wife of imprisoned ANC official Walter Sisulu, was
one of 18 black activists whose movements and speech had already
been restricted in February.
   The front, a coalition of anti-apartheid groups, was banned in
February from all activity along with 17 other anti-apartheid
organizations.
   Mrs. Jana said Mbeki filed a court challenge to the first
restrictions placed on him but will have to refile the appeal under
the new regulations.
   Mbeki was freed last August after serving 23 years for a 1964
conviction on charges of sabotage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
