<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Bolsheviks     06-14 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Bolsheviks,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Exonerates Purged Bolsheviks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Bolshevik leaders who were purged, convicted
and died during Stalin's terror of the 1930s have been exonerated
in the Kremlin's latest revision of Soviet history.
   The Soviet Supreme Court's ruling is a signal that open debate
will be allowed on reform proposals at a special Communist Party
conference this month.
   The court reversed the convictions of Lev Kamenev, Gregory
Zinoviev and Karl Radek and the lesser-known Gregory Pyatikov, the
government newspaper Izvestia reported Monday. The move restores
``to these tragic figures their honor and their names,'' the paper
said.
   The ruling does not mean complete rehabilitation unless their
Communist Party membership is restored.
   The decision had been expected since February, when the court
reversed the death sentence of Nikolai I. Bukharin, another old
Bolshevik killed in the purges. Kamenev and Zinoviev were as
important as Bukharin.
   Izvestia said the court ``did not evaluate whether they were
right or wrong in the old debates. But it said clearly: They are
innocent before the law, state, and people.''
   The article directed extraordinarily harsh criticism at Josef
Stalin, who killed many former comrades during the terror he used
to shape the Soviet economy and society while he ruled the Soviet
Union from 1927 to 1953.
   Since assuming power March 15, 1985, Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
been dismantling much of the Stalinist governing structure.
Monday's court decision was another step in that process.
   At the party conference, scheduled to start June 28, delegates
will debate proposals to widen the scope of Gorbachev's
``perestroika,'' a reform program that some midlevel party and
government officials are resisting.
   Clearing Bukharin was essential because he broke with Stalin's
policy of rapid industrialization in the 1930s and advocated
policies similar to those Gorbachev is pursuing.
   Zinoviev and Kamenev are not identified as closely as Bukharin
with specific policies, but Izvestia made clear that exonerating
them was intended to foster debate.
   ``We are learning democracy, mastering the rules of political
discussions, also in a time of hard struggle,'' it said in a long
article under the headline ``A Return to Truth.''
   Zinoviev and Kamenev spent years in exile with Vladimir I.
Lenin, the Bolshevik leader, and returned to Russia with him in
February 1917. They opposed Lenin's decision in October of that
year to begin the Bolshevik Revolution, but were forgiven and named
to party posts.
   When Lenin died in 1924, Zinoviev and Kamenev sided with Stalin
against Leon Trotsky, who was driven into exile and murdered in
Mexico City in 1940. Trotsky has not been rehabilitated, but
several recent articles have dealt with his role in the revolution.
   After Trotsky was exiled, Stalin turned on his former allies.
Zinoviev and Kamenev were convicted of treason and executed after a
show trial in 1936.
   Radek, born in Poland, took part in the 1917 revolution but was
accused of siding with Trotsky and expelled from the party in 1927.
   He was rehabilitated and edited Izvestia in the 1930s, but was
tried again in 1937 and sent to a labor camp, where he is believed
to have died in about 1940.
   Pyatikov led the left wing of the Ukrainian Communist Party in
1917 and later held government posts. He was sentenced along with
Radek and executed.
   ``Our predecessors, the people of the 20s, could not control the
situation ... and were burned up in the flames of repression,''
Izvestia's legal correspondent, Yuri Feofanov, wrote in a detailed
account of the purges.
   ``They preached intolerance toward the opinions of their
opponents and gave birth to physical and moral terror,'' he wrote.
   ``In a word, discussion has been cut off for a long time about
the paths toward the building of socialism. It has been restored
now, more than a half century later, and from the same place; about
the paths of developing revolution, about the role of the party and
about the place of `the Vozhd.'''
   Stalin was known as the ``Vozhd'' _ supreme leader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
