<DOCNO> AP880614-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Election     06-14 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Election,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Seek Way to Form Workable Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Socialist President Francois
Mitterrand and all of France wrestled with a political identity
crisis after legislative elections raised more questions than they
answered.
   Mitterrand called the elections hoping for a Socialist majority
in the 577-seat National Assembly. Polls initially predicted he
would succeed.
   But he didn't, although the opposing center-right alliance lost
the majority it won in 1986. France was bereft of a governing
majority for the first time in 30 years.
   ``The country is exhausted from having voted too much,'' the
influential Le Monde newspaper declared Monday. ``It has had enough
of politicians' games. It is up to the president, everybody says it
and everybody is right, to act.''
   Yet the president likely will find action difficult.
   Sunday's election was a defeat for Mitterrand, who won his
second seven-year term as president May 8 with 54 percent of the
vote.
   Mitterrand has in recent times largely abandoned Socialist
principles and talked of an opening to the center. On Sunday, many
French voters balked at his party's candidates.
   Mitterrand was making no announcements about his strategy after
Sunday's elections. But it was clear he could end up with a bruised
political ego in courting balky centrists or Communists.
   ``There is only one conclusion to draw from these failures,''
said Le Monde: ``All arrogance henceforth is forbidden to those who
govern us or hope to do so. Nobody can pretend to incarnate the
will of the people.''
   The Socialists tried to act like victors.
   Lionel Jospin, the Socialist education minister, said: ``One
thing is sure: the right cannot govern.'' All the rightist votes
together would not make a majority, which Jospin said ``can only be
built around the Socialist Party,'' the largest single group in the
National Assembly.
   But Socialists will need help from either the reluctant far left
or center.
   The most logical approach for Mitterrand and his premier, Michel
Rocard, would be a coalition with the Communists, whose 27 seats
would make a total of 304 for the left.
   Second on the list of possibilities is an attempt to entice at
least 13 centrist deputies from the rightist camp.
   Or Rocard could attempt a minority government at least until
autumn, trying to find a majority for each issue.
   Socialist and Communist leaders have made deals and alliances in
the past, but this time Communist Party chief Georges Marchais is
saying no. Mitterrand cannot make deals with the center-right and
the Communists at the same time, Marchais has declared, and his
party will judge the government on an issue-by-issue basis.
   Jean-Claude Gaudin, leader of the Union for French Democracy in
the outgoing assembly, said of the second possibility: ``If they
persist today in wanting to detach a few centrist personalities in
order to turn them into Socialists, I trust my elected centrist
friends to reject this proposition, which would be unworthy of
them.''
   Other centrists are more open to the idea of helping the
Socialists.
   Bernard Stasi, another centrist, said: ``If a very large union
is going to be constituted, which seems desirable to me, the center
must be the pivot.''
   Except for two seats from French Polynesia to be decided June
26, final results gave the Socialists 276 seats and Communists 27.
The center-right Union for French Democracy had 129, the
conservative Rally for the Republic 126 and minor rightists 16 for
a total of 271.
   A majority requires 289.
   The Communist Party dropped eight seats. The far-right National
Front got one seat instead of the previous 35, and it did not go to
party leader Jean-Marie Le Pen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
