<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UnmistakablyCanadian     06-14 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unmistakably Canadian,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadians Advised To Show The Flag After Americans Threatened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian residents were advised by their embassy
to wear pins or flags with their nation's emblem during last week's
scare over a potential terrorist attack against U.S. citizens.
   The embassy, in notices sent out Friday to the approximately 150
Canadians in the Chinese capital, also recommended that hotels and
other places frequented by North Americans be avoided, Embassy
First Secretary E.C. Wilson said.
   The notice said Canadians should try to identify themselves
through flags or pins because it is difficult for terrorists to
distinguish between Americans and Canadians, Wilson said.
   It also provided tips on security, ``but the basic message was
that this is not a serious threat to Canadians.''
   The U.S. Embassy issued a warning Thursday to the more than
1,500 Americans in Beijing, saying the Chinese government had
information that unidentified third-country terrorists might attack
Americans.
   The warning, unprecedented in the Chinese capital, was canceled
Sunday after the Chinese government gave assurances the danger was
over.
   The Chinese did not provide details of the terrorist threat _ or
explain why the danger had passed _ but said there was Middle East
involvement.
</TEXT>
