<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ElectionsRdp     06-14 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elections Rdp,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Dakotans To Vote On Lottery; Virginians Pick A Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   North Dakotans today got the second chance in two years to vote
on a lottery, while voters in Virginia's 5th District will fill the
seat vacated when Rep. Dan Daniels, a conservative Democrat, died
during his 10th term.
   In Maine, Linda Bean-Jones, an heiress to the L.L. Bean outdoor
wear fortune, faced Edward S. O'Meara ina 1st District Republican
primary for Congress. The winner will face Democratic Rep. Joseph
Brennan, a former two-term governor now in his first term in the
U.S. House.
   South Carolina also has congressional primaries today. In the
6th District, Democratic Rep. Robin Tallon faces a challenge from
Luther Lighty.
   The North Dakota lottery is opposed by former Gov. Arthur Link,
who says it constitutes a regressive tax on poorer citizens, and by
charities that are allowed to run casino gambling and fear the
competition.
   The measure failed two years ago, but backers predicte success
this time, helped by increased public awareness of flourishing
lotteries in neighboring South Dakota and Montana.
   Twenty-six states and the District of Columbia operate
lotteries. Wisconsin and Virginia are scheduled to start them this
summer. Voters in neighboring Minnesota are to decide in November
whether to allow one. North Dakota is the only state that has voted
down a state-run lottery.
   In Danville, Va., Vice President George Bush appeared at a rally
and barbecue Sunday on behalf of Republican Linda Arey, who faces
Democrat L.F. Payne Jr. in the special congressional election.
   Mrs. Arey, a former Reagan administration official in the
Education, Justice and Transportation departments, said she hoped
the visit would show voters she has the connections to get things
done in Washington.
   Payne developed Virginia's Wintergreen resort and ski area.
   The Maine primary heated up last week when Bean-Jones was quoted
in the Kennebec Journal in Augusta as calling the minimum wage an
``oppressive'' law that keeps people from working and saying she
would vote to abolish the $3.35 standard. O'Meara labeled her
position ``incredible'' and ``an affront'' to workers who rely on
the minimum to make ends meet.
   Bean-Jones later issued a statement saying she thought she had
been asked about a pending bill to increase the minimum wage, but
her statement did not disclaim her comments in the story.
   The latest campaign spending reports show that Bean-Jones had
raised nearly $377,000 _ nearly $280,000 in self-secured loans _
through May 25. O'Meara's total was $52,000.
</TEXT>
