<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Turkey     06-14 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Turkey,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ozal and Papandreou Disagree Over Divided Cyprus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The premiers of Greece and Turkey
failed to agree over how to end their 14-year division of Cyprus
despite improved relations between the two NATO members.
   ``In the general climate of detente ... it would be strange if
Cyprus remained an example of an unsettled and dangerous
irregularity,'' Premier Andreas Papandreou said at a dinner Monday
at a tightly guarded seaside hotel outside Athens.
   Visiting Premier Turgut Ozal indicated he will not give in to
Greek pressure for troop withdrawals from northern Cyprus and said
there ``is no room for petty designs, one-sided gains and
shortsighted tactics.''
   In central Athens, about 2,000 Greek Cypriot, Armenian and
Kurdish demonstrators shouted, ``Fire for the Turkish dogs!'' and
burned Turkish flags and an effigy of Ozal outside the Turkish
Embassy.
   The fires capped a day of anti-Ozal protests that began when 60
Greek Cypriot women, some relatives of people missing since the
1974 Turkish invasion of Cyprus, blocked the two gateways to the
Acropolis temples.
   More protests were set for today, the second day of Ozal's
three-day visit, when the Turkish premier planned to lay a wreath
at the Tomb of the Unknown Warrior outside Parliament.
   Papandreou, speaking at the poolside dinner, also said Greece
could not ignore the Cyprus problem for ``legal, moral and national
reasons.''
   The Socialist premier reiterated an earlier proposal for the
demilitarization of the eastern Mediterranean island and setting up
a mixed Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot police force.
   Last week, U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar also
called for Turkey to make a gesture by reducing its estimated
29,000-strong force in the island's northern sector.
   Cyprus has been divided into separate Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot sectors since 1974, when the military junta then in power
in Athens backed a coup aimed at uniting the island with Greece.
   The action triggered a Turkish invasion, and the United Nations
has since policed the Green Line that divides the island.
   A total of 1,619 Greeks and Greek Cypriots still are missing
since the invasion, and Turkey has not accounted for their fate.
   Ozal is the first Turkish premier to visit Greece in 36 years.
In 1952, Premier Adnan Menderes received a warm welcome in Athens
at a time of Greek-Turkish detente.
   The atmosphere is sharply different this time, with 5,000 Greek
police detailed to protect the Turkish premier. He will be confined
mostly to one wing of the Vouliagmeni hotel complex.
   Papandreou also is staying in the state-owned hotel on a
peninsula jutting into the Saronic Gulf, where he spends much of
his time in the summer.
   During the meetings, two Greek Navy patrol boats cruise in the
gulf and frogmen in rubber boats ride close to the shore.
   The only sign that the Turkish premier is visiting is a
red-and-white Turkish flag flying opposite a blue-and-white Greek
flag at the hotel's front gate.
   Ozal's visit is the latest move to improve relations after a
Greek-Turkish summit at the Swiss ski resort of Davos in January.
   Fifteen months ago Greece and Turkey nearly went to war over
oil-drilling rights in the Aegean Sea, which apparently persuaded
Papandreou to change his hard-line policy toward Turkey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
