<2ND_LINE>PM-People-von Karajan,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berlin Says It Wants to Keep Karajan as Conductor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials who investigated complaints Herbert
von Karajan improperly called off too many Berlin Philharmonic
orchestra concerts decided that, despite the criticism, they need
the legendary conductor.
   West Berlin cultural affairs chief Volker Hassemer said Monday
that the West Berlin Senate voted to support the 80-year-old
Karajan's continued work with the orchestra.
   ``Karajan's name is important for the Philharmonic,'' said
Hassemer, who has himself criticized the conductor for frequent
cancellations of domestic concerts.
   A Senate committee had been reviewing its contract with Karajan,
the orchestra's conductor for life, after he called off an
appearance in Berlin in April because of illness and then flew to
Japan for a 10-day tour with the orchestra the next day.
   Karajan has suffered serious medical problems in recent years,
including severe back pains that have forced him to cancel
conducting appearances.
   But critics said several concerts were canceled under
questionable circumstances.
   Philharmonic fans also complained in angry letters to newspapers
about Karajan's infrequent appearances in Berlin.
   In November, Karajan announced he could not mount the podium in
Duesseldorf because he had food poisoning from tainted fish. He
later changed his mind and performed but called off his appearance
in Stuttgart during the same tour.
   Karajan's Berlin contract calls for him to conduct about a dozen
concerts a year.
   Hassemer said the Senate would make sure the contract was
fulfilled in the future. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
