<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConcreteMail     06-14 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Concrete Mail,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contractor Mailing Concrete Blocks 700 Miles Via Postal Loophole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Anchorage building-materials
supplier is taking advantage of a loophole in postal regulations to
mail 6,000 concrete blocks to a remote village 700 miles away.
   The shipments across Alaska could end up costing the U.S. Postal
Service $500,000, and even the air carrier that stands to profit
thinks the mail system is being abused.
   Sam Krogstad of Bush Consolidators, which specializes in sending
construction materials via the mail, says the Postal Service's
losses are partly self-inflicted because the postal system pays 10
times as much to send the building materials by air freight as it
charges Krogstad to mail them.
   Each individually addressed concrete block costs Krogstad $4.33
in postage. The same block costs the post office $50.94 to deliver
to Wainwright, an Arctic Ocean Eskimo community about 90 miles
southwest of Barrow. That's a subsidy of $46.61 per block.
   Krogstad also is mailing 4,600 bags of cement to Wainwright.
   The blocks each weigh 67 pounds and the bags of cement about 65
pounds, so they fall just under the parcel-post limit of 70 pounds
to qualify as mail. His postage costs will total about $45,000.
   The blocks and bags could have been shipped via air freight from
Anchorage for a little more than $210,000, but the way mail is
handled in rural Alaska more than doubles the cost.
   First, the Postal Service trucks the blocks to Fairbanks, about
360 miles. They are then flown to Barrow on large cargo planes,
transferred to small planes and flown to Wainwright in loads of 18
to 35 blocks.
   The practice is called ``bypass'' mail because the shipment
moves directly from sender to airline to addressee, bypassing post
offices.
   ``This was not the intent of the bypass program,'' says Tim
Dorgan, a Postal Service transportation supervisor. ``The original
intent of bypass mail was to clear the postal floor of large
shipments of groceries and staples required for day-to-day living.''
   But Krogstad says the system means his shipments cost the Postal
Service 76 cents a pound from Fairbanks to Wainwright instead of
the 30 cents a pound that a charter flight from Anchorage to
Wainwright would cost.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Krogstad said. ``It's un-American, it's got
to be unconstitutional, that a branch of the U.S. government can't
go out and competitively bid to get the best price on hauling the
mail.''
   Even one of the prime beneficiaries of the block-lift has
misgivings.
   ``We're philosophically opposed to it,'' says Don Brugman,
president of Northern Air Cargo, which is hauling many of the
blocks and cement bags. ``It's not what the mail is for.''
   Dorgan says he's worried the block-lift may put an end to bypass
mail once word gets around. ``The people in the bush are the ones
who are going to suffer,'' he said.
   Another problem, says Dorgan, is that the block-lift may cause a
backup of ordinary mail, such as groceries, bound for villages
served from Barrow.
   The idea of mailing the materials ``was an angle that got us the
job,'' said Bob Gilman, owner of Gilco Construction, a contractor
building a small-boat harbor at Wainwright with the blocks.
   He says he feels bad, but ``it is just an angle and that's the
nature of the business we're in.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
