<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoeticJustice     06-14 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poetic Justice,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Finds Poetic Justice In Civil Damage Award Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alas! 'Tis poetic justice, wrote the jurist,
perhaps disturbing your legal purists.
   In a ruling that started with a poem, U.S. District Judge H. Lee
Sarokin upheld a bankruptcy judge's decision that Kevin A.
Rowland's filing for bankruptcy was no protection from an $8,500
award won against him by Sean Coughlin.
   Coughlin, 27, won the award in his lawsuit against Rowland, who
punched out his front teeth during a teen-age fracas in Bergenfield
in 1979, according to Sarokin's opinion.
   In his ruling Monday, Sarokin wrote:
   ``On this appeal the facts are undisputed; Mr. Rowland's punch
caused Mr. Coughlin's teeth to be uprooted,''
   ``Coughlin sued in the state court and won.
   ``Rowland filed in bankruptcy to get the debt undone.
   ``The bankruptcy court found the assault to be a willful and
malicious blow,
   ``And the request to discharge the debt was answered `no.'
   ``The bankruptcy court correctly decided that the debtor
intended harm,
   ``By propelling his fist into plaintiff's mouth with his arm.
   ``This court agrees that bankruptcy law should not be enlarged,
   ``So as to permit a judgment for assault and battery to be
discharged.
   ``To do so would require existing precedent to be spurned.
   ``For these reasons the decision of the bankruptcy court will be
affirmed.''
</TEXT>
