<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteSuit-Players     06-14 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit-Players,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Cigarette Suit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the key players in the cigarette
liability case filed by Rose and Antonio Cipollone against three
tobacco companies in U.S. District Court:
   _ Antonio Cipollone, 64, recently moved to a Lakehurst
retirement community after more than 20 years in Little Ferry. He
emigrated from Italy at age 15 and worked in construction, then as
a cable-splicer. He attended every day of the four-month trial. He
said his wife's painful illness and death was ``devastating,'' and
continued with the case because she wanted him to.
   _ Rose Cipollone started smoking at age 16, contracted lung
cancer in 1981 and died four years ago at age 58. Mrs. Cipollone
was raised in East Harlem in New York, and moved to New Jersey in
1960. ``I was sure that if there was anything that dangerous, that
the tobacco people wouldn't allow it and the government wouldn't
let them'' sell cigarettes, she said before her death.
   _ Marc Z. Edell, 36, acted as the lead attorney for Cipollone. A
graduate of New York University Law School, he works for the
Millburn Township firm of Budd, Larner, Gross, Picillo, Rosenbaum,
Greenberg & Sade, which defended the Manville Co. in asbestos
litigation. Edell, at a previous firm, defended another asbestos
company. Edell, in explaining why his client was seeking damages in
the case, said in his summation that, ``This is not acceptable
behavior by any industry.''
   _ Donald J. Cohn, 58, senior attorney for tobacco companies and
specifically represented Liggett. A graduate of Yale Law School,
Cohn is a member of the New York firm Webster & Sheffield and has
represented Liggett in tobacco suits for 23 years. A former
assistant U.S. attorney in New York and a fellow of the American
College of Trial Lawyers.
   _ Philip Morris Inc. of New York is the leading U.S. cigarette
manufacturer with 37.9 percent of $22 billion market and makes
Marlboro, the nation's top-selling brand. Its parent corporation
also owns General Foods Corp. and Miller Brewing Co. The
conglomerate reported net earnings of $1.84 billion on operating
revenues of $27.7 billion in 1987. It employs 90,000 in United
States.
   _ Lorillard Inc. of New York has 8.2 percent of domestic
cigarette market with a net income of $246.9 million on sales of
$1.68 billion. It is a wholly owned subsidiary of Loews Corp.,
which also owns CNA Insurance, Bulova Watch Co. and one quarter of
CBS Inc. Lorillard is the nation's oldest tobacco company. Founded
in 1760 by Frenchman Pierre Lorillard. Makes Newport, Kent and
True. It has 4,650 employees.
   _ Liggett Group Inc. of Durham, N.C., has 3.6 percent of the
cigarette market. It has a net income of $30.7 million on sales of
$531.9 million and is the nation's sixth largest cigarette maker
and manufactures L&M, Chesterfield, Lark and Eve. It employs 1,800.
   _ U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin, 59, was born in Perth
Amboy to a newspaper publisher, was raised in Maplewood and was
appointed to the federal bench by President Carter in 1979. He
acted as campaign finance chairman for Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.,
in 1980. Among his cases, Sarokin freed former boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, who was jailed on triple murder charges,
citing racial bias in Carter's conviction. Sarokin is known for
outspoken opinions and ruled mid-way through the cigarette case
that the jury had enough evidence to find a tobacco industry
conspiracy ``vast in its scope, devious in its purpose and
devastating in its results.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
