<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AwadDeportation Bjt   06-14 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Awad Deportation, Bjt,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab-American Activist Deported By Israel Arrives In New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mubarak Awad, an Arab-American advocate of
non-violent resistance to Israel, arrived here after Israel defied
the United States and deported him from his birthplace of Jerusalem.
   The deportation ended a seven-month legal battle and made Awad
the 21st Arab to be expelled by Israel since the Dec. 8 start of
the Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Awad, 44, did not meet waiting reporters at Kennedy
International Airport after his arrival Monday night from Israel.
But a spokesman made a brief statement on his behalf and said Awad
planned to a hold a news conference this afternoon.
   ``He wanted me to express his deep appreciation'' to U.S.
officials who protested his deportation, said Charles Kimball,
director of the Middle East office of the National Council of
Churches. He named Secretary of State George Shultz, Assistant
Secretary of State Richard Murphy, U.S. Ambassador to Israel Thomas
Pickering and counsuls general in Israel Morris Draper and Bill
Wilcox.
   ``They have worked consistently, arduously and enormously
helpfully on his behalf from the beginning of this whole process,
and he's deeply grateful,'' Kimball said, his words at times
drowned out by the chanting of anti-Awad protesters.
   The United States condemned Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's order that Awad, a U.S. citizen, be deported. Shamir
alleged that Awad played a key role in the Arab uprising in the
occupied territories.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday, ``We think
it is unjustifiable to deny Mr. Awad the right to stay and live in
Jerusalem where he was born. If he acted illegally, he should have
been charged and tried in court with full due process of law.''
   Israel has regularly carried out deportations to quell unrest or
subdue Palestinian nationalist activity, notably expelling nine
West Bank mayors between 1980 and 1982. But the number of
deportations has greatly increased since the Arab uprising began.
   Awad, whom supporters call the ``Palestinian Gandhi,'' denied
inciting violence against Israel but has supported the uprising in
the territories Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war.
Although he has little influence in the Palestinian community, some
tactics he advocates, such as tax boycotts and commercial strikes,
were adopted by leaders of the uprising.
   Awad, who was incarcerated 40 days in Israel, was kept away from
reporters in Jerusalem before he left, but his letters to
supporters from prison were distributed.
   ``Even after my departure, my efforts will continue,'' Awad
wrote. ``We have no choice but to continue with the uprising for
our liberation.''
   He vowed in the letters to return soon. Awad, a Christian, has
said he might convert to Judaism as a means to return to Israel.
   His deportation was protested by about a dozen Israelis at the
Jerusalem airport and 25 supporters in downtown Jerusalem. Dozens
of angry Israelis staged an impromptu counterdemonstration, calling
the Awad supporters traitors.
   Awad was deported on the grounds that his three-month tourist
visa, issued when he entered Israel last August, had expired. The
Israelis refused to extend the visa, and the Israeli Supreme Court
last week rejected Awad's appeal to remain.
   Some 50 demonstrators _ about evenly split for and against Awad
_ gathered at Kennedy Airport.
   New York State Assemblyman Dov Hikind, a Brooklyn Democrat, led
a group of protesters who shouted ``Awad is a terrorist.''
Separated from the Hikind group by a line of police officers was a
pro-Arab group shouting ``Down, down with Israel'' and ``Long live
Mubarak.''
   Awad, who lived in the United States for 13 years before
returning to Jerusalem in 1983, is the founder of the Palestinian
Center for the Study of Non-Violence. He has lectured on civil
disobedience, counseled teachers against corporal punishment and
planted olive trees in West Bank villages to underscore the Arabs'
claim to the land.
   He lived in Wapakoneta, Ohio, where he still owns a home. His
wife, Nancy Nye, flew to New York on Sunday.
</TEXT>
