<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     06-14 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Turn Up Volume on Afghan Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev threatened to retaliate if
Pakistan keeps supplying Afghan rebels while Moscow withdraws its
troops from Afghanistan.
   Monday's warning was the first of its kind directly from the
Soviet leader. It came in a joint statement with Afghan President
Najib.
   It followed reports from Pakistan that said Soviet forces
returned to some cities in eastern Afghanistan to fight guerrillas
who raided posts defended by Afghan troops.
   The joint Najib-Gorbachev statement distributed over the
official Tass news agency said: ``The Soviet Union and Afghanistan
believed that the U.N. Mission monitoring compliance with the
Geneva accords would adopt ... effective measures to curb the
practice (of Pakistan aiding the guerrillas) which, if continued,
would make it necessary to undertake the most resolute retaliatory
steps.''
   In recent days, the Soviets have been warning Pakistan and the
United States that continuing to arm the guerrillas violated the
accords signed in Geneva in April. Under the accords, the Kremlin
agreed to withdraw its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan by
Feb. 15, and the withdrawal began May 15.
   The Red Army intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979 and has
been helping the Marxist government fight U.S.-backed Moslem rebels.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez said Monday that Soviet troops were
leaving Afghanistan ``faster than we all expected.''
   Thousands of Soviet troops have already pulled out, but Cordovez
refused to say exactly how many.
   However, Pakistan's U.N. ambassador, S. Shah Nawaz, said Monday
that ``the world will not be surprised if a crumbling (Afghan)
regime makes a desperate bid to retain the protective umbrella of
foreign troops.''
</TEXT>
