<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-14 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Call For Korean Unification Near Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.H. LEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IMJINGAK, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students
chanting anti-American slogans demonstrated today at the edge of
the demilitarized zone for reunification of North Korea and South
Korea.
   About 1,300 students staged a sitdown protest in front of a
bridge leading to the zone that divides the Korean peninsula. The
bridge was blocked by steel barriers and rolls of barbed wire.
   ``Drive out Yankees who hinder unification'' and ``Advance
unification,'' students chanted.
   The students denounced the government of President Roh Tae-woo
and yelled slogans calling on all South Korean students to refuse
compulsory weekly military training. The training is required for
all male students.
   U.S. Army troops that normally guard the bridge were withdrawn
before the students arrived today. A few South Korean personnel
were seen guarding the bridge on the other side of the barriers.
   The students, from Korea and Joongang universities in Seoul,
went to Imjingak in a convoy of buses for a prayer ceremony for
reunification. They were accompanied by professors from the two
schools to help ensure the demonstration was peaceful.
   Imjingak, the last civilian area on the main road from Seoul, is
about three miles from the southern edge of the demilitarized zone.
   The government banned a march Friday to the border with
communist North Korean by thousands of radical students seeking
talks with North Korean student delegates on reunification.
   Fierce street clashes erupted in Seoul when riot police blocked
radicals going to the border, and about 900 students were arrested.
   Student leaders said today's demonstration, described as a
prayer ceremony for unification, was different from Friday's march
since there were no plans to enter the demilitarized zone or meet
with North Korean representatives. The South Korean government says
it alone can have contacts with the north.
   The 2{-mile-wide zone separates the two Koreas with the border
running through the center. Forces of the two sides control their
respective sides of the zone.
   U.S. troops help control the south's side of the zone across
from Imjingak and the Panmunjom truce site that straddles the
border.
   Students wanted to meet Friday at Panmunjom with North Korean
student delegates who reportedly were waiting there.
   Radical students have been demanding reunification of the Korean
peninsula, divided since 1945 when U.S. and Soviet troops ended the
Japanese occupation at the end of World War II.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent anti-government
and anti-American protests during the past month. Radical students
battled riot police to press for overthrow of the Roh government
and reunification.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority among South Korean
students, claim the United States enforces partition of the
peninsula to rule the south. Radicals demand withdrawal of the
42,000 U.S. troops based in the south under a defense treaty.
   The radicals have been unable to attract public support. Most
South Koreans fear the north is determined to conquer the
peninsula. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to start the
Korean War.
</TEXT>
