<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IllegalAliens     06-14 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Illegal Aliens,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Appeals Court Says Illegal Alien Entitled To Sue For Back Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court decision that an illegal
alien can sue his employer for nearly $50,000 in unpaid wages
``blazes a trail'' for other rulings favoring immigrant workers, a
union official says.
   The Atlanta-based 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that
Rajni J. Patel, an illegal alien from India, is entitled to sue for
unpaid back wages incurred during a three-year period. The decision
reverses a U.S. District Court ruling last year throwing out the
case, which hinged on the court's interpretation of the U.S. Fair
Labor Standards Act.
   The International Ladies Garment Workers Union supplied Patel
with legal help and filed a brief supporting him.
   Union spokesman John Burke said the ruling not only vindicates
Patel's claims, but ``blazes a trail which, we hope, will lead to
similar rulings on other fronts ... favorable to immigrants.''
   The appeals court cleared the way for Patel to proceed with his
lawsuit against a Birmingham, Ala., hotel, where he worked as a
maintenance man and janitor from 1982 to 1985.
   Patel in 1986 sued the Quality Inn South of Birmingham and its
owners, Sumani Corp., contending that the hotel violated wage and
overtime laws and owed him $47,132 in back pay, plus damages and
attorneys' fees.
   In March 1987, according to the appeals court opinion, U.S.
District Judge William M. Acker Jr. suggested to the hotel's
lawyers that they request a summary judgment to the effect that
Patel, as an undocumented alien, wasn't entitled to the protection
of the Fair Labor Standards Act.
   The hotel's attorneys, ``able to take a hint,'' made such a
request, the 11th Circuit noted, and the judgment was issued
against Patel in May 1987. He appealed.
   A three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit Court, in an opinion
released last week, noted that the U.S. Supreme Court has
historically ``adopted an expansive definition of the term
`employee,''' and that Congress has clearly intended for
undocumented aliens to be protected under the fair labor law.
   Patel's case, the 11th Circuit Court said, falls under the law,
and ``nothing in the act purports to limit the remedy available to
... workers.''
   ``Patel is not attempting to recover back pay for being
unlawfully deprived of a job,'' the appeals court wrote. ``Rather,
he simply seeks to recover unpaid minimum wages and overtime for
work already performed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
