<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Market Quiet, Dollar Weaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market's key indicator closed
slightly higher today, while the U.S. dollar weakened against the
Japanese yen in slow trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose by 25.26
points, or 0.09 percent, from Monday to finish at 28,061.80, the
highest closing level since Thursday's record 28,072.02 points.
   An official of Nomura Securities Co., who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the market was slack, even though the Nikkei Stock
Average rose slightly. He said investors were refraining from
taking action without fresh incentives.
   Volume of trade in the first section totaled 850 million shares,
down from Monday's 900 million shares.
   In foreign exchange dealings, the U.S. dollar closed at 125.05
yen, down 0.14 yen from Monday's close. It opened at 125.15 yen and
was traded in a range between 125.02 yen and 125.18 yen.
   An official of the Bank of Tokyo said the market was quiet in
anticipation of the release of U.S. trade figures for April in the
United States later today.
   Volume of trade totaled $2.5 billion, compared to Monday's $2.6
billion dollars and $5.5 billion on Friday.
   Traders said market participants were expecting the U.S. trade
deficit in April to rise from the March level of $11.95 billion to
$12-13 billion on an adjusted basis.
</TEXT>
