<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters President Released from Phoenix Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President Jackie Presser has
been released from a hospital where doctors have said the
critically ill Presser has been receiving radiation treatments for
brain tumors.
   Presser was released Monday from Barrow Neurological Institute,
Kay Lyshoj, a nursing coordinator, said today. She said she had no
information on Presser's whereabouts or condition.
   Debra Gelbart, Barrow spokeswoman, said she had no information
about Presser and noted that his family had requested no
information be released.
   Presser had been at Barrow since mid-May, receiving radiation
treatment after the removal of a cancerous lesion from his brain
May 17.
   In a June 7 telephone conversation with U.S. District Judge
George White in Cleveland, Barrow Director Dr. Robert Spetzler said
Presser was being treated with radiation for one brain lesion and
may have two others.
   Another doctor, Dr. Leslie Sheeler of the Cleveland Clinic, told
White in a May 26 letter that Presser may have six months to live.
Presser underwent lung cancer surgery at the Cleveland Clinic in
January 1987,
   White on June 7 postponed indefinitely Presser's trial on
racketeering and embezzlement charges. The trial had been scheduled
to start July 12.
   Presser relinquished his duties as Teamsters president for four
months beginning in May because of his poor health.
Secretary-Treasurer Weldon Mathis has taken over Presser's duties.
