<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0501EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Cardin     06-14 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Cardin,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Justice Minister Dies at 69.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucien Cardin, who precipitated a parliamentary
crisis in 1966 as justice minister in the Liberal government of
Prime Minister Lester Pearson, died at his home after a long battle
with cancer. He was 69.
   Cardin, who died Monday, had been a judge of the Tax Court of
Canada since 1983.
   First elected to Parliament as Liberal member from Quebec in
1952, Cardin was re-elected six times before deciding not to run in
the 1968 general election.
   After the Liberals under Pearson formed a government in 1963,
Cardin was appointed associate defense minister, then public works
minister, and finally justice minister.
   His troubles as justice minister began in 1965 when he confirmed
on television that Victor Spencer, a Vancouver postal clerk, had
been spying for the Soviet Union.
   Spencer had admitted to spying and was fired by the post office
without a pension. He wasn't prosecuted because he was dying of
cancer.
   The opposition in Parliament contended that Spencer shouldn't
have been fired without being prosecuted. Cardin defended the
government's position.
   To save his government, Pearson had to agree to an opposition
demand for an investigation into the loss of Spencer's pension.
   The scandal grew when Cardin, under opposition attack for the
Liberals' handling of security cases, replied on March 4, 1966,
that the opposition had no business talking. Cardin then mentioned
an embarrassing case involving the Conservatives.
   Pearson had asked the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in 1964 for
all files on members of Parliament in which security was involved.
   As a result, he had been briefed on Gerda Munsinger, a German
call-girl and suspected Soviet agent who was considered a security
problem because of an affair with Pierre Sevigny. At the time,
Sevigny was associate defense minister in the Conservative
government of Prime Minister John Diefenbaker.
   Pearson had discussed the Munsinger affair privately with
Diefenbaker, but Cardin's blurted reference in Parliament was the
first public disclosure.
   Pearson appointed a justice of Canada's Supreme Court to look
into the matter, which aroused concern in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Cardin resigned as justice minister in 1967. He was member of
the immigration appeal board from 1970 to 1972 and served on the
tax review board that eventually became the Tax Court of Canada.
   He is survived by his wife Marcelle and four children.
</TEXT>
