<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0491 06-14 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Hit Singapore-flagged Ship off Saudi Arabia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details on the attack. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX MINASIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats attacked a
Singapore-flagged oil tanker with machine guns and set it on fire
today in the Persian Gulf, shipping executives reported.
   It was the second time in four days that Iranians raided a
tanker near Iran's Farsi island off Saudi Arabia's coast.
   The shipping sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
identified today's target as the 87,768-ton Neptune Subaru. No
casualties were reported.
   They said its Asian crew, including a Sri Lankan captain and
sailors from Malaysia, Singapore and India, put out the fires, and
the vessel sailed under its own power to the Saudi Arabian port of
Jubail for inspection.
   The Neptune Subaru was also hit by the Iranians in the Strait of
Hormuz, gateway to the gulf, in March, the executives said.
   The tanker was empty and heading for Kuwait for a shipment of
crude oil when the gunboats opened fire early today in a 45-minute
raid.
   Farsi island is a base for Iran's Revolutionary Guards, who
often attack ships sailing to and from Kuwait. They also have been
blamed for mining the waterway.
   The U.S. Navy has mounted a major mine-sweeping operation and
sent several warships to patrol in the area. It was not immediately
clear if any U.S. warship was nearby when the Neptune Subaru was
attacked today.
   The vessel was about 40 miles west of Farsi, near the Saudi
island of Hurqus. Iran had attacked several ships in that area
earlier in the so-called ``tanker war,'' an offshoot of the
7{-year-old gulf war.
   In the exchanges, Iraq attacks Iran's vital oil shipping lanes
to try to throttle its foe's economy. Iran retaliates by raiding
neutral vessels, mainly those trading with Kuwait or Saudi Arabia.
   The Persian state accuses these two oil powers of aiding Iraq's
military effort.
   Shipping sources said the skipper of the Neptune Subaru appeared
to be on his first trip into the gulf.
   ``This captain, like others we encounter, came to the gulf with
no prior knowledge whatsoever about the dangers of the tanker war
or what precautions should be taken against ship attacks,'' said a
shipping official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On Saturday, the Iranians attacked the U.S.-owned,
British-flagged Esso Demetia supertanker about 120 miles south of
where the Neptune Subaru was raided. A U.S. frigate rushed to the
scene, but its help was not needed.
   Kuwait registered 11 of its tankers in the United States last
year to entitle them to U.S. warship protection.
   The Pentagon recently broadened the task of the U.S. Navy in the
gulf by allowing warships to intervene in attacks on foreign
commercial ships.
   Before the new policy went into effect May 3, the Navy was
allowed to offer only humanitarian assistance.
   But Iran has struck seven vessels in the waterway since then in
apparent defiance of the Navy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
