<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers and Storms Roll Over South; Heat Hits North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms converged on the South and Midwest
today, bringing drenching rains to the Texas Panhandle, after much
of the North sweltered in a record-breaking heat wave.
   The thunderstorm system rumbled through northeastern New Mexico,
southwest Kansas and the Texas Panhandle, and a flash flood watch
was in effect for a number of counties in the southwest Panhandle.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across Minnesota and
the Dakotas, with the most intense thunderstorms in eastern South
Dakota and southwestern Minnesota.
   Showers and thunderstorms also lingered over southern Florida.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with clear
skies over much of America's eastern half.
   On Monday, the heat wave scorched sections of Wisconsin. At
Green Bay's, Austin Straubel Airport, the temperature hit 94
degrees, surpassing the 1956 record high of 93.
   In Michigan, Marquette reported a 93-degree high, the sixth day
this month a record mark was set there. The old record of 85
degrees was set in 1976. In Alpena, the temperature reached 94,
breaking the old record set that year by 2 degrees.
   The high for the nation Monday was 107 degrees at Laughlin, Nev.
   Today's forecast called for showers through northern Maine and
southern Florida; showers and thunderstorms from northern Minnesota
to North Dakota, eastern South Dakota, eastern Nebraska and eastern
Montana; and sunny skies over much of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s over northern Maine,
from northern Minnesota to North Dakota, Montana, Wyoming, western
South Dakota, the Nebraska Panhandle and northern Colorado, as well
as along the California coast; in the 90s from New England to
Virginia, over the Ohio Valley and the Tennessee Valley, across
lower Michigan and Wisconsin, from Iowa to Louisiana, over the
eastern portion of the central Plains and much of Texas; reaching
the 90s from southwest Oregon to inland northern and central
California; and 100 to 110 degrees through the desert Southwest;
and in the 80s over the rest of the country.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 87 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 fair; Boston 76 fair; Buffalo 66 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 64 fair; Cincinnati 66 fair; Cleveland 71 fair;
Detroit 68 fair; Miami 76 showers; New York 70 fair; Philadelphia
68 fair; Pittsburgh 67 fair; Portland, Maine 60 fair; Washington 70
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 61 rain; Chicago 75 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
77 partly cloudy; Denver 58 partly cloudy; Des Moines 70 fair;
Indianapolis 66 fair; Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 82
windy; Nashville 65 fair; New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 75 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 68 fair; Anchorage 56 fair; Las Vegas 80
fair; Los Angeles 59 foggy; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake City 56
fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 54 windy; Seattle 60 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 68 fair; Toronto 66 fair.
</TEXT>
