<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GentlemanBandit     06-14 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gentleman Bandit,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Seeks Man Suspected in 30 Bank Robberies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robber dubbed ``the
gentleman bandit'' because of his penchant for three-piece suits
and his soft-spoken manner in dozens of holdups, has changed his
clothes and his pattern, says the FBI.
   The robber, who's averaged one to three holdups a month since
his 30-bank spree in Georgia and South Florida began in 1986,
pulled his last heist in Naples on March 21, FBI spokesman Paul
Miller said in asking the public for help Monday.
   ``It does look like his pattern has been broken, but whether
he's been arrested for something else or is sick from narcotics
abuse, we don't know,'' Miller said. ``That's part of the reason we
want to get some publicity.''
   The bandit, who is about 30 years old, could be pulling the
robberies to feed a drug habit, Miller said. Investigators base
that theory on photographs taken during robberies that show the man
growing thinner.
   The bandit also has recently stowed his three-piece suit for
more casual garb, and has shaved off his beard, FBI officials said.
   The robber usually carries a folder or accordion-type briefcase,
Miller said. While the soft-spoken man has threatened bodily harm
in notes to tellers, he rarely displays a weapon and no one has
been hurt.
   Thousands of dollars have been taken, but Miller did not give an
amount.
   Because of the robber's mobility and familiarity with different
cities and exit routes, investigators believe he has a legitimate
job, possibly as a traveling salesman, Miller said.
   Investigators speculate the man does not live near the banks he
robs because no one has come forward to help identify him, even
though robbery photos have been publicized.
   ``We're hoping somebody who owns a motel or a hotel might
recognize him as a steady client,'' Miller said.
</TEXT>
