<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru   06-14 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0455,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Strike Eases, Azerbaijan Turns Down Annexation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Armenians ending strike,
Azerbaijan rejecting annexation appeal. No pickup. Changes byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Armenians who joined a strike to demand
annexation of a disputed region of neighboring Azerbaijan returned
to work today after being assured that their republic's government
would press their demand.
   But the Azerbaijani government voted to reject ceding control of
the Nagorno-Karabakh region, which is predominantly Armenian.
   Mofses Gorgisyan, an Armenian jailed in April and May for
staging nationalist demonstrations, said a general strike shut down
most businesses in Armenia on Monday, but that today ``some people
are working, maybe half.''
   He said students agitating for annexation had for three weeks
staged a sit-in outside the Opera Theater in Yerevan, capital of
the southern republic.
   Nagorno-Karabakh was assigned to Azerbaijan in 1923. Most
Azerbaijanis are Moslems and most Armenians are Christians.
   Azerbaijan's official Baku Radio reported today that the
executive committee of that republic's legislature met Monday in
the Azerbaijani capital, Baku, and turned down a request by
Nagorno-Karabakh officials that their territory be transferred to
Armenia.
   The report, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in
London, said the Presidium of the republic's Supreme Soviet found
the demand ``unacceptable'' because it would be ``contrary to the
interests of the Azerbaijani and Armenian population of the
republic and would be incompatible with the tasks of consolidating
the friendship between all the peoples of our country, as well as
with the task of reconstruction.''
   It said the annexation request came from the Nagorno-Karabakh
Autonomous Region's Soviet of People's Deputies, one of two
chambers of the region's legislature. A request from the same body
in February touched off massive street demonstrations and strikes
in Nagorno-Karabakh and Yerevan.
   Armenia's legislature is to meet Wednesday to discuss the
annexation demand.
   Armenia's new Communist Party leader, Suren Arutyunyan, told
more than 500,000 demonstrators in Yerevan on Monday that the
Armenian Supreme Soviet would ``decide positively'' on their claim,
according to Gorgisyan and Sergei Grigoryants, a dissident
journalist in Moscow.
   Gorgisyan quoted Arutyunyan as saying a majority of Supreme
Soviet deputies indicated they support annexation. He said the
speech was replayed three times on Armenian television, apparently
in an effort to persuade people to return to their jobs.
   Since the Azerbaijani legislature has rejected the annexation
demand, if the Armenian Supreme Soviet calls for transfer of
Nagorno-Karabakh, the issue would have to be decided by the central
government in Moscow.
   Moscow officials have rejected the demand once.
   Gorgisyan said Armenians believe the next move is up to Moscow:
``We are interested in Moscow's answer. Moscow has been silent so
far.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev got involved in the issue in
February, appealing to Armenians and Azerbaijanis to be calm and
promising the dispute would be reviewed.
   The Kremlin later rejected the annexation demand and the central
government instead approved a package of social and cultural
improvements for Nagorno-Karabakh.
   According to Gorgisyan, three Armenians have been lying on the
square outside the Opera Theater on a hunger strike since June 4.
He estimated that 2,000 to 5,000 people were gathered on the
square, where the latest round of demonstrations began May 25.
   A worker at the Yerevan Hotel said the general strike was still
on and demonstrators were making speeches and holding posters.
``It's very peaceful. People are highly cultured,'' said the
worker. The phone conversation was cut off before a reporter could
ask the woman's name.
   The ethnic dispute has erupted into violence several times. In
late February and early March 32 people, mostly Armenians, were
killed in riots in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait.
   On Monday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said
an Azerbaijani officer was killed by shotgun fire from an Armenian
during protests in Baku. He did not say precisely when the shooting
occurred.
   There were unconfirmed reports Saturday of large-scale protests
in Baku.
   Also Monday, the party leader of Azerbaijan, Abdul Rahman
Vezirov, told workers in Baku that they were correct in resisting
Armenians' demands to give up Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Communist Party authorities put Vezirov in charge of Azerbaijan
and Arutyunyan in charge of Armenia on May 21, apparently firing
their predecessors for not containing the dispute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
