<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-14 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Little Changed as Markets Await U.S. Trade Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in Europe this
morning as markets awaited the release later in the day of U.S.
trade data. Gold made slight gains.
   Dealers said the dollar might strengthen if forecasters were
correct in predicting an increase in the U.S. trade gap from $11.95
billion in March to a seasonally adjusted $12.2 billion in April.
   One dealer in Frankfurt said this would leave the dollar room to
rise, but another said:
   ``There was a lot of optimism after the last (trade) figures,
but the new figures will remind the market that the deficit is
still around, and that it won't fall below $10 billion any time
soon. And the central banks don't want the dollar to rise either.''
   A dealer in Milan commented: ``Any result above $12 billion will
just remind traders how stubborn a problem the U.S. trade imbalance
is.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.14 yen to a closing 125.05. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 125.12 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _ 1.7249 West German marks, up from 1.7241
   _ 1.4414 Swiss francs, down from 1.4424
   _ 5.8210 French francs, up from 5.7265
   _ 1.9349 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9345
   _ 1.281.00 Italian lire, down from 1,281.75
   _ 1.2185 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2203
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8150, compared
with $1.8165 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $450.20 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $449.00. At mid-morning Tuesday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$450.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $450.70, up from $448.50 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, where trading resumed following a long
weekend, gold closed down $5.41 at a bid $452.58.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.98 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $7.02.
</TEXT>
