<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     06-14 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Sikhs Killed After Attacking Troops With Swords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two militant Sikh separatists rushed out
of the Golden Temple complex today, attacked paramilitary troops
with swords and wounded two before they were shot dead, police said.
   Elsewhere in Punjab state, a gang of Sikh extremists raided a
village north of Amritsar on Monday night and shot nine people to
death, including eight Hindus, police said. One of the victims was
a 10-year-old girl.
   The attack at the Golden Temple occurred just outside the main
entrance, where police set up a post a month ago to search
everybody entering the Sikh religion's holiest shrine.
   The searches are intended to keep Sikh extremists from sneaking
weapons into the shrine. Sikh radicals have been fighting a
guerrilla war since 1982 for a separate homeland in Punjab.
   The two Sikh radicals apparently had escaped earlier police
detection, said M.S. Sethi, superintendent of the paramilitary
Central Reserve Police Force.
   They grabbed swords from shops near the temple gate and began
slashing at paramilitary forces, Sethi said. He said two of his men
were wounded before the assailants were shot to death by other
troops.
   Police and paramilitary forces besieged the Golden Temple May
9-18 to drive out extremists who had turned the shrine into an
armed camp. At least 46 people were killed during the siege, most
of them militants. More than 200 radicals and sympathizers
surrendered.
   The government has begun buying and demolishing buildings with
30 yards of the Golden Temple complex to prevent extremists from
using them as cover to sneak into the shrine.
   The attack on the Hindus Monday night was in the village of
Chakpamani, about 22 miles north of Amritsar. Police said up to 10
Sikh extremists arrived at the village on foot and entered several
Hindu homes, killing seven people.
   The Sikh servant of the village's Hindu leader, Kishan Chand,
tried to ward off the attackers but was killed, police said.
Chand's 10-year-old daughter was shot to death, but Chand escaped
injury, they said.
   The killings in Chakpamani raised to nearly 1,290 the number of
people killed by Sikh extremists in Punjab since the start of the
year. Last year, 1,030 people died.
   Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed
to the separatist campaign.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million people
but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
