<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AviancaSeizure     06-14 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Avianca Seizure,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Returns Seized 747</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Avianca Airlines jumbo jet seized June 4 after
422 pounds of cocaine was found in a shipment of cut flowers has
been released, and the national airline of Colombia has agreed to
halt shipments, officials say.
   The Customs Service said Monday that Avianca has decided to
suspend flower shipments, but airline sources have said the carrier
will halt all cargo shipments to the United States after June 23.
   Under an agreement with Customs, Avianca also said it will
``make substantial efforts to persuade the Colombian government to
make much greater efforts to prevent criminal elements in Colombia
from using commercial aircraft for the smuggling of controlled
substances to the United States.''
   Customs issued a $6.8 million penalty notice after the seizure
of the Boeing 747; Avianca has advised Customs it will petition to
reduce the amount.
   The seized jet had been making about 22 flights a month from
Colombia to Miami carrying an average of 6,1000 boxes of flowers
per flight.
   The perishable shipments of roses and carnations have been one
of the favorite hiding place for drug smugglers, drug investigators
say. Inspectors have seized 14 Avianca shipments since January
1986, including eight flower shipments that yielded 1,677 pounds of
cocaine.
</TEXT>
