<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Italy 1stLd-Writethru a0433 06-14 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Italy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 4 grafs new with Shultz meeting; Editing throughout to
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian Premier Ciriaco De Mita calls on
President Reagan today after meeting with Secretary of State George
Shultz to discuss East-West relations and the Middle East peace
process.
   Italy's agreement to provide a home for 72 American fighter jets
shares room with the forthcoming economic summit on De Mita's
agenda here.
   Also on the agenda are Reagan's recent summit with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and arms control negotiations between the two
superpowers, said a U.S. official who briefed reporters on the
visit.
   Shultz and De Mita met for an hour but there were no details
immediately available on their talk.
   Reagan and De Mita were expected to discuss the agenda of the
seven-nation summit, which brings together the heads of the world's
major industrialized countries for three days of talks beginning
Sunday in Toronto, Canada.
   The topics of discussion at the informal get-together in Toronto
are still being worked out and the United States would like to hear
Italy's views, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   De Mita, who took office in April at the head of Italy's 48th
government since World War II, also was to meet with Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, and House and Senate leaders.
   Shultz and De Mita had been expected to discuss Italy's
agreement in principle to take in the 72 F-16 fighter jets of the
401st Tactical Fighter Wing which Spain is evicting from the
Torrejon air base near Madrid.
   Italy's lower house of parliament is scheduled to vote on the
matter Thursday or Friday, and then the Italian Senate must give
its approval.
   Once parliamentary approval is given, NATO experts will meet to
determine where to deploy the planes, the official said.
   The official indicated that a new facility may have to be built
to accommodate the 401st, but said no decision had been made.
   Shultz also had been expected to brief De Mita on the secretary
of state's shuttle last week to the Middle East, where he tried in
vain to persuade Israeli and Arab leaders to negotiate peace.
   ``Italy as a Mediterranean state has a view of the Middle East
and of the region which it believes is unique,'' said the official.
``They have different views,'' the official conceded, ``but we've
always wanted to listen to them.''
   Italy believes Israel and its Arab neighbors should meet under
international auspices to negotiate an agreement under which Israel
would give back all the lands it captured in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   The United States favors a return of some lands to be worked out
in direct Arab-Israeli talks, without external interference.
   De Mita, who heads the Christian Democratic Party, took office
on April 13 after a month-long political crisis caused by the
resignation of his predecessor Giovanni Goria who served for only
seven months.
</TEXT>
