<HEAD>`Croc' Holds On, `Big' Looks Big</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS order in list showing accumulated gross before weeks
in release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were few surprises in last weekend's
movie box office ratings as ``Crocodile' Dundee II'' remained in
first place for the third straight week despite stiffening
competition from the second-place comedy ``Big.''
   In third place was the debut Disney comedy ``Big Business,''
starring Bette Midler and Lily Tomlin in dual roles as two sets of
twins.
   ``The Presidio,'' an action-adventure story starring Sean
Connery and Mark Harmon, was in fourth place for its debut, while
the third movie in the ``Poltergeist'' series captured fifth place.
   ``Rambo III,'' fell to sixth place after a 44 percent drop in
business, and the George Lucas-produced ``Willow'' was in eighth
place.
   The second ```Crocodile' Dundee'' film starring Paul Hogan
earned $8.5 million over the weekend, while ``Big,'' starring Tom
Hanks as a 12-year-old boy who gets his wish to be a grown-up, sold
$7.9 million worth of tickets.
   The combination of Miss Midler and Miss Tomlin drew $6.1 million
in ticket sales for ``Big Business.''
   ``The Presidio'' attracted $5.1 million for its debut week.
   ``Poltergeist III,'' earned $4.3 million for its debut week.
   ``Rambo III'' had ticket sales of $4.2 million over the weekend,
down from the previous weekend's $7.69 million.
   Chevy Chase's ``Funny Farm,'' about a sportswriter's life in the
country, was in seventh place with more than $4 million in business.
   Ninth and 10th place were held by two holdovers,
``Beetlejuice,'' with $1.1 million and ``Colors,'' with $991,150.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available:
   1. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' Paramount, $8.5 million, 2,410
screens, $3,535 per screen, $61.3 million, three weeks, n-a.
   2. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $7.9 million, 1,134 screens,
$6,967 per screen, $20.5 million, two weeks, n-a.
   3. ``Big Business,'' Disney, $6.1 million, 1,167 screens, $5,238
per screen, $6.1 million, one week, n-a.
   4. ``The Presidio,'' Paramount, $5.1 million, 1,152 screens,
$4,443 per screen, $5.1 million, one week, n-a.
   5. ``Poltergeist III,'' MGM-UA, $4.3 million, 1,471 screens,
$2,953 per screen, $4.3 million, one week, n-a.
