<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0519 06-14 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Adopt Mideast Statement, Prepare To Take Up Peace
Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Awad Deportation, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 18th graf, `The recommended ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
wording of statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's largest Presbyterian group urged
Israel to end its occupation of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip,
calling its response to the Palestinian uprising ``heavy-handed,''
and today was considering its policy on U.S. anti-nuclear dissent.
   The 200th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)
also was to select a top denominational officer in an election
today taking precedence over other business facing the 630
delegates.
   The assembly on Monday approved 494-67 its statement calling on
Israel to end its occupation of the territories seized during the
Six-Day War of 1967.
   The statement from the 3 million-member Protestant denomination
said Israel's ``heavy-handed crackdown'' during the 6-month-old
Palestinian uprising ``portends what lies ahead unless a political
settlement is reached.''
   It asked Israel to ``cease the systemic violation of human
rights of Palestinians,'' such as beatings, and food and fuel
embargoes.
   The denomination urged Israel to suspend settlement programs in
the occupied territories, ``since these simply provoke the Arab
peoples and reduce the opportunity for a peaceful resolution of the
conflicting claims of Israelis and Palestinians.''
   It also:
   _ Called on Palestinians and their leaders to try to control
violence to ease the peace process.
   _ Asked the United States to ``discourage retaliation as a
counter-terror strategy in the Middle East and to address the
injustices which are among the root causes of terrorism.''
   The statement urged the United States to insist that weapons
supplied for Israel's defense not be used against civilians in the
occupied territories or in ``aggressive attacks or disproportionate
retaliation upon other countries.''
   _ Asked all parties to participate in a United Nations-sponsored
international peace conference.
   Today, the assembly was to begin discussing its statement on
``Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age.''
   The statement, which stemmed from a request five years ago by
local Presbyterian groups for guidance on how to respond to tax
resisters, was revised in lengthy meetings at the assembly by three
committees.
   The recommendations were edited to make it clear that while tax
resistance and other acts of civil disobedience could be justified,
Christians normally are expected to obey civil authorities.
   The statement was edited in an effort to remove any doubt that
disobedience is not a normal course. A section was added saying
military service could be an appropriate response to a Christian's
conscience.
   The committees reworded discussion of nuclear deterrence, but
left alone the declaration that nuclear war itself is immoral.
   The original paper said nuclear deterrence assumes the
willingness to use such weapons and is therefore immoral, although
it said unilateral disarmament is not yet feasible.
   The final recommended statement said ``nuclear deterrence has
been in danger of being regarded as an adequate and permanent means
to national security rather an interim measure of self-defense.
Such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible.''
   The Presbyterians also were to elect the stated clerk, who is
the officer responsible for overseeing the assembly's operation.
   On Saturday, a committee said it would nominate Harriet Nelson,
a lay leader from California, surprising many who expected the
panel to nominate two people, including the Rev. James E. Andrews.
   Andrews, interim co-stated clerk or stated clerk since the
denomination was formed in 1973 from the merger of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.) and the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), has said he
will be nominated from the floor.
</TEXT>
