<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--LightningStrikes     06-14 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Lightning Strikes,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lightning Starts Fire At Uranium Enrichment Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMANS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning struck a hydrogen storage tank
at a uranium enrichment plant in southeastern France and started a
fire, but firefighters put out the blaze and there was no threat to
people nearby, authorities said Tuesday.
   The tank was hit by lightning at 9:30 p.m. Monday during a
storm. It is about 500 yards from the main plant. About 30
firefighters were called to ensure that the fire did not spread to
other tanks.
   Philippe Baudoin, director of the plant, said there was no
threat to the environment or to people in the vicinity.
   The Franco-Belgian plant at Romans, 350 miles southeast of
Paris, enriches 800 tons of uranium a year for use in
pressurized-water nuclear reactors.
</TEXT>
