<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WelfareOverhaul     06-14 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare Overhaul,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Try to Craft Bill Acceptable to Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators worked Tuesday to craft a
welfare-overhaul bill acceptable to the Reagan administration but
said they would move ahead with the landmark, work-oriented measure
if no compromise could be reached.
   ``We're either going to wind it up ... or go out there (on the
floor) and start battling it out,'' said Republican Leader Bob Dole
of Kansas.
   ``It's not very clear what will satisfy the administration, and
that makes it very difficult,'' said Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., author and chief sponsor
of the five-year, $2.6 billion Family Security Act, said
closed-door negotiations on his popular bill would go on all day
and possibly into Wednesday.
   Asked if the administration appeared to want a welfare bill, he
replied, ``I think they don't want to veto a bill.''
   Aides have said President Reagan will do just that if senators
do not agree to demands that include broader state flexibility to
experiment with demonstration projects and a guaranteed rate of
welfare recipient participation in broad new education, training
and employment programs.
   Moynihan's bill would require states to institute new work and
training programs and enroll as many welfare parents as they could
afford, with special emphasis on teen-age mothers and others who
are or are likely to be long-term recipients.
   As part of its emphasis on parental responsibility, the bill
also requires extensive state efforts to determine paternity and
automatic wage withholding immediately upon the awarding of child
support.
   Moynihan's bill has 64 sponsors in the 100-member Senate, and an
aide said two additional senators support it. Before going to the
White House, it would have to be reconciled with a similar but much
more expensive House bill passed last December. It is unclear
whether either the Senate or the House could muster the two-thirds
majority needed to override a presidential veto.
   Moynihan has been fighting mandatory participation rates on
behalf of the nation's governors, who fear that with their limited
resources, they would have to provide cursory services to the least
needy people in order to meet the required level.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., said senators were discussing a
mandatory 10 percent or 15 percent participation rate, rising
eventually to 25 percent. The administration wanted to go higher
than that, he said.
   Senators said Monday that the administration was seeking a
universal, mandatory and expensive workfare program, but the issue
appeared to have evaporated by Tuesday.
   ``That's not even under discussion,'' Moynihan said.
   ``There will not be a compulsory (work) requirement from the
federal level,'' Packwood said. ``The states will have a lot of
options.''
   Moynihan also said the administration was no longer fighting a
new requirement that states make welfare benefits available to
two-parent families at least six months in a year. Twenty-six
states already provide year-round coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 1822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ProductLiability     06-14 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Product Liability,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Product Liability Bill Opposed by Consumerists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee
approved a controversial product liability bill Tuesday that
consumer activists immediately denounced as a pro-business assault
on the legal rights of victims of hazardous products.
   The bipartisan compromise, which is given virtually no chance of
passing Congress this year, would establish uniform federal
liability standards for lawsuits over defective consumer goods.
Conflicting but generally stronger state laws would be pre-empted.
   Business lobbyists said a federal law would ease the growing
burden of liability insurance costs and result in lower consumer
prices. Consumer groups said the bill would make it harder for
victims to recover damages from manufacturers of unsafe products.
   The bill, described by Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., as ``complex
and politically charged,'' was approved 30-12 with the unanimous
support of the committee's 17 Republicans and a bare 13-member
majority of its 25 Democrats.
   It was the first time a product liability bill had ever cleared
a House committee. A similar measure died on the Senate floor in
late 1986 after a filibuster led by Ernest B. Hollings, D-S.C., an
adamant foe of such legislation.
   The House measure now heads for further study by an unfriendly
Judiciary Committee, which shares jurisdiction and traditionally
has favored trial lawyers in their opposition to such bills.
   ``We are getting ready for a fight in Judiciary,'' said Rep.
Mike Synar, D-Okla., who had won the Energy and Commerce panel's
approval of several pro-consumer amendments during more than a
month of wrangling over the bill.
   Consumer lobbyists lost no time castigating the bill and its
supporters.
   ``Since 1981, American industry has been battering away at
Congress, trying to get a pre-emptive federal product liability law
passed that would give manufacturers and sellers greater
opportunity to place dangerous products on the market with
diminished liability to the people they injure,'' said Joan
Claybrook, president of Public Citizen.
   ``Today a majority of the committee brought that consumer
nightmare a little closer to reality,'' she said.
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader said the committee had sided with
``toxic chemical producers, dangerously defective product
manufacturers and other promoters of corporate violence.''
   Alexander B. Trowbridge, president of the National Association
of Manufacturers, said the bill provides a ``fair and responsible''
overhaul of product liability laws. He said it would ``help curb
the number of unwarranted lawsuits,'' stimulate the economy and
reduce consumer prices.
   ``Everyone _ except the nation's trial lawyers _ wins under this
bill,'' Trowbridge said.
   A major feature protested by consumer advocates is the ``state
of the art'' defense made available to manufacturers under the bill.
   That provision says manufacturers can escape liability for
damages if they can prove they did not know _ or could not know _
of a design defect with knowledge ``reasonably available to
experts,'' or if there was no feasible alternative design.
   Synar won approval of an amendment putting the burden of proof
on the manufacturer rather than the consumer. The committee also
accepted a pro-consumer ``escape hatch'' sponsored by Synar that
would require plaintiffs to prove only that the product was so
unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should not have been
marketed.
   Another Synar provision would ease the standard of proof that
plaintiffs must meet in suing manufacturers. But consumer interests
are unhappy over his proposal to give a judge rather than a trial
jury the responsibility for deciding whether a product should have
been barred from the market because of safety hazards.
   Critics say the bill's provision for a state-of-the-art defense,
currently available to manufacturers in only eight states, would
undermine the legal doctrine of ``strict liability'' used in 47
states and favored by consumer interests.
   That doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the
manufacturer's alleged misconduct to the defective product itself,
relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or
should have known about a product's defects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
