<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-14 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Highs In Northeast, Showers In Central States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures soared to record highs again Tuesday over the
northeastern quarter of the nation, and drought-plagued North
Dakota got cool temperatures and rain.
   Temperatures neared 100 degrees at Newark, N.J., and dozens of
other cities reached the middle 90s.
   The high of 93 at Pittsburgh tied a record that has been on the
books since 1885, and the high of 94 at Traverse City, Mich.,
toppled a record set in 1897. Marquette, Mich., had its fourth
consecutive day of record heat with a high of 89.
   Other record highs were 95 at Allentown, Pa.; 98 at Alpena,
Mich.; 96 at Baltimore; 84 at Beckley, W.Va.; 91 at Binghamton,
N.Y.; 93 at Bridgeport, Conn.; 94 at Burlington, Vt.; 94 at
Cleveland, tie; 93 at Columbus, Ohio; 95 at Detroit; 96 at Fort
Wayne, Ind.; 88 at Muskegon, Mich.; 99 at Newark, tie; 96 at
Philadelphia; 84 at Portland, Maine, tie; 93 at Providence, R.I.;
93 at Rochester, N.Y., and 95 at Syracuse, N.Y.
   On the same date one year earlier, 32 cities in the central part
of the nation reported record highs.
   Showers fell over the Texas coastal areas and from the Dakotas
across Kansas to western Texas.
   North Dakota, where some fields have been so dry seeds wouldn't
germinate, afternoon temperatures were only in the 50s and 60s with
rain throughout most of the state. Minot got almost an inch of rain.
   Thunderstorms were expected from the upper Mississippi Valley
across sections of the central Plains to western Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Dickinson and Minot, N.D., to 102 at Needles, Calif. The
low for the day was 28 degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.,
and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Michigan across the middle Mississippi Valley, Kansas and
western sections of the southern Plains to the mountains of
Colorado, and over southern Texas and across the Florida Peninsula.
Showers were forecast over the Washington coast, with widely
scattered thunderstorms in the mountains of the Northwest and in
sections of New England.
   Highs in the 60s or 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;
in the 70s from northern Michigan across Minnesota and the Dakotas
to western sections of the central Plains; near 100 over
California's interior valleys and near Texas' Rio Grande Valley;
near 108 in sections of the desert Southwest; and in the 80s to mid
90s over most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
