<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Computers-Convention     06-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computers-Convention,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Computer Tallies, Traditional Roll Call Will Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats are planning to use computers to
tally some of the votes at the party's nominating convention next
month, but officials say the high-tech addition won't upstage the
traditional high point of the convention _ the state-by-state roll
call.
   The party's convention committee is working out the bugs in an
electronic voting system that will allow delegations, using small
computers on the floor, to vote on the party platform and
convention rules. Votes would be displayed on a big overhead screen
behind the podium.
   ``But we will still do the roll call for the president and vice
president in the traditional manner,'' said Ruth Berry, a
spokeswoman for the committee that is planning the July 18-21
convention in Atlanta.
   The state-by-state roll call, in which the head of each
delegation takes the floor to announce the state's votes, ``is a
long-standing tradition,'' she said. ``It's something people expect
and it adds excitement to the convention.''
   Several other high-tech features are being explored by the
convention committee, incuding the electronics to allow delegates
to send messages to other delegates on the floor, computer to
computer, she said.
   The committee also is talking to Southern Bell, which provides
local phone service in Atlanta, about televising convention
activities on closed-circuit, high-definition television monitors
around the convention center and in nearby VIP and hospitality
suites.
   High-definition TV, still in the experimental stage, is
considered the next generation in television, delivering clearer,
brighter images on a screen that is wider than conventional TV sets
and with the sound quality of a compact-disc recording.
   Southern Bell has found eight large-screen, Japanese-made
monitors it can use at the convention but is having trouble finding
more, said Bill McCloskey, a spokesman for BellSouth, the parent
corporation of Southern Bell. Few monitors are available because
the Japanese, leaders in HDTV development, plan to cover the Seoul
Olympics in high definition for a country-wide demonstration in
Japan this summer, he said.
   Southern Bell has put in a 1,063-mile fiber optic network to
handle about 9,000 convention telephone lines that will be used by
an estimated 16,000 reporters, editors and technicians and 14,000
delegates, party representatives and other convention participants.
</TEXT>
