<DOCNO> AP880614-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VDTOverride     06-14 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VDT Override,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Island County Enacts 1st Law To Regulate Terminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first law in the nation to regulate
use of computer terminals in the workplace was enacted Tuesday when
the Suffolk County Legislature overrode the county executive's veto.
   ``It is a happy day for Suffolk County's workforce,'' said
legislator John Foley, who introduced the bill.
   In six months, businesses with more than 20 visual display
terminals will have to provide special treatment for workers who
spend more than 26 hours a week in front of the computer screens:
   _The workers must have 15-minute breaks or a new work assignment
after three hours with a VDT.
   _The employer must pay 80 percent of the cost of annual eye
exams and any eyeglasses that are needed.
   In addition, any equipment purchased after next year must have
such features as non-glare screens, adjustable desks and
five-legged chairs.
   The bill was written in response to worker complaints of
eyestrain, muscle aches and other ill effects from long-term VDT
use.
   Subsequently, California researchers reported that a study found
that women who used VDTs for more than 20 hours a week during the
first three months of preganncy suffered twice the number of
miscarriages of women who rarely used terminals. But the
researchers said they could not determine whether the VDTs or some
other factor such as job stress caused the increased rate.
   County Executive Patrick Halpin vetoed the Suffolk measure on
Friday, saying it would drive businesses away from the eastern Long
Island county.
   ``The new law will cost Suffolk many good high tech jobs,'' he
predicted after Tuesday's vote.
   The 18-member Legislature discussed the bill for about an hour
before voting 13-5 _ one vote more than needed _ to override
Halpin's veto.
   ``The county executive heard what he wanted to hear from big
money, big business and fear,'' said Legislator Rose Caracappa.
   ``Opposition to this bill was based on overreaction,'' charged
legislator Gregory Blass. ``We've heard the doom and gloom from
business in the past,'' when bottle-deposit and anti-smoking bills
were enacted.
   Halpin said he would try ``to implement the law so it will have
minimal impact on the business community.''
   The County Health Department is responsible for enforcing the
new law.
   James LaRocca, president of the Long Island Association, a
business group, predicted the loss of more than 3,000 jobs in
pending expansion and relocation deals.
   Supporters of the bill were the Communications Workers of
America, Civil Service Employees Association, and various women's
groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
