<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0732 06-14 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Blasts Sandinistas for Harassment, Bad Faith Negotiations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: Shultz said, with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with comments by Nicaraguan ambassador. INSERTS 1 graf after 9th
graf pvs, Shultz met, to UPDATE with Contras meeting Powell</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz lashed out
at Nicaraguan authorities on Tuesday, accusing them of reneging on
promises to create democracy and of subjecting Contra negotiators
to harassment and intimidation during talks last week.
   But Shultz, after a meeting with the Contra leadership, declined
to say whether the failure of the peace negotiations between the
leftist Sandinista government and the Contras means the
administration will seek military aid for the rebels.
   Meanwhile, Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann held the
Contras responsible for collapse of the peace talks, contending
they had made ``demands so outlandish and unacceptable'' that they
knew in advance the Sandinista negotiators would reject them.
   In a letter to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, Tunnermann
said that on the last day of the talks, the Contras introduced ``an
entirely new set of demands'' and insisted that the government
accept all of them within two hours.
   ``They virtually presented my government with an ultimatum,''
Tunnermann said.
   Shultz, speaking with reporters, said that in Managua last week,
``the resistance delegation was harassed, initimidated and
subjected to continual abuse, treated virtually as prisoners,
refused permission to meet with democratic political leaders and
threatened with harm by Defense Minister Humberto Ortega if they
refused to sign an agreement.''
   Alfredo Cesar, a member of the Contra directorate, asked to
elaborate on Shultz's allegation, said Ortega at one point
threatened to deny the rebel delegation permission to leave Managua
if the talks broke down.
   ``About 20 minutes later, he (Ortega) said that once the war
started again, the bullets from the Sandinistas will not only be
against our combatants from the mountains but against the people
sitting across this table,'' Cesar said.
   Shultz, blaming the Sandinistas for the breakdown of the talks,
said their actions have shown the world ``that their promises of
democratization have no counterpart in concrete action.
   ``Their consistent and apparent goal has been to disarm and
eliminate the resistance so that they can proceed to consolidate
their rule in Nicaragua,'' Sultz said.
   ``Their kind of rule in Nicaragua will never be accepted as
legitimate by the United States. We will stick with the resistance
freedom fighters. Their cause of peace with freedom is the right
cause.''
   It was not clear what Shultz meant when he raised questions
about the legitimacy of the Sandinista government because the
United States has always been represented in Managua by an
ambassador since the start of the 1979 revolution.
   Shultz met with Cesar and two other members of the Contra
directorate on Tuesday along with the rebels' military commander,
Col. Enrique Bermudez, as part of an assessment of future options.
   The Contra leaders met into the dinner hour at the White House
with national security adviser Colin Powell. There was no immediate
indication of what transpired in that meeting.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., has recommended a $105 million package
of military and humanitarian aid for the Contras, and Contra leader
Adolfo Calero has indicated support for that proposal.
   The Contras have received no military aid since Feb. 29. But
Congress has approved assistance for the purchase of food, shelter,
medical supplies and clothing. The administration's last request
for military aid was rejected by the House on Feb. 3.
   The rebels will confer Wednesday with members of Congress about
possible future steps.
   House Republican leader Bob Michel of Illinois said Contra aid
was discussed at a meeting of GOP congressional leaders with
President Reagan on Tuesday, but no decisions were reached.
   Michel said he expects a push for renewal of humanitarian aid.
Asked about the prospect of military aid, he said, ``I don't think,
quite frankly, there has been the kind of dramatic movement either
way that would indicate we would change any votes in Congress.''
</TEXT>
