<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceStation     06-14 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Station,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Defers Some Space Station Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Appropriations Committee voted
Tuesday to let the next president decide whether to fund
construction of a space station.
   Under the bill approved by the committee, $387 million would be
available for research and development between Oct. 1, when the
next fiscal year begins, and April 15, when the next president
would have to decide whether to continue with the space station.
   Another $65.4 million would be held in an account, and should
the president decide not to proceed further, those funds would be
used to shut down the program.
   Additionally, $450 million would be held through April 15. If
the new president decided to continue with the program, the money
would go to the space station. If he decided against the space
station, $150 million would be transferred to Space Flight Control
and Data Communications at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. The remaining $300 million would be rescinded.
   Under the bill, the new president would have to let Congress
know between Feb. 1 and April 15 of his intentions to continue with
the space station.
   ``If it's (Democrat Michael) Dukakis, it could be the end of the
space station,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``The guy is a
northern liberal. This is set up to pit domestic spending against
defense spending....
   DeLay, whose Houston-area district borders Johnson Space Center,
said about half of the station would be built in Houston.
   ``The Russians have already gotten their space station up,'' he
said. ``They're going to beat us on technology and industrial
development through a space station. The future is right there and
we're way behind.''
   He said construction of the space station could begin next year
if it stays on schedule. The original bill, before it was amended
Tuesday, called for a $902 million appropriation, which officials
said was just enough to keep the program on schedule.
   The space station is planned to be in orbit around Earth and
occupied by astronauts at the end of 1996. A year before that it
would be available for periodic visits by astronauts.
</TEXT>
