<HEAD>West Bank Schools Ordered Closed For Two Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army ordered West Bank schools closed for
two days, trying to head off student protests during a general
strike called for Wednesday by underground leaders of the
6-month-old Palestinian rebellion.
   Schools in the West Bank were closed for four months and
students held violent demonstrations after high schools reopened
this week. The two-day closing Wednesday and Thursday was intended
as a warning to students that they may be shut again if violence
continues.
   New army figures said dozens of Israeli soldiers have been
convicted of or charged with excessive use of force and other
violations of regulations since the uprising began Dec. 8 in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The figures also showed the number of Arabs detained without
charges, which permits them to be held for up to six months,
increasing by one-fifth since May, to 2,500. Most are young
activists.
   Civil rights workers criticized Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
statement to the Cabinet this week that Israeli civilians who see
Arabs holding firebombs would be allowed to shoot them.
   ``This is giving the green light for shooting and killing
without justification,'' lawyer Amnon Zichroni said. ``This will
lead to counterattacks from Palestinians. It's a vicious cycle
without end.''
   At least 207 Palestinieguards our freedoms and underpins the development
of
the West.''
   ``The prospects for a lasting peace require us to prevent any
weakening of our Atlantic solidarity, to refrain from any actions
of unilateral disarmament,'' he said.
   De Mita said later at a news conference that a disagreement over
Middle East policy was aired during his talks with administration
officials.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz is trying to arrange
negotiations between Israel and a delegation of Jordanians and
Palestinians. He has ruled out participation by the Palestine
Liberation Organization unless it accepts Israel's right to exist,
as well as creation of a Palestinian state.
   De Mita said he told the Americans that Italy continues to
believe the PLO is the legitimate representative of the Palestinian
people.
   One of the topics expected to arise at the Toronto summit is the
extent to which the industrialized democracies should help Eastern
European nations solve their economic problems.
   De Mita said he and the president agreed that massive aid for
these countries should be withheld as long as their economies are
predominantly state-managed.
   De Mita planned to meet on Wednesday with members of Congress
and Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci before making a private
visit to Bar Harbor, Maine.
