<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviets-Latvia     06-14 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Latvia,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Latvians March in Memory of Those Deported by Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people joined a march in the Latvian
capital of Riga Tuesday in memory of Latvians deported from the
republic when it was occupied by Soviet forces before and after
World War II, Tass reported.
   The official Soviet news agency said the march was sanctioned by
Soviet officials and ``many thousands'' of people participated.
   It reported Latvian historian Jan Riekstins addressed a rally
and quoted him as saying: ``We justifiably condemn the policy of
cruelty.''
   Last year a similar demonstration was allowed by Soviet
authorities without interference and Latvian activists said 5,000
people took part.
   The fact that this year's march was officially sanctioned
appeared linked to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
more open reporting of the wrongs conducted under the dictatorship
of Josef Stalin, who died in 1953.
   Latvian activists had said Tuesday's demonstration was called
``to prevent the return of Stalinist and neo-Stalinist crimes
against the people and in the further unwavering forward course of
M. Gorbachev's restructuring,'' according to Ojars Kalnins of the
World Federation of Free Latvians in Washington.
   Tass quoted Riga Mayor Alfred Rudiks as saying the government of
the republic had ``approved the initiative of young people to build
in Riga a monument to victims of Stalin's personality cult.''
   Official Soviet historians say 31,000 people were deported from
Lativa after it was occupied by the Soviet army in 1940 and in
1949. The last occupation came after Germany had been defeated and
the Soviets were in the process of annexing Latvia and the
neighboring Baltic republics of Lithuania and Estonia. Germany had
seized the republics during the war.
   Tass said many of the deportation victims were Nazi sympathizers.
   ``Apart from those who were deservedly punished for acts of
political sabotage, collaboration with fascists, banditism and
espionage, the deportees also included innocent people,'' the
agency said.
   It had harsh words for one of the march organizers, Edmund
Cirvilis, calling him ``a former Nazi soldier who was sent to
Latvia on a terrorist mission in 1945.''
   Repeated attempts to reach Latvian activists in Riga by
telephone were unsuccessful.
   There was no word on a demonstration planned Tuesday in
Lithuania. Various reports say 36,000 Lithuanians were deported in
1941 and 200,000 in 1948.
   Last month, Soviet police broke up a demonstration by 5,000
Lithuanians marking the anniversary of the 1949 deportations,
according to Lithuanian activists.
   The United States has never officially recognized the Soviet
claim to the Baltic republics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     06-14 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Labor Official Quits Over Nuclear Weapons Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Labor Party official resigned Tuesday in
a dispute over whether the party should modify its controversial
pledge to abandon Britain's nuclear weapons and shut down U.S.
nuclear bases.
   Legislator Denzil Davies, the party's parliamentary spokesman on
defense, said the ``last straw'' was a recent statement by party
leader Neil Kinnock that Labor's unilateral nuclear disarmament
policy is outmoded.
   ``I am fed up with being humiliated by Mr. Kinnock,'' said
Davies, 49.
   ``He never consults me on anything ... I cannot get up in the
House of Commons and make a speech when Mr. Kinnock says all sorts
of things all over the place, one thing one day and another the
next _ and he is supposed to be the future prime minister.''
   Kinnock said he was amazed and sad that Davies, a fellow
Welshman and longtime senior figure in the opposition party, had
quit. Kinnock later named Martin O'Neill, a legislator since 1970,
to replace Davies.
   Davies' resignation, announced in statement, highlighted a
widening split as Kinnock pushes Labor back toward the center in
what he sees as the socialists' only hope of ousting Conservative
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at the next election. It must be
held by 1992.
   Kinnock, 46, a lifelong anti-nuclear campaigner, angered Labor
left-wingers when he said in a June 5 television interview there
was ``no need now for something-for-nothing unilateralism'' because
the superpowers had broken the impasse by singing an accord
scrapping intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   ``We would be complete fools, whatever our politics, to ignore
the scope and scale of the change and the opportunities and
responsibilities that go with trying to be part of that change,''
Kinnock said of U.S.-Soviet agreements.
   Tony Benn, an ex-Cabinet minister and leading leftist who will
challenge Kinnock for the leadership at the party conference in the
fall, said Davies' resignation confirmed ``there is unhappiness
across the whole party about the way things are going.''
   The Conservatives were jubilant at the renewed public outbreak
of fighting among the Laborites over the anti-nuclear policy, which
polls show is a major vote-loser. ``The job of defense spokesman in
today's Labor Party is an impossible one,'' commented Mrs.
Thatcher's armed forces minister Ian Stewart.
   ``The choice is between a policy of unilateral disarmament,
which makes Labor unelectable, or a policy of realism, which is
unacceptable to large sections of the Labor Party,'' he said.
   Kinnock has denied dumping the non-nuclear pledge, which the
party first adopted as official policy in 1982, three years after
losing power to Mrs. Thatcher. But the June 5 interview was his
strongest indication that a Labor government would use Britain's
nuclear weapons as a bargaining chip in arms control talks with the
Soviets, rather than simply scrap them on principle.
   The current policy calls also for closing U.S. nuclear bases in
Britain.
   In the House of Commons on Tuesday, Mrs. Thatcher reiterated her
opposition to including Trident missiles in arms control talks,
noting it was the equivalent of three percent of the Soviet arsenal.
   ``There is no point ... in giving up 100 percent of our Trident
for the Soviet Union giving up 3 percent of her strategic
weapons,'' she said.
   Polls indicate that while a majority of Britons oppose having
U.S. nuclear weapons in this country, many also believe Britain
should remain a nuclear power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
