<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0737 06-14 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0737,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: Stop SDI, Emphasize Conventional Forces</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs Bush comment after 3rd graf pvs; edits to
tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis promised on Tuesday to replace
the Reagan administration's Strategic Defense Initiative with a
``Conventional Defense Initiative'' to help defend Europe against
Soviet attack.
   The all-but-certain Democratic presidential nominee, in a major
defense and foreign policy speech, also said the federal budget
situation means it is time ``to make tough choices on defense.'' He
denied that he was tipping his hand to the Soviets by announcing
opposition to the MX and Midgetman missiles.
   Dukakis declared a strong commitment to NATO and outlined a
step-by-step plan for reducing the risk of war in Europe. In a
reference to the Soviet Union and its allies, he said that to
eliminate the possibility of a surprise attack ``we have to have
greater reductions from the side with the most forces, the Warsaw
Pact.''
   Vice President George Bush, for his part, denounced Dukakis as
``wrong, wrong'' for opposing SDI and the MX missile.
   ``He's wrong twice,'' the vice president told reporters in
Washington.
   On another foreign policy subject, Dukakis appeared
uncomfortable with his party's plan to label South Africa a
terrorist state in its platform, as his own representatives agreed
at a platform drafting session Sunday in Mackinac Island, Mich.
   ``I tend to resist labels generally because I don't know exactly
what they mean,'' said Dukakis.
   But Madeleine Albright, his foreign policy adviser, said later
that Dukakis was ``very comfortable'' with the evolving platform,
and ``there is absolutely no distancing himself from what was
said'' at the drafting session.
   In his speech at the State Department before a pro-NATO group
called the Atlantic Council, Dukakis said, ``We've got to be very
tough on South Africa. Constructive engagement's a failure. ...
South Africa is not only engaging in blatant racism against its own
people and in terrorist acts; it's committing naked military
agression against its neighbors all over southern Africa.''
   Dukakis also said that if President Reagan can achieve an
agreement with the Soviets on long-range missiles in the closing
months of 1988, ``I strongly urge the administration to go for it
and I hope they do.''
   He declared his commitment to ``a NATO so strong and so united
that no nation will be tempted to begin a war against us.'' But he
also said the European allies must bear a greater share of the
common defense burden.
   ``NATO has worked for 40 years. It can work for 40 more _ if our
allies do their share and if we stop trying to go it alone as we
have done too often during the past seven years,'' he said.
   ``We all know that the defense budget isn't going to increase in
real terms, unless an emergency arises, no matter who the next
president is, he said. ``The time has come to make tough choices on
defense.''
   ``We don't need SDI; we need CDI, the Conventional Defense
Initiative begun by leaders in the Congress to apply advanced
technology to the challenge of fighting and winning a conventional
war,'' he said. The Strategic Defense Initiative is the
administration's proposed space-based missile-defense system, still
in the research stage.
   ``We don't need MX missiles running around on railroad cars. We
need an anti-tank weapon that can stop Soviet tanks.''
   Asked why he would announce in advance that he opposes such
mobile weapons as the MX and Midgetman missiles, Dukakis denied
that he was giving the Soviets an advantage at the bargaining
table. He said modernizing the U.S. nuclear arsenal was ``an open
question.''
   Later Tuesday, after returning to Massachusetts, Dukakis
denounced Reagan for allowing Coast Guard budget cuts that he said
have hampered the war on drugs.
   Dukakis held a meeting with Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., and
leaders of a regional drug taks force aboard the Coast Guard cutter
Vigilant, and he said the commander told him the ship would remain
at the docks for the next several months because of the cuts.
   ``This is our first line of defense,'' Dukakis said. ``It
doesn't make any sense. ... We need them.''
   In Washington, he called for persuading the Soviets ``to
withdraw some of their advanced armored equipment from Eastern
Europe and to withdraw bridging equipment from their forward-based
divisions.''
   He also called for talks ``to eliminate the threat of chemical
warfare not only in Europe, but throughout the world.''
   ``But while we negotiate, we must strengthen the alliance as
well, beginning with our conventional forces,'' Dukakis said.
   ``The commanders of our armed forces have repeatedly warned us
of the dangers we face. Maintenance backlogs are growing. We have
serious shortfalls in airlift and sealift, in spare parts and
ammunition,'' he said.
</TEXT>
