<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Taxes     06-14 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taxes,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Chairman Says Bill To Give Diesel Fuel Tax Relief To
Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee said Tuesday his panel will begin writing a tax bill next
week that will include relief for farmers from the tax on diesel
fuel.
   ``I'm encouraged,'' the chairman, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
said after separate meetings with Democrats and Republicans on his
panel.
   The bill likely would be the only tax legislation that has a
chance of passing Congress this year. The main purpose of the bill
would be correcting errors in the 1986 tax overhaul, but the
committee could attach to the bill any of dozens of other tax
provisions that have been proposed.
   However, the number of successful amendments is likely to be
small this year because of budget agreements requiring that any
provision cutting taxes be offset by another that raises revenues.
   Most such amendments usually are added when a tax bill goes
through the Senate. But Rostenkowski said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, chairman of the Finance Committee, is ``encouraged that he
can hold a very well disciplined bill together on the floor of the
Senate'' _ that is, that he could protect it against serious
amendment.
   ``That's encouraging to me,'' Rostenkowski told reporters.
   Rostenkowski acknowledged that any bill will include a popular
provision to excuse farmers and state and local governments from a
new law requiring them to pay taxes on their purchases of diesel
fuel and then apply to the treasury for a rebate. The Finance
Committee already has voted to repeal the requirement.
   The chairman said there is considerable support on his committee
for extending some tax breaks that have expired or are scheduled to
end later this year. These include a tax exemption for revenue
bonds that help first-time homebuyers; a credit for increased
research and development, and a tax credit that encourages
employers to hire the poor.
   Because of budget restrictions, Rostenkowski said, any extension
of expiring provisions likely would be limited to one or two years.
   The chairman indicated there may not be enough support on the
committee to toughen the tax on unrelated business income of
organizations that generally are tax-exempt. Some lawmakers,
striving to help small business against unfair competition, have
called for taxation of such income, including that from
universities' sale of computers and non-profit hospitals' newstands.
   Any tax bill that is debated this year is likely to face
amendment by lawmakers who want to reduce the tax on capital gains,
which are profits from the sale of stocks, land and other assets.
   This issue is complicated by the fact that advocates of a
reduction _ including Vice President George Bush _ contend such a
move would increase tax collections by encouraging investment.
Opponents deny it.
   Another hot issue is a ``taxpayer bill of rights,'' aimed at
curbing alleged excesses of the Internal Revenue Service. The
Finance Committee has approved a version but Ways and Means
Committee members have been cool to the idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
