<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NMWildfires     06-14 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NM Wildfires,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Continue Battling Wildfires in New Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters contained a wildfire that scorched nearly 500 acres
Tuesday and battled to control several smaller fires sparked by
lightning in southwestern New Mexico in recent days.
   The biggest fire burned at least 475 acres of grass and
woodland, including pinon, juniper and ponderosa pine trees, on
U.S. Bureau of Land Management land, officials said.
   The blaze, located on Pelona Mountain about 110 miles southwest
of Albuquerque, was contained after about 175 firefighters cut a
fire line with hand tools, said Ron Dunton, state fire management
officer for the BLM in Santa Fe.
   The blaze, which was first reported Saturday afternoon, was one
of at least 25 reported since Friday, when a storm moved through
the area.
   Many of the fires were small and did not burn long, said George
Ewan of the U.S. Forest Service. All were triggered by lightning,
he said.
   Ray Polasky, operations bureau chief for the state Forestry
Division, said a 70-acre fire on Luera Peak about 60 miles
southwest of Socorro was expected to be controlled, or effectively
extinguished, by Tuesday evening. The fire's spread was contained
Monday.
   The fire started Saturday and burned ponderosa pine trees on
Forest Service and private land.
   Elsewhere, a fire burned about 30 acres at Shaw Canyon, between
the Pelona Mountain and Luera Peak blazes, and another fire in
Whitewater Canyon in the Gila National Forest blackened at least 15
acres, according to Willie Zapata, Forest Service relief dispatcher
in Silver City. More than 50 firefighters battled the two blazes.
   Crews also fought two smaller fires covering about 2 acres each
in the Gila forest near the Arizona border, Zapata said.
   In addition, firefighters monitored four small fires covering
less than one-tenth of an acre each in the Sacramento Mountains in
south-central New Mexico, said Ed Wood, Forest Service public
information officer.
</TEXT>
