<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AshlandTrial     06-14 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ashland Trial,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland to Appeal $70 Million Award to Two Former Vice Presidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. says it will appeal a
nearly $70 million award to two former vice presidents who claimed
they were illegally fired for refusing to bribe foreign officials
or cover up such bribes.
   A U.S. District Court jury Friday awarded Bill McKay $44,594,936
and Harry D. Williams $24,980,431.
   Ashland, in a prepared statement, said it was ``very
disappointed by the verdict,'' which it said was not supported by
the evidence, and planned to appeal.
   The company maintained throughout the trial that payments to
secure Arab oil during the 1970s and 1980s went to men of influence
who were not government officials.
   The jury decided that three of the men were government officials
when they were paid and that at least two cases of bribery
occurred, putting the case under the Racketeering Influence
Corruption Act (RICO), a federal law usually aimed at organized
crime.
   Ashlandm also maintained the men were fired for ineffective work
and claimed the plaintiffs conspired to get fired in order to sue
Ashland.
   The jury's decision came after a 35-day trial. Named as
defendants were the company, former chairman Orin Atkins, current
chairman John R. Hall, vice chairman Robert McCowan and vice
president Dick Spears.
</TEXT>
