<DOCNO> AP880614-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Extradition     06-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Extradition,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ireland To Appeal Failed Extradition Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it will
appeal an Irish court's release of a man wanted in Britain on
bombing charges. The ruling struck a blow to the new British-Irish
extradition agreement.
   In London, British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher blamed Irish
officials for losing the extradition case and said the two
governments were holding ``urgent consultations.'' It was Britain's
first extradition attempt under the agreement signed Dec. 1.
   Patrick McVeigh, 37, was freed Monday after a district court
ruled the Irish government had not properly established his
identity and said British police failed to produce witnesses that
could identify the suspect.
   Britain sought his extradition to face charges in connection
with explosions between 1981 and 1983 in London that killed two
people outside Chelsea Barracks and a bomb disposal expert in
Oxford Street.
   Mrs. Thatcher told the House of Commons: ``The Crown Prosecution
Service have done everything they could. ... They expressly asked
whether further evidence from the United Kingdom on identification
was needed and was told it was not.''
   Irish Justice Minister John Murray, addressing the Parliament in
Dublin, said the government was ``very deeply concerned'' by the
case and will appeal to the High Court.
   He said British officials had told Irish authorities that no
British police officer was ``in a position to make a personal
identification of Patrick McVeigh as the person concerned in the
alleged offense.''
   But he said the British officials were told further evidence of
identification was not required because the information given to
the court to identify the suspect as McVeigh was in accordance with
established norms.
   McVeigh, from Belfast, Northern Ireland, was arrested May 18 as
he left Portlaoise prison outside Dublin after serving five years
of a seven-year sentence for arms offenses linked to the Irish
Republican Army, outlawed in both Britain and Ireland.
   McVeigh was seized only days after the British and Irish
governments settled legal differences that had prevented any
extradition efforts this year under the new pact. Britain and
Ireland agreed to make positive identification a chief factor in
extradition.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to unite Northern
Ireland, a British province where Protestants outnumber Catholics
3-2, with the predomidnantly Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
