<DOCNO> AP880614-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0719 06-14 0911</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0719,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks Defense, Bush Differs; VP Selection Getting Serious</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs Bush reax to Dukakis speech; picks up 2nd
graf pvs, bgng: Meanwhile, the; new graf 25, bgng: ``We don't, with
Dukakis MX comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis declared in a speech on defense Tuesday
that ``we don't need SDI,'' while Republican George Bush retorted
that Dukakis is ``wrong, wrong'' for opposing the Strategic Defense
Initiative and the MX missile.
   ``He's wrong twice,'' the vice president told reporters in
Washington.
   Bush concentrated on education, proposing a new $500 million
program to reward schools that improve their performance in
educating disadvantaged children.
   Meanwhile, the Boston lawyer in charge of Dukakis' search for a
running mate conferred with Democratic congressional and party
leaders, and a new poll indicated the Massachusetts governor still
holds a big lead over Bush as the summer conventions near.
   Jesse Jackson, in Salt Lake City to address the nation's mayors,
continued to insist he has earned the right to consideration for
the vice presidency, though he didn't say he would accept it if
offered.
   Not only did he do well in the Democratic primaries, he said,
but ``I have an expertise in third world relations that the nation
needs.'' He added, ``The black constituency has earned the
consideration.''
   Dukakis, in a speech to the Atlantic Council in Washington,
called for a shift in emphasis to conventional forces as the key to
defense of Europe and said that if President Reagan can reach an
agreement with the Soviet Union on long-range missiles ``I strongly
urge the administration to go for it.''
   Education was the topic for the Republican vice president, who
called for a $500 million program to reward schools that come up
with innovative programs to help disadvantaged students.
   Dukakis campaign spokesman Leslie Dach said Paul Brountas, a
close friend and adviser to the Massachusetts governor, was
conferrring with leading Democrats in Washington and ``asking them
for their thoughts'' on the vice presidential selection process.
   Dach said Brountas would meet with House and Senate leaders as
well as other key elected and party officials.
   Then, the spokesman said, the plan is for Brountas and Dukakis
to ``get together and have a conversation about what they've both
heard about names and ideas on how to go forward and then go on
from there.''
   Dach refused to identify people with whom Brountas was meeting.
An aide to Sen. John Glenn of Ohio, one of the people mentioned
most often as a potential Dukakis running mate, said Brountas had
asked the senator for a meeting. Brountas was also to meet with
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
   Also Tuesday, a new Gallup poll found 52 percent support for
Dukakis and 38 percent for Bush. The same poll a month ago gave
Dukakis a 54-38 lead.
   Two other recent polls had single-digit leads for Dukakis, 49-44
in a Harris poll conducted June 1-6 and 45-39 in a USA Today-CNN
poll June 7-9.
   The newest poll was conducted by Gallup for the Boston Globe and
Boston television stations WEEI and WCVB June 10-12 among 1,005
registered voters. It had a margin of sampling error of four
percentage points.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, who dropped out of the
Democratic presidential race after the New York primary, planned to
endorse Dukakis on Thursday in Nashville, Tenn., as the governor
opened a Southern campaign swing.
   Gore, whose name also is on many observers' vice presidential
lists, planned to fly to Boston on Wednesday and then go to
Tennesse with Dukakis. Before going to Boston, Gore also had a
meeting scheduled in his Senate office with Jackson.
   Bush spoke to a Washington luncheon honoring 139 Presidential
Scholars, some of the nation's top high school seniors.
   ``I believe the best thing we can do is invest in our young
people,'' said the vice president.
   Bush called for rewarding schools ``that significantly improve
their performance'' serving disadvantaged students.
   ``Let the states determine the criteria for improvement,'' he
said. ``Each school meeting the criteria would be recognized as a
National Merit School.''
   The vice president said such schools would receive federal
grants averaging $100,000.
   ``Each winning school could use the money as it pleased _ for
lab equipment, library books or rewards for teachers and
principals,'' he said.
   Speaking to the Atlantic Council meeting at the State
Department, Dukakis said, ``We all know that the defense budget
isn't going to increase in real terms unless an emergency arises,
no matter who the next president is. ... The time has come to make
tough choices on defense.''
   ``We don't need MX missiles running around on railroad cars. We
need an anti-tank weapon that can stop Soviet tanks,'' he said.
   Referring to Reagan's proposal for a space-based missile defense
system, Dukakis said, ``We don't need SDI; we need CDI, the
Conventional Defense Initiative begun by leaders of the Congress to
apply advanced technology to the challenge of fighting and winning
a conventional war.''
   Dukakis also said he did not believe the recently approved
treaty to remove U.S. and Soviet medium-range missiles from Europe
meant a lessening of the U.S. commitment to defense of the
continent.
   ``I don't buy that at all,'' he said. ``Our commitment to Europe
goes far beyond a few hundred missiles.''
   But he also called for European allies to pay a greater share of
the burden of maintaining military strength in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
