<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     06-14 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Advance on Afghanistan's Second-Largest City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas have punched
through defenses of Afghanistan's second-largest city and delayed
Soviet troop withdrawal, Western diplomatic sources said Tuesday.
   The sources, speaking on condition their names not be used, said
the guerrillas have penetrated the defenses of Kandahar, a
provincial capital of 20,000 people about 270 miles southwest of
Kabul, Afghanistan's capital.
   One diplomatic source, quoting a Kandahar resident, said
guerrillas have been entering the city's bazaars daily to hunt
communist military and government personnel.
   The diplomatic sources also said fighting there and the Afghan
army garrison at Spin Buldak had slowed the Soviets' pullout from
Kandahar province and increased speculation they may reinforce the
area with additional troops. Spin Buldak is 60 miles southeast
Kandahar, on the Pakistani border.
   Reports indicate the main areas of combat, in addition to
Kandahar and Kabul, are at Ghazni to the south, Khost to the east
and Baghlan city to the north near the Soviets' main withdrawal
route.
   Pakistani sources say the guerrillas have taken the offensive
this spring, capturing more than 25 towns and communist posts in
the last three months.
   However, the diplomatic sources said Moscow's overall withdrawal
from the country was continuing, with convoys last weekend heading
north through Kabul from the eastern garrisons of Ghazni and Gardez.
   They agreed with Kremlin figures that 13,000 Red Army troops
have crossed the Oxus River onto home territory since the
nine-month pullout began May 15 under an accord negotiated in
Geneva.
   Afghanistan's Marxist president, Najib, said at the United
Nations last week that 34,000 Soviets had left _ about a third of
the more than 100,000 Soviets in Afghanistan.
   In Moscow Tuesday, a Foreign Ministry official said Soviet
troops on their way out of Afghanistan will strike back at Moslem
guerrillas who attack.
   Vadim I. Kuznetsov, deputy head of the ministry's U.S. desk,
said that under the Geneva withdrawal accords, ``our troops were
not supposed to take part in combat as they withdraw. Now they can.
Obviously, they are going to defend themselves.''
   Kuznetsov told The Associated Press there had been casualties,
but that he was unable to give the extact time, place and extent of
the attacks.
   His remarks were the most detailed explanation of a warning
issued Monday by Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Najib that
violations of the accord would bring ``resolute retaliatory steps.''
   Soviet troops came to Afghanistan in 1979 to bolster the
communist government.
   The Indian Embassy, which already closed its missions in
Kandahar and the eastern city of Jalalabad, has begun evacuating
personnel from Kabul, according to the source.
   That report appeared to contradict assertions this week by
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi that survival prospects for
Najib's government were good.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
