<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Riot     06-14 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Riot,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extradition Hearing For West German Suspect Sparks Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch riot police battled West
German and Dutch demonstrators outside a courthouse in Amsterdam on
Tuesday where a suspect in the murder of two West German policemen
was fighting extradition.
   A running street battle began during a hearing on the
extradition of 25-year-old Frank Hoffmann to West Germany.
   Hoffmann, a West German citizen, denies involvement in the Nov.
2 shootings, which occurred during a demonstration against building
a new runway at Frankfurt's Rhein-Main Airport.
   Hoffmann wore a leg restraint during the hearing.
   Defense attorney Pieter Bakker Schut argued that the killings
were political crimes, for which Dutch law bans extradition.
   Public prosecutor M. Bonn conceded the two killings were
``politically influenced'' but argued they could not be regarded as
political crimes.
   A ruling on the extradition request is set for June 28.
   At least eight protesters were arrested in the fighting outside,
said police spokesman Leo Detering. Police used baton charges to
disperse about 100 protesters, many of them masked to avoid
identification.
   Dozens of flak-jacketed police stood guard inside and outside
the courthouse and four armed guards were detailed to Hoffman.
   Aside from those directly involved in the proceedings, only
reporters were allowed inside the courtroom. About 30 Hoffmann
sympathizers watched from a public gallery separated from the
courtroom by bullet-proof glass.
   West German authorities say Hoffmann shot the West German
officers with a police service pistol he stole during the protest.
He also is charged with the attempted murder of two other policemen
during the protest.
   West Germany also wants Hoffmann for alleged membership in an
unspecified ``terrorist organization'' and for attacks against
property in protests against West Germany's nuclear energy program.
   Hoffmann denied involvement in all instances. He grinned at his
sympathizers and yelled ``Rebellion! Resistance!'' as police
hustled him out of the courtroom at the end of the hearing.
</TEXT>
