<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MechamTrial     06-14 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham Trial,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Held in Mecham Criminal Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Mecham's defense lawyer told a jury
Tuesday the former governor is being unjustly prosecuted by a
politically ambitious attorney general whose aides are ``like the
guards at Auschwitz.''
   ``The prosecution wants a conviction in this case ...
notwithstanding the innocence of these defendants,'' lawyer Michael
Scott said in closing arguments in Maricopa County Superior Court.
   Prosecutor Michael Cudahy insisted Mecham and his brother,
Willard, purposely concealed a $350,000 campaign loan from
developer Barry Wolfson on financial reports required by the state.
   ``Evan Mecham never had any intention of disclosing the Wolfson
loan,'' Cudahy said.
   The prosecution was scheduled to finish its rebuttal Wednesday
morning before the case is submitted to the jury for deliberations.
   ``I'm glad this day is here,'' Mecham, 64, told reporters before
the arguments began. ``I want to get it over with. I want to get on
with my life.''
   Scott told the jurors that there was no motive to conceal
Wolfson as the source of the loan because the campaign's financial
reports were filed after the November 1986 election.
   The defense lawyer said Mecham could have been charged with a
misdemeanor for false campaign finance reporting, ``but a
misdemeanor is not good enough for (Attorney General) Bob Corbin
and his henchmen.''
   Corbin wanted a conviction on felony charges to further his own
political ambitions, but he is ``not entitled to bring home Evan
Mecham's scalp and hang it in the trophy room at the attorney
general's office,'' Scott said.
   ``Perhaps I shouldn't be so hard on my colleagues because, like
the guards at Auschwitz, they're just doing their job,'' he said,
referring to the prosecutors.
   Auschwitz was a Nazi death camp.
   In his rebuttal, co-prosecutor Barnett Lotstein accused Scott of
making a ``vicious personal attack'' on him and Cudahy. ``It's not
a new tactic. It's used when you don't have anything else to say,''
Lotstein said.
   Cudahy said Mecham desperately needed money for his 1986
gubernatorial campaign, which had a theme of integrity and
abolishing special interests.
   ``Along came a pot of gold in the form of Barry Wolfson, and
Evan Mecham wound up selling that theme of integrity and ridding
the state of hidden special interests when he and Willard Mecham
decided to hide from the public the $350,000 loan,'' Cudahy said.
   Cudahy said testimony showed that even some of Mecham's top
aides and people who signed promissory notes to back the loan were
not told it was coming from Wolfson and not from a bank.
   The loan was hidden on a campaign financial report as part of a
``fabricated'' $465,000 lump sum listed as a contribution from
Mecham, Cudahy said. He also pointed to a letter in which Mecham
promised Wolfson the loan would ``remain confidential.''
   Scott contended that the loan was properly reported as part of
the $465,000 lump sum because Mecham was responsible for its
repayment.
   Mecham was charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents and faced up to 22 years in
prison if convicted.
   Willard Mecham, who was his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer,
faced three similar counts and up to 9{ years in prison if
convicted.
   Mecham, a Republican, took office in January 1987 and was
removed April 4 when the state Senate convicted him of two
unrelated charges.
</TEXT>
