<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Children'sHome     06-14 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fountain Doesn't Want to Be Bailed Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fundamentalist operator of an
unlicensed boarding school closed by the state amid allegations of
abuse and neglect said Tuesday he didn't want supporters to bail
him out of jail.
   ``I don't want the people to put the money up for this _ not
when we're right,'' the Rev. Herman Fountain said.
   Fountain spoke after an appearance before a Youth Court judge
trying to decide the cases of 41 children taken last week by court
order from the Bethel Home for Children in Lucedale. He was held in
the George County jail in lieu of $40,000 bond on three charges of
felonious assault of a police officer.
   Meanwhile, $1,000 bonds were posted by two other people arrested
Monday, when 60 state troopers and local officers raided a church
on the 28-acre campus of the school. A June 24 court date was set
for the two.
   They were among five people, including assistant pastor David
Owens, who were charged with disorderly conduct when the church was
raided Monday.
   Since Friday, the state has taken 77 children from the home,
with about 35 released to their parents.
   Officers entered the church to look for three children Fountain
said he had taken back in. But Fountain said Tuesday the three
weren't among 11 children taken by the state in the Monday raid.
   State officials said they took all of the children because
church officials refused to identify for them the three they were
looking for.
   Fountain said Tuesday that he knew where the three were, but
wouldn't disclose their location, which he said wasn't on the
campus.
   ``If they are going to take these kids to the mental hospital, I
ain't going to have no part of it,'' Fountain said.
   The children turned over to the state temporarily were being
housed at the state psychiatric hospital at Whitfield.
   Fountain said he had heard that the children in state custody
were being allowed to smoke and play rock music.
   ``That really upsets me,'' he said.
   Asked about discipline methods at his school, which have come
under fire off and on since 1980, Foutain claimed only God can set
the limits but that he and staffers had guidelines.
   No more than 10 licks with a switch were allowed, he said. Asked
the kind of paddle or switch used, he said: ``An old mamma's switch
_ like the one you pick up in the woods.''
   Chancery Judge Robert Oswald, who presides over the youth court,
continued hearings at which he required parents or guardians to
promise not to send the children back to Bethel. He ruled that the
children, ages 10 to 17, had been subjected ``to physical abuse,
medical neglect and detention amounting to imprisonment'' at Bethel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
