<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0806 06-14 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0806,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Claims Thousands of Iraqi Casualties; Iraq Says New Front
Opened</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new details from both sides.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq claimed Tuesday that it recaptured
five strategic heights in new battles on the northern front while
Iran reported that the Iraqis suffered 19,000 casualties in their
southern offensive.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi forces backed by
helicopter gunships and fighter planes stormed Iranian-held
positions in northern Iraq to win back the heights.
   It said artillery, tank and infantry units joined in retaking
five Iranian positions in the mountain peaks of Suliamaniya
province, but It did not say when the offensive started or how long
it lasted.
   Iranian news reports made no mention of fighting in the north.
Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian forces killed or
wounded 19,000 Iraqis after launching a new offensive east of Basra
in southern Iraq on Monday.
   The various reports were monitored in Nicosia. Claims by the
opposing sides could not be independently verified as both
countries rarely allow independent observers near the 730-mile
front. The war began in September 1980.
   The Iranian military communique said more than 1,500 Iraqis were
killed or wounded Tuesday and that Iran's heavy artillery destroyed
tanks, personnel carriers and other vehicles.
   Iran also claimed that Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical weapons
on a village in Kurdistan province at 8 a.m. Tuesday, killing two
villagers and ``poisoning'' 10 others, according to IRNA.
   Iraq's official news agency said Tuesday that Iran's attack in
the southern zone was contained and Iraqi troops counterattacked.
   Iraq protested to the United Nations on Tuesday, saying
sanctions should be imposed against Iran for attacks on Iraqi
territory.
   In the Persian Gulf, Iranian gunboats riddled a
Singapore-flagged tanker with machine-gun fire as the ``tanker
war'' flared anew in northern waters that were relatively quiet for
months.
   Gulf-based shipping executives said the 87,768-ton Neptune
Subaru was attacked about 6 a.m. as it sailed toward Kuwait to pick
up a cargo of crude oil.
   The executives said no casualties were reported, the crew
extinguished several fires, and the ship sailed under its own power
to the Saudi Arabian port of Jubail.
   Iranian television on Tuesday quoted Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker
of Parliament and commander in chief of Iran's armed forces, as
saying he was ``pessimistic'' about Iraq surrendering in the war.
   Rafsanjani was quoted as saying Iran is ``not insisting on
getting our rights on the battlefield with military means.''
   That could indicate a softening in Iran's avowed determination
to crush the Iraqi government, but Rafsanjani also spoke of Iran's
insistence that the war will end only when President Saddam Hussein
of Iraq is ousted.
   Iraq has expressed its willingness to accept a U.N. Security
Council resolution passed last year calling for a cease-fire, but
Iran has not.
   In February 1986, Iran captured the Faw Peninsula near Basra but
was driven out by an Iraqi offensive last April. Iran launched new
attacks in late May to regain the peninsula at the northern tip of
the gulf and both sides have claimed victories.
   Iraq said Monday that its troops, under the direction of
President Hussein, fought for 19 hours to repulse the Iranian
incursion and that Hussein returned to the capital of Baghdad afer
the main fighting ended.
   Iran claimed its forces recaptured some of the land lost in
April.
</TEXT>
