<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Doherty-IRA 1stLd-Writethru a0643 06-14 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doherty-IRA, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Rules That IRA Member Should be Deported to UK, Not Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs bgng, `Failure to,' to
UPDATE with call for Meese's resignation due to Doherty decision</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Irish Republican Army should
be deported to the United Kingdom, Attorney General Edwin Meese III
ruled Tuesday, declaring that sending the man to Ireland instead
would be prejudicial to U.S. interests.
   Meese disapproved a decision by the Board of Immigration
Appeals, which had ruled there was insufficient evidence that
deportation of Joseph Patrick Thomas Doherty to Ireland would be
against U.S. interest.
   Doherty was convicted in the United Kingdom in 1981 of murder in
the ambush of a British army convoy in which a captain was killed.
   Doherty escaped from a prison in Belfast, Northern Ireland,
before sentencing, came to the United States in 1982 and has been
held in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City since
1983 on charges he illegally entered the country using a false
passport.
   Doherty designated Ireland as the country to which he wished to
be deported.
   In reversing the Board of Immigration Appeals, Meese said U.S.
policy is that those who commit acts of violence against a
democratic state should receive swift and lawful punishment, and
that Doherty should serve his sentence in the United Kingdom.
   Michael Armacost, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
wrote the attorney general that a decision to deport Doherty to
Ireland would injure relations with the United Kingdom.
   ``Failure to return Doherty to the United Kingdom could
undermine'' Great Britain's ``confidence in the ability of the
United States to cooperate in counter-terrorism efforts of special
bilateral concern,'' Armacost said. Portions of the letter were
printed in Meese's decision.
   Meese's decision was denounced by a New York Republican
politician who is an activist for Irish causes.
   ``I'm demanding that Meese resign because I'm charging that he's
betrayed the Constitution by ordering Joseph Doherty deported to
the United Kingdom,'' said Peter King, Nassau County comptroller
and the unsuccessful Republican nominee for New York State attorney
general in 1986.
   ``Every court has ruled in favor of Doherty and yet Meese is
ordering him deported to a prison where he will be tortured and
spend the rest of his life in jail,'' King said. ``He is entitled
to political status in this country.''
   The Board of Immigration Appeals now must rule on Doherty's
request to withdraw an earlier admission that he is deportable. If
his request to withdraw the earlier admission is unsuccessful,
Doherty would be deported to the United Kingdom.
   If he prevails, he could file a request seeking asylum in the
United States or file a request for deportation to a country
besides Ireland or the United Kingdom.
   Meese acted on an appeal filed by the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which had objected to Ireland as the
country to which Doherty should be sent.
   INS supplied an immigration judge with newspaper articles and
speeches on the issue of terrorism, but was unsuccessful in its
arguments after failing to submit additional evidence. The appeals
panel upheld the immigration judge's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
