<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     06-14 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Businessman's Three Children Kidnapped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen kidnapped the three children of a
Sunni Moslem businessman Tuesday after stopping the car taking them
to school and shooting the driver in the legs, police reported.
   They said police units and Syrian soldiers in Moslem west Beirut
arrested four suspects but the victims were not found.
   A police spokesman said six gunmen in two cars intercepted the
chauffeur-driven Mercedes-Benz limousine Tuesday morning.
   ``Three gunmen jumped out of a white Volvo, shot the driver in
the legs from silencer-equipped pistols, pulled the children out
and forced them into another Mercedes-Benz and sped away,'' the
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, not identified according to police regulations,
said the victims were the children of Zuhair Ariss, owner of a
jewelry shop and a foreign exchange company in west Beirut.
   The officer idenfied the captives as Dunia, 14, and her brothers
Samer, 9, and Ramzi, 5.
   He said the kidnappings were carried out ``for ransom,''
although no note was received.
   A police communique said security forces seized four gunmen in
connection with the abductions in a raid on the bomb-ravaged Hilton
Hotel, controlled by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems of the Hezbollah,
or Party of God, organization.
   In other developments, a cease-fire officially took effect
Tuesday among Palestinian factions battling in two Beirut refugee
camps, but one group reportedly continued fighting.
   In Damascus, Syria, the Palestinian group Fatah-Uprising of Col.
Abu Mousa said Palestinian Liberation Organization factions began
observing the truce early Tuesday.
   But a spokesman for Mousa later said the mainstream Fatah group
of PLO chief Yasser Arafat continued fighting.
   The struggle for mastery of the Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh
camps flared last week between Arafat's group and the
Fatah-Uprising backed by Syria.
   Syrian troops recently moved into the southern suburbs of Beirut
to quell fighting between Shiite Moslem militias.
   In southern Lebanon, 20 Israeli soldiers continued to blockade
the outpost of a Norwegian unit of the U.N. peace-keeping force for
the second day.
   A U.N. source said the tension developed when the Norwegians
stopped the Israelis Sunday from establishing a checkpoint close to
a Norwegian outpost on the southern edge of Hebbariyeh village.
   Hebbariyeh is seven miles north of Israel's self-designated
security zone in southern Lebanon. It has a Norwegian garrison of
nine peacekeepers.
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli military official speaking on condition
of anonymity said the area where the Norwegians intervened was
inside the Israeli security zone.
   Norway has an 881-member battalion in the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon, made up of 5,800 troops from nine nations and deployed in
1978 to serve as a buffer in southern Lebanon. Its area overlaps
with the six-to-10-mile security zone Israel carved out north of
its border in 1985.
</TEXT>
