<2ND_LINE>AM-Soldiers-Remains,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Soldier's Remains Return To U.S. From Vietnam</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family tearfully accepted the remains of a
soldier Tuesday, more than two decades after his plane was shot
down over North Vietnam.
   ``The 22-year nightmare is over,'' said Joseph Chiarello,
brother of Lt. Col. Vincent Chiarello, an Air Force intelligence
officer.
   Anne Chiarello, the officer's mother, broke down during an honor
guard ceremony as the remains were presented to the family at
Philadelphia International Airport.
   Later, during a news conference, she said she will take off the
MIA bracelet engraved with her son's name that she has worn since
1978.
   ``I will be happy to wear one for another MIA until he comes
home,'' she said.
   Other relatives also said they will continue to help other
families with missing loved ones.
   ``We beseech the Vietnamese government ... to act expeditiously
on behalf of all these families,'' Joseph Chiarello said.
   Chiarello's plane was shot down near the Laotian border on July
29, 1966, according to Joanne Cornell, the officer's sister.
   About four months ago, the Air Force told the family the
Vietnamese government was returning the remains of 20 American
soldiers, including Chiarello.
   However, on March 3, the remains of only 17 soldiers were
returned along with identification cards for Chiarello and two
others. It took an exhaustive comparison of remains with dental,
military and family records to finally identify Chiarello.
   ``The findings were so definite,'' said Mrs. Cornell. ``We felt
we must accept this. We feel beyond a shadow of a doubt these are
my brother's remains.''
   Tom Engkilterra, a coordinator with the National League, an
organization working for information about all Americans missing in
Vietnam, said there were ``2,400 stories out there that need to be
told so this doesn't become a one-day event.''
   The family will bury the remains Saturday in Newtown, about 25
miles northeast of Philadelphia, after a funeral Mass.
</TEXT>
