<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Strike     06-14 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Strike,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Employees Walk Off Job In Wage Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60,000 government employees demanding
more pay staged a one-day strike Tuesday, shutting down Israel's
railroads and disrupting government ministries, hospitals and
airports.
   Court clerks did not show up for work and tax offices were
closed.
   The job action originally was open-ended, but organizers later
called on workers to return to their jobs Wednesday.
   Union leaders said they will attach their labor dispute to the
wage negotiations being held between the Histadrut trade union
federation and the Finance Ministry.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir condemned the strike. ``I think
there was no need for the strike that causes damages and creates
inconvenience for the economy,'' he told Israel radio.
   At Ben Gurion International Airport, an emergency staff of 10
out of 180 customs officials checked the luggage of passengers on
incoming flights, Israel army radio reported.
   The strike affected the Interior Ministry, which stopped issuing
identity cards and passports, as well as the Employment Service and
the National Insurance Institute. Israel's Educational Television
stopped its broadcasts.
   The strike came after the failure of seven-hour talks Monday
between the union of civil servants and the Finance Ministry. Media
reports said the ministry told the strikers it will exclude the
strike days from their salaries.
   But union secretary Reuven Ben-Ami told the army radio that the
civil servants, whose average monthly salary is about $625, are
``ready to sacrifice to achieve better wages.''
   Union officials said they are demanding a wage increase of $77,
a raise in medical payments and an increase in the annual
recreation period covered by these payments to 15 days instead of
11.
</TEXT>
