<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Protest     06-14 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Protest,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Protest Economic Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 University of Toronto students
defied campus administrators Tuesday and held a protest against
their university's acting as host for part of the seven-nation
economic summit conference next week.
   ``If no one's going to point out the crimes of the Group of
Seven, then we're all in trouble,'' said Michael Polanyi, 21, son
of professor John Polanyi, the Nobel laureate for chemistry in 1986
who teaches at the university.
   Leaders of the seven nations will visit the downtown campus for
working dinners Monday at Hart House, a cultural and social center.
   ``One of the reasons they are coming to Hart House is to find an
idyllic surrounding, but we just won't be quiet, we won't make it
easy for them,'' said Polanyi, a political science student and
spokesman for a coalition organizing a ``Popular Summit.''
   Asked what his father thought of his risking arrest, Polanyi
said, ``He's supportive.''
   The protesters erected eight tents on a lawn outside Hart House
in defiance of an administration ruling that the tent complex would
pose a threat to public health because of the lack of water and
sanitation.
   The students began the protest Tuesday evening with songs and
banners objecting to U.S. policy in Central America, British rule
in Northern Ireland and the presence of President Reagan and other
leaders on campus.
   University spokesman Stephen Lindt said campus police warned
students to disperse and threatened to issue tickets for illegal
trespassing and camping, which carry a $53 ($43 U.S.) fine.
   One of the protesters, Robert Bruckner, a 21-year-old
archaeology major, said students were upset that the university
decided to be host to the leaders of the United States, Canada,
Britain, West Germany, France, Italy and Japan without consulting
the 34,000-member student body.
   ``Why aren't they (the seven leaders) talking about the problems
their economic system forces on the world _ poverty, homelessness,
the underfunding of universities, the problems of native peoples,
South Africa?'' he said.
   Last week, a Toronto anti-nuclear group staged a mock trial of
the summit leaders for alleged ``crimes against humanity,''
including U.S. aid to rebels in Nicaragua, nuclear armaments and
support for the white-led government of South Africa.
</TEXT>
