<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FisherTreasure     06-14 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fisher Treasure,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasures from the Deep on the Auction Block</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bidders offered more than $2.5 million Tuesday
for a trove of gold, silver and emeralds that had laid undisturbed
for centuries on the bottom of the sea until found by treasure
hunter Mel Fisher.
   A 62-inch-long gold chain formed from 136 oval links attracted
the most attention and fetched $319,000 in spirited but quick
bidding. The chain, purchased by an anonymous telephone bidder, had
an estimated pre-sale price of $150,000 to $250,000.
   The auction was the first of a two-day sale at Christie's
auction house of booty recovered from Spanish sailing ships
discovered in the Caribbean by Fisher, a diver who has devoted much
of his life to treasure hunting.
   The auction house said more than 70 percent of the items offered
Tuesday were sold for a total of $2,588,443.
   The treasure _ which included gold and silver bars, jewelry and
artifacts as well as coins, emeralds and 17th century navigation
instruments _ was taken mostly from the Spanish treasure galleons
Nuestra Senora de Atocha and her sister ship the Santa Margarita.
   The two vessels, battered by a hurricane, went down off the
Florida Keys in September 1622.
   A gold two-handled cup recovered from what's believed to be the
Santo Cristo de San Roman, part of the Spanish fleet sunk in 1715,
brought the night's second-highest sale price, $275,000. It was
bought by a London dealer, S.J. Phillips.
   The Santo Cristo was one of six wrecks found by salvors working
off the east coast of Florida near Vero Beach.
   Fisher, who attended the auction with heavy gold chains salvaged
from the Atocha draped around his neck, said he was satisfied with
the sale and said there would likely be others.
   ``We're still dividing the treasure. It's taken us three years
to divide it all up,'' he said.
   Tuesday's items were offered by backers who financed Fisher's
expeditions in exchange for a share of the proceeds.
   Fisher began his search for the Atocha in the Keys in 1968 and
found the vessel three years later. In 1980 he discovered the
Margarita.
   The treasure hunter himself had only one item in the sale, the
gold cup, which he owned with an investor.
   ``I didn't want to saw it in two, give him half and keep half,''
he said. So he sold it.
</TEXT>
