<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Economy     06-14 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Economy,0431</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Ortega, Cabinet Discuss New Economic Measures</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega and his
Cabinet on Tuesday discussed dramatic new economic policies that
lift price and wage controls, the president's office said.
   Details were not immediately known, but it appeared the leftist
Sandinista government was moving away from central control toward a
Western-style free market.
   Enrique Bolanos, president of the Superior Private Enterprise
Council, said his umbrella group for privately owned businesses
supports the removal of price controls. But he warned it might
further fuel inflation, now running at about 4,000 percent.
   Ortega failed to show up for a news conference Tuesday and his
office said he was held up by meetings with Cabinet members.
   Ortega announced on Saturday that the government was withdrawing
a wage scale in effect since 1985. The idea, he said, was to link
wages to productivity, sharply down in recent years.
   But some speculation arose that basing salaries on production
might cause a surge in unemployment.
   Six years of civil war coupled with U.S. trade sanctions enacted
in 1985 have shattered the Nicaraguan economy.
   ``For all intents and purposes, Nicaragua at the end of 1987 was
a bankrupt country,'' said a U.S. Embassy report in January.
   Nicaragua has a foreign debt of more than $6 billion. Soviet
bloc infusions of about $400 million a year fail to cover the
country's trade deficit.
   From 1980 to the end of 1987, inflation caused the average urban
worker's purchasing power to drop almost 90 percent.
   The government has controlled salaries, basic foodstuffs, the
prices of primary products and the distribution of imports and
exports.
   Measures taken by the government have failed to right the
economy, which was in disarray when the Sandinistas came to power
in a 1979 revolution that deposed dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   The Sandinistas promised broad social programs and benefits. But
the war by the U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras started a little
more than a year after the revolution.
   Today, despite a fragile, three-month cease-fire, about 60
percent of the national budget goes toward defense. The Sandinistas
put the war's pricetag at $3 billion.
   Thousands of Nicaraguans fled the fighting for the cities,
leaving behind fertile lands in the northern and central war zones.
Young peasants who normally would work on farms are forced to fight
for either the Contras or the Sandinistas
   In April, the government began laying off 20,000 public
employees in hopes they would turn to agriculture.
</TEXT>
