<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nepal-USWomanRunner     06-14 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nepal-US Woman Runner,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Woman Completes Himalayan Run</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran endurance runner Mary Margaret
Goodwin of Fort Lewis, Wash., reported Monday that she completed a
1,300-mile run through the Nepal-Himalayan region and said she was
the first solitary runner to do so.
   She said she had to cope with an elephant charge and 110-plus
heat to accomplish her feat, but added, ``I have done the
Nepal-Himalaya run exactly in one day less than three months. Now I
am crossing to India. But that is a big problem. At the moment the
border is closed.''
   Goodwin, 50, told The Associated Press by telephone from
Mahendranagar, about 330 miles southwest of Katmandu, that she
arrived at the Nepalese township along the border Sunday in a bid
to complete her trans-Himalayan run from India's Darjeeling city in
West Bengal state to Gulmarg in Kashmir, India.
   She left Darjeeling on March 11 and entered into the Himalayan
kingdom of Nepal two days later.
   Her only companion was a 2-year-old German shorthair pointer,
Velia.
   ``But India has closed this point of the border to foreigners,''
she said. ``The Banbasha Bazar of the northern Indian state of
Uttar Pradesh is only 15 miles away from here. But I can't go there
from here,'' goodwin said.
   She said that before setting she went to New Delhi and thought
she had secured permission from the Indian authorities for the
trans-Himalayan run.
   Goodwin said she sent a message to the U.S. Embassy in New Delhi
to approach the Indian authorities again.
   She described the crossing of the Nepalese Himalayan foothills
from one end of Nepal to the another as a ``big victory for me .. .
I have today become the fastest woman, and the first solo runner
through the Himalayan kingdom.''
   After leaving the mountainous region on Thursday, Goodwin said
she and her dog arrived at Chisapani in the tropical plains of
south Nepal.
   ``We had come through the tigers and snakes areas ... coming
from Chisapani all the way to Mahendranagar,'' she reported.
   She said she had to spend three days to complete the 112-mile
Chisapani-Mahendranagar route in a heat of more than 110 degrees.
   ``My dog had been surrounded by troops of monkeys all along the
road every day. And while we were resting on the bank of Karnali
River, a huge elephant came out of a nearby jungle, charging us ..
. both me and my dog.''
   They got out of that without harm, but she noted that ``even my
dog did not sleep on the ground because of snakes.''
   ``There was no bridge on the river,'' Goodwin said, ``My dog had
to swim. I was wading across it. But the water was very deep. So
all the day long, I had to move with wet shoes and wet clothes.''
   Goodwin has been participating in endurance events since the
1950s. She was the first woman to run the 1,000-mile route through
Scotland, Wales and England and also completed a 2,000-mile trip
through Japan in 1986.
   A former resident of northern Virginia, she served as director
of environmental and conservation matters in the Office of the
Secretary of the Navy from 1979-83.
</TEXT>
