<HEAD>Stocks At New Highs, Dollar Surges On U.S. Trade Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closing figures. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices surged to new highs while the U.S.
dollar leaped in value against the Japanese yen early Wednesday, in
reaction to a report of better-than-expected U.S. trade figures for
April.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues finished the
morning session up 186.56 points at a record 28,248.36.
   The key market barometer had peaked last Thursday when it closed
at 28.072.02.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, morning session volume was a record
1.6 billion shares, dealers said. A total 930 million shares were
traded for all of Tuesday.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened at 126.36 yen, up sharply
from Tuesday's close of 125.05 yen, and changed hands in the
126.27-126.55 yen range before closing the morning trading at
126.15 yen.
   ``The largest factor for the dollar's rise is the improvement in
the U.S. trade deficit in April,'' said an exchange dealer at a
major commercial bank in Tokyo.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit narrowed in April to $9.89 billion, the
lowest level since December 1984, largely because of a decline in
imports.
   Financial markets have reacted strongly in recent months to U.S.
trade figures, which are seen as providing signals for the likely
direction of stocks and the dollar.
   The Bank of Tokyo said a total of $4.1 billion were traded in
brisk transactions on the foreign exchange market during the
morning session.
</TEXT>
