<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has found that Liggett Group
Inc. failed to warn the public about the dangers of cigarettes,
marking the first time a tobacco company has been found liable for
contributing to a smoker's death.
   The jury awarded $400,000 damages Monday to the husband of Rose
Cipollone, who died of lung cancer in 1984 at the age of 58. But it
held that Mrs. Cipollone bore 80 percent of the blame for her own
death.
   The jury also exonerated Liggett, Lorillard Inc. and Philip
Morris Inc. of misleading the public about the dangers of smoking
and of conspiring to mislead.
   It also found that Liggett violated its promise to consumers to
make a safe product, but awarded no damages on that claim.
