   Legislation to close a loophole in the
regulation of polychlorinated biphenyls, the highly toxic chemicals
whose manufacture was banned in 1976, has been approved by the
House.
   The bill, sent to the Senate Monday, would require brokers, the
middlemen who arrange for the transportation and destruction of
PCBs, to be registered, keep records and demonstrate financial
responsibility.
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the legislation is a response to
reports that unregulated PCB brokers have handled the chemicals
improperly and in some instances have gone bankrupt, leaving power
companies and communities to clean up PCB storage sites.
