<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-14 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall Amid Pessimism Over OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued failure by OPEC members to agree on a
new pricing and production agreement has sent oil prices lower.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude, fell 30 cents Monday
to close at $16.43 a barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
fell 0.71 cent a gallon to 48.51 cents, and home heating oil
declined .50 cent to 43.75 cents a gallon.
   Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries,
meeting in Vienna, agreed Monday to extend their existing
production accord but kept haggling over whether to prolong it for
three months or six months.
   Analysts in Vienna said an extension of the accord highlighted
the members' inability to overcome their differences on output
levels and reach a new agreement. The agreement already has been
extended once _ from last December until this month _ because the
13 OPEC members could not reach a new pact.
   One OPEC faction wants to cut production to push weak oil prices
higher. Another _ including Saudi Arabia _ wants to increase
production or at least maintain it at current levels to take
advantage of an expected increase in demand in the second half of
the year.
   ``It comes down to the Saudis and their allies are not
interested in doing anything to shore up the price of oil,'' said
Peter Beutel, an assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc. in New York.
   Oil prices fell in reaction to developments at the meeting
because ``the market has been disappointed by the opportunities
lost,'' Beutel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
