<DOCNO> AP880614-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-Business Bjt   06-14 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ruling Gives Banks Limited Underwriting Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Major banks are applauding the Supreme Court's ruling that banks
can use subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in some securities as
another step toward their industry's expansion into lucrative
investment banking.
   Some banking companies, including Bankers Trust New York Corp.
and Chemical New York Corp., said Monday that they planned to take
advantage of their new underwriting powers before the end of the
week. Others, such as Chase Manhattan Corp., said they would begin
operations some time this summer.
   The Supreme Court's ruling Monday upheld a lower court decision
permitting banks to use subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in
municipal revenue bonds, mortgage-related securities and commercial
paper, a form of short-term corporate IOU.
   The Federal Reserve Board had granted such powers to seven of
the nation's biggest banks, but restricted the activity to no more
than 5 percent to 10 percent of the subsidary's gross revenue. That
action was appealed by the Securities Industry Association.
   In its decision, the Supreme Court let stand an appeals court
ruling four months ago that such activity did not violate the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act.
   The law, passed by Congress in the wake of the 1929 stock market
crash, was aimed primarily at protecting the financial stability of
banks by restricting them from speculating in stocks and bonds.
   Congressional legislation is pending to repeal parts of the law.
   Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., said the court's decision
would not deter the House banking committee, which he chairs, from
legislating such ground rules.
   ``A majority of the banking committee ... feel that it is a
mistake to alllow the future structure of the financial community
to be decided by the regulatory agencies and the courts,'' St
Germain said in a statement released Monday by his office.
   Charles Pistor, president of the American Bankers Association,
said Monday's ruling displayed ``another hole in the
anti-competitive Glass-Steagall Act and another important victory
for consumers. But, before large numbers of bank customers will
benefit, we need to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act and allow all
banks to offer securities services.''
   SIA President Edward I. O'Brien said his group was disappointed
by the decision. ``But we are pleased the Federal Reserve itself
has erected a series of firewalls ... to prevent banks from taking
excessive risks within the securities arena which would further
weaken banks and thus endanger the nation's economy,'' he said.
   In other Supreme Court decisions Monday, the justices:
   _Let stand a ruling that allows states indirectly to tax
interest paid to banks and other financial institutions from
investments in Federal Home Loan Bank bonds.
   _Ruled unanimously the government may be forced to pay damages
when a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended to
prevent.
   _Barred states from banning all direct mail advertisements sent
by lawyers to potential clients.
   _Ruled the Postal Service was similar to a private business and
must pay interest on back pay owed to a Chesterfield, Mo., worker
who won a lawsuit charging it with illegal discrimination.
   _Ruled that companies may violate antitrust law when they lobby
private organizations that play a prominent role in influencing
business legislation. _Struck down a federal antitrust lawsuit by
actor Paul Newman and director George Roy Hill over profits from
video cassette sales and rentals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
