<DOCNO> AP880614-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Icahn-Texaco     06-14 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icahn-Texaco,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Says He Has Put $310.2 Million In Escrow To Cover Texaco Bid
Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl C. Icahn says he has put $310.2 million
into an escrow account to be divided among Texaco Inc. shareholders
if he fails to come up with financing for his $60-per-share offer
to buy the company.
   At its White Plains, N.Y., headquarters, the nation's
third-largest oil company reacted skeptically to the action Monday
by its biggest shareholder, saying Icahn had ``been caught
red-handed giving the Texaco shareholder false and misleading
information.''
   ``Given the number of strings and conditions that remain
attached to this money, it doesn't matter to the Texaco shareholder
what account Icahn puts it in,'' Texaco stated. ``He can move it
from one pocket to another as much as he wants _ we are still
convinced it will never get to Texaco shareholders.''
   Icahn also said he had sent a signed ``bare bones'' $60 a share
merger agreement to the company.
   ``If Texaco executes the merger agreement, we will terminate our
proxy contest and withdraw our slate of nominees,'' the statement
said, referring to Icahn's attempt to elect himself and four
colleagues to Texaco's board of directors.
   Texaco has said repeatedly it was not interested in Icahn's
advances.
   Texaco's stock slid $1.37{ to $50.50 a share Monday in
consolidated nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
issues. It has remained in the $50-per-share range since Icahn
launched his bid last month.
   Icahn has offered to pay $12.4 billion for the 207 million
Texaco shares he does not already own. He paid about $1.2 billion
for his existing stake of about 36 million shares. The offer puts a
value of $14.6 billion on the oil company.
   But Texaco has refused to put Icahn's buyout offer to a
shareholder vote, prompting him to field the slate of five
candidates for Texaco' 14-member board. Icahn has said he wants the
seats on Texaco's board so he can pressure it into putting his
offer before the shareholders.
   The proxy fight deadline is Friday, when Texaco holds its annual
meeting in Tulsa, Okla.
   Originally, Icahn offered to put $100 million in escrow to ease
market suspicions that he could not come up with the money actually
to buy the company.
   Last week, Icahn increased the guarantee to $300 million, and
promised it would be distributed directly to Texaco shareholders,
instead of the company treasury, if he failed to get financing.
   Icahn's statement that $310,201,955 in cash was placed in escrow
with Fleet National Bank of Providence, R.I. _ $1.50 per share for
all Texaco stockholders eligible to vote on the special meeting he
is seeking _ apparently was designed to stifle Texaco's criticism
that he was unlikely ever to have to pay the money.
   Icahn said the escrow would be forfeited if, at the time of the
special stockholders meeting to vote on his offer, the financing
was not in place.
   He said the escrow would not be forfeited if by the time of the
meeting another entity made a legitimate bid for more than $60 per
share, or if the Internal Revenue Service failed to give required
approval to Icahn's proposal.
   Icahn said Friday he was forming a new holding company to act as
his sole vehicle for acquisitions, including a possible hostile
takeover bid for Texaco. He said the holding company intended to
raise up to $3.25 billion through an offering of stock and debt
securities.
   Icahn stated that if his slate was elected but a majority of the
Texaco board refused to allow a shareholder vote on the offer, he
would consider making a hostile bid for it through the new holding
company at yet to be determined terms.
</TEXT>
