<DOCNO> AP880614-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessStarts     06-14 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Starts,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Business Startups Fall 6.6 Percent in 7th Quarterly Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Business Starts-States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A continuing decline in the number of U.S.
business starts reflects the nation's changing economic profile and
not necessarily broad economic problems, according to a business
information concern.
   The number of new domestic businesses declined by 6.6 percent to
53,382 in the first three months of the year _ the seventh straight
quarterly drop _ from 57,158 in first quarter 1987, according to
Dun & Bradstreet Corp.
   Dun & Bradstreet officials cited the maturing of the nation's
economic expansion, now in its sixth year, and a shift from
consumerism to export-driven growth as factors in the decline of
business starts, a barometer of economic activity and money-making
opportunities.
   Joseph W. Duncan, Dun & Bradstreet's corporate economist and
chief statistician, said new retailing businesses fell because of
expectations that consumer demand will weaken, and startups of new
service businesses fell in response to increased competition and
corporate budget reductions.
   Retailing and service concerns account for about half of all new
businesses.
   ``While the current surge in U.S. exports will create new
business opportunities in some sectors, existing manufacturers are
the primary beneficiaries,'' Duncan said in a report of the latest
figures.
   Business starts are considered important because they signal the
level of entrepreneurial activity and perceived opportunities for
profit in local area markets. But a persistent decline in starts
does not necessarily indicate a broader economic problem, said Reid
Gearhart, a Dun & Bradstreet spokesman.
   ``With the recovery in its sixth year, that's just having a
dampening effect,'' he said. ``It's not really a negative.''
   Dun & Bradstreet data indicated first-quarter business starts
fell in seven of the nine major industry sectors. The largest
decrease came in the finance-insurance-real estate category, which
fell 9.8 percent. Retail business starts dropped 8.1 percent and
services fell 5.7 percent.
   Starts also fell in the construction, manufacturing, wholesale
and transportation sectors, with decreases of between 5 percent and
8 percent.
   Increases were in agriculture, up 11.5 percent, and mining, up
2.3 percent.
   ``Both mining, which includes oil and gas extraction businesses,
and agriculture appear to be turning the corner after several years
of severe stress,'' Duncan said.
   Despite a drop in manufacturing-related business starts, there
was evidence that export growth was encouraging some entrepreneurs,
Duncan said. An analysis of manufacturing starts showed significant
increases among motor vehicle and equipment makers, metal producers
and office equipment manufacturers.
   Geographically, first-quarter starts fell nationwide, with the
largest decreases in the Rocky Mountain states, down 15.6 percent.
Other significant drops occurred in the Middle Atlantic states,
down 12.2 percent, and the West North Central states, down 12
percent.
   Starts in New England dropped only 1.1 percent, while starts in
the South Atlantic and East North Central states were both down 3.3
percent. Starts fell 3.8 percent in the Pacific states, 6.7 percent
in East South Central states and 6.3 percent in West South Central
states.
   Dun & Bradstreet describes itself as the world's largest
marketer of business information and related services, with revenue
of $3.4 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     06-14 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Mixed on Short-Term Treasury Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the government's latest auction, with
three-month securities unchanged and the six-month rate down
slightly.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.44 percent on Monday, identical to
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 6.67 percent, down from 6.72 percent last
week.
   The rate on three-month bills this week and last was the lowest
since these bills sold for 6.53 percent on May 3. The rate on
six-month bills was the lowest since May 16, when they averaged 6.5
percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.64 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,837.20 and 7.0 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,662.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages dropped to 7.46 percent last
week from 7.59 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
