<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OPEC 3rdLd-Writethru f0030 06-14 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0030,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Ministers Extend Output Agreement For Six Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info and editing grafs 1-10 to show that agreement had
been expected, Iraq unlikely to sign. INSERTS 15th graf, Hernandez,
however ... to UPDATE with UAE involvement. Hernandez cq on second
reference. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers reached agreement today to
extend their existing oil output pact for six months but failed to
take any further steps aimed at limiting production and boosting
prices.
   Venezuelan oil minister Arturo Hernandez Grisanti, disclosing
the agreement to reporters at the 13-nation cartel's regular
midyear meeting, said ``we think the market will have a good
perception of what we have done.''
   Nevertheless, the agreement confirmed widespread speculation
that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries wouldn't
agree on significant new moves to cut the world supply of oil.
Prices are now substantially below OPEC's $18-per-barrel objective.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a sensitive barometer of
prices, the July contract for West Texas Intermediate crude fell 30
cents Monday to close at $16.43 a barrel, partly in anticipation of
the OPEC agreement reached today.
   The ministers, who began their conference on Saturday, gathered
to decide whether to change the agreement among 12 of the producers
that limits output to 15.06 million barrels a day.
   Delegation sources said the ministers had haggled over whether
to extend the accord by three months or six months. The accord was
to have expired June 30.
   High-level sources in several delegations, speaking on condition
of anonymity earlier, said a majority of the OPEC ministers had
favored the shorter extension. But the minority, favoring the
longer extension, included influential Saudi Arabia, OPEC's biggest
producer.
   Analysts had said the prospect of yet another extension
highlighted OPEC's inability to overcome its differences on
production levels and agree on a common formula to raise prices.
   One OPEC faction has wanted to cut production to push prices up
to the target level. The Saudi-led minority has wanted to increase
production or at least maintain it at current levels to take
advantage of an increase in demand expected in the second half of
the year and to maintain OPEC's market share.
   Iraq refused to sign the current accord because it wants a quota
equal to that of Iran, with which it has been at war since 1980.
OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, Nigeria's oil minister, said it was
unlikely Iraq would participate in the latest agreement.
   Lukman said Monday that the ministers were working hard on a
compromise to bring Iraq back into the fold.
   Iran has a daily production quota of 2.369 million barrels.
Iraq, which previously had a quota of 1.54 million barrels a day,
is producing 2.6 million barrels daily.
   Success on that front would lower Iraq's production, which could
help boost oil prices.
   The United Arab Emirates' oil minister, Mana Saeed Oteiba, left
the talks on Sunday. He said he needed to consult with his
government and might or might not return, although he left the rest
of the UAE delegation behind.
   Hernandez, however, said it was likely Otgiba would return today
to sign the rollover agreement.
   OPEC members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
