<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BeerMarket-Bud Adv18-19   06-14 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Beer Market-Bud, Adv 18-19,0667</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 18-19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Why Is Bud On Top?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Beer Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most beer companies grapple with a
stagnant market, Anheuser-Busch Inc. is soaking up customers and
leaving some observers scratching their heads.
   ``That's the $64 question,'' said Frank Walters, research
director for M. Shanken Communications in New York which publishes
beverage industry magazines.
   Since the beginning of the decade, Anheuser has raised its share
of the market from 28 percent to nearly 40 percent largely due to
growth in Budweiser sales, which have bubbled from 35 million
barrels in 1980 to 50 million last year.
   The answers given for the company's success range from superior
marketing and management to high quality products to other factors
that are less tangible.
   For example, Budweiser appears to succeed in getting consumers
at an early age and keeping them, said Emanuel Goldman, an analyst
with Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
   If beer customers want to try a different brand, and that
product happens to be unavailable, then the consumers most commonly
choose a Budweiser, analysts say.
   ``It's become everybody's No. 2 brand,'' said John Collopy, who
follows the beer industry and is president of the Milwaukee
investment firm, Cleary Gull Reiland McDevitt & Collopy Inc.
   Robert Weinberg, a St. Louis analyst who is a former Anheuser
executive, said some of the brewer's successful strategies emerged
after the company was bruised by its current main competitor,
Miller Brewing Co. in Milwaukee.
   Weinberg said Miller was first to use the marketing technique of
putting the consumer at the center of an ad, with the Miller High
Life slogan: ``If you've got the time, we've got the beer.''
   ``It had Anheuser-Busch spinning through 1975,'' Weinberg said,
and Miller was able to eat away much of Anheuser's lead.
   But Anheuser, he said, responded with its own consumer-oriented
slogan, ``This Bud's for you,'' which helped the company recapture
its momentum.
   John MacDonough, vice president of brand management at Anheuser,
said advertising alone cannot carry a product.
   ``All I can say is that the consumer is very sensitive,'' he
said. ``No amount of marketing could keep a product going if you
don't have a good product.''
   Analysts also note that Budweiser has been protected from the
discount beer battles of Miller and Stroh Brewery Co. by using the
Busch brand as a shield.
   But it might be difficult to maintain Budweiser's growth as
Anheuser ventures more into the low-calorie beer market, MacDonough
said.
   After the light beer market opened up, Anheuser made a stab with
Natural Light, which has not taken off like its counterpart, Lite
beer at Miller.
   But Anheuser introduced Bud Light in the early 1980s, and while
the brand has not challenged Lite in terms of volume, its sales
have had double-digit growth each of the past two years.
   MacDonough acknowledged that Anheuser officials were reluctant
to enter the light beer market with the Budweiser name for fear
that it would eat away Budweiser sales similar to what has happened
at other companies.
   ``We don't like to give people as good a head start as we gave
Lite,'' he said. ``What's unusual is that we've gained that
terrific growth (with Bud Light) and have still grown with
Budweiser.''
   One of the few areas where Anheuser has had problems is with its
super-premium Michelob line, which, according to Goldman's
estimates, has lost an estimated 20 percent since the beginning of
the decade.
   But he noted Michelob sales probably were hurt by a strong
dollar, which allowed imported beers to hold down their prices. Now
that the dollar has weakened against other currencies, he said,
Michelob's erosion might subside.
   Anheuser also has had success selling its beer overseas through
exporting and licensing agreements.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
