<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     06-14 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0490</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market held at sharply higher levels
today after surging on a better-than-expected trade report that
worked to ease inflation fears.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 31.82 points to
2,131.22, its highest level since the October market crash, by
midafternoon.
   Trading was active. Volume on the Big Board came to 170.23
million shares. Gainers led losers by about 3 to 1 with 1,133 up,
396 down and 405 unchanged at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Stock prices surged at the opening on a long-awaited Commerce
Department report which showed the nation's seasonally adjusted
trade deficit narrowed to $9.89 billion in April, far below the
$12-plus billion market watchers had been anticipating.
   It was the lowest trade imbalance since December 1984.
   The report also sparked a rally in the bond market, where the
bellwether 30-year Treasury issue was up more than $17 per $1,000
in face value at midday. The dollar also moved sharply higher
against the major currencies.
   One trader said the market was ``feeding off the effect the
(trade) number has on inflation.''
   Analysts noted that the markets embraced the trade report
because it showed a decline in exports, which eased by 2.5 percent
and worked to dispel concerns that the economy is overheating.
Imports declined by 6.4 percent in April.
   Last month, although the government's March deficit figures also
were better than expected, a surge in both imports and exports
replaced investors' enthusiasm with fears of inflation.
   ``If exports are surging, the economy is surging and inflation
is surging,'' noted Larry Wachtel, first vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The Dow had been flirting with the 2,100 mark for weeks. ``But
we've broken out of that much-publicized resistance level,'' one
trader said.
   Analysts noted that a lot of cash still remains on the
sidelines. ``Portfolio managers are getting `performance anxiety'
fears because they've got a lot of cash,'' one trader noted. ``A
lot of it is going into bonds and equities.''
   Among actively traded issues, IBM jumped 2] to 119], Ford Motor
was up 1] at 52}, Exxon was up 1 at 46~, and Motorola was up 1\ at
51~.
   Philip Morris, a component of the Dow, was off 1| at 83], and
RJR Nabisco was off 1\ at 46}. Tobacco stocks were expected to come
under pressure after a jury in New Jersey on Monday ordered a
tobacco company to pay damages for the death of a smoker.
   Texaco was up \ at 50}. Traders were curious about who purchased
a block of about 7.7 million Texaco shares that traded hands early
in the session.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.85 to 154.87. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.05 at 309.19.
</TEXT>
