<HEAD>London Share Prices Jump As U.S. Trade Gap Narrows</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended sharply higher Tuesday on the
London Stock Exchange following a surge on Wall Street that stemmed
from a better-than-expected U.S. trade report for April.
   The U.S. government said the trade deficit shrank to a
seasonally adjusted $9.89 billion from a revised gap of $11.7
billion in March. The April shortfall was the lowest since December
1984 and about $3 billion down from what many economists had
predicted.
   Wall Street fired ahead from the opening bell, with the closely
watched Dow Jones industrial average up about 30 points to the
2,129 level as the London session neared its close.
   In response, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
ended up 27.4 points, or 1.49 percent, at 1,866.2. Trading volume
was a moderate 472.8 million shares, compared with Monday's 316.2
million.
   Brokers said dollar-dependent international issues were boosted
by a stronger U.S. currency.
   Among the few losers was Consolidated Gold Fields, which fell 10
pence to 10.48 pounds. Dealers said investors took profits and
unloaded their shares as inflation worries began to evaporate.
</TEXT>
