<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PCTrades     06-14 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PC Trades,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM To Accept Old PCs As Trade-Ins For New Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. confirmed
Tuesday it plans to accept its old XT and AT model personal
computers as trade-ins for discounts on its new Personal System-2
line.
   The trade-in program is apparently intended to hasten the
acceptance of the Personal System-2 line _ introduced in April 1987
_ as a new industry standard.
   Although PS-2 sales have been healthy, there is still strong
demand for computers built to the old standard, such as the XT, the
AT and compatible models made by such companies as Compaq Computer
Corp. and Tandy Corp.
   IBM spokesman Scott Brooks said the promotion was still in the
planning stages and it was too soon to give details.
   IBM dealers were informed of the promotion in recent weeks, Info
World, a weekly newspaper on personal computers, reported in its
Monday edition.
   ``This is going to be an excellent program, something IBM has
never offered before,'' Richard Rose, president of Dataflex Corp.
in Edison, N.J., told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
