<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade-Markets Bjt   06-14 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Markets, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks and Dollar Jump, Interest Rates Drop In Response to Trade
Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors scooped up U.S. securities and dollars
Tuesday in response to a surprise plunge in the trade deficit that
diluted inflation fears, depressed interest rates and sent the
stock market to a post-crash high.
   ``I don't think it's an overreaction. It's a very positive
development,'' said Thom R. Brown, chairman of the investment
policy committee at the Philadelphia-based brokerage Butcher &
Singer Inc.
   A government report that the April trade deficit shrank to $9.89
billion startled many economists and investment strategists who had
expected a much larger number.
   The shrinkage reflected a big drop in America's appetite for
imports and a lesser decline in exports, key concerns of those who
fear the economy is too strong and much higher inflation is
inevitable.
   The impact was immediately felt in the foreign-exchange markets,
where surging demand for dollars strengthened the currency's value
relative to the Japanese yen, West German mark and British pound.
   In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of the economy, prices
of the 30-year Treasury bill soared more than $20 per $1,000 in
face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price and is an
important signal of interest rate trends, tumbled to 8.81 percent,
its lowest level in two months.
   The bond-market rally overflowed into Wall Street, where stock
prices advanced strongly and sent some key indices to their highest
closing levels since the the October crash.
   Volume was heavy, an indication that more investors have been
lured back to the market after a prolonged period of apathy and
cynicism about stocks.
   ``The interesting thing I've seen today is that individual
investors are calling to see what stocks we like,'' said Peter A.
Karos, manager of equity and over-the-counter trading at Piper,
Jaffray & Hopwood Inc. in Minneapolis. ``That's the first time I've
seen that for months. It's very encouraging.''
   Nevertheless, some strategists were cautious about interpreting
the monthly trade number, which historically has been unpredictable
and subject to major revisions. They said the markets were simply
overlooking other evidence of impending inflation, such as higher
commodity prices and low unemployment.
   ``I'm somewhat concerned overall because even though
statistically we don't see the kind of inflation we saw in the late
1970s, we're possibly building a fairly good springboard for
inflation,'' said Jack Barbanel, a futures trader at Gruntal & Co.
in New York. ``The market is ignoring it.''
   Stephen B. Timbers, executive vice president and chief
investment officer at Kemper Financial Services in Chicago, said
the trade deficit number showed definite improvement but he also
expressed skepticism about its significance.
   ``We will undoubtedly have a disappointing figure in the next
couple of months,'' he said. ``These numbers swing all over the
place.''
   Even some strategists who were more positive about the trade
number saw some long-term danger lurking because it signaled a
possible end to an economic boom in Japan, a key U.S. trading
partner that largely relies on the American market for its
export-oriented economy.
   If that happened, the roaring Japanese stock market could
tumble, setting off a powerful reverberation through other markets
worldwide, especially in the United States.
   ``I don't think investors are paying any attention to this,
which might come back and bite them,'' said Brown of Butcher &
Singer. ``The Japanese market is so grossly overvalued, it could
come down fast and hard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880614-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-14 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar leaped in value against most major
foreign currencies Tuesday in reaction to a report that the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit narrowed in April to a
better-than-expected $9.89 billion.
   Gold prices finished mixed after initially being knocked down by
the trade news. Republic National Bank of New York said gold was
bid at $450.15 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $449.70 late
Monday.
   In its strongest move in months, the dollar climbed 1.6 percent
against the West German mark although West Germany's central bank
sold dollars in an attempt to stem the U.S. currency's rise,
traders said.
   The dollar also rose 1.7 percent against the British pound and
by slightly less against other European currencies and the Japanese
yen. It slipped against the Canadian dollar, in part because a
strong bond rally lowered yields on U.S. securities in comparison
to Canadian securities.
   Traders said there were no confirmed reports of dollar selling
by central banks other than West Germany's.
   Many traders had expected the April merchandise trade deficit to
be about $12.2 billion. Instead, the gap proved to be the lowest
since December 1984.
   ``The statistics were quite a shock to the marketplace,'' said
Richard Witten, a vice president at Goldman, Sachs & Co.
   Witten said some traders concluded the United States would be
able to trade its way out of its deficit, although he said, ``I
think it's too early to say that.''
   West Germany's intervention briefly suppressed the dollar's
rise, but the currency rebounded and finished the session at its
highs of the day, said Jeff Mondschein, vice president and foreign
exchange manager for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   In London, the dollar strengthened to $1.7925 to the pound from
$1.8165 on Monday. Later in New York, the dollar strengthened to
$1.7864 to the pound from $1.8165 late Monday.
   Before the announcement of the trade figures, the dollar closed
at 125.05 Japanese yen in Tokyo, down from 125.19 Monday. In London
the dollar traded at 126.20 yen. At the end of the trading day in
New York, the dollar rose to 126.55 yen from 125.12 yen late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7496 West German marks, up from 1.7227; 1.4626
Swiss francs, up from 1.4408; 1.2183 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2208; 1,297.50 Italian lire, up from 1,280.25; and 5.8970 French
francs, up from 5.8125.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with Monday's late rates,
included: 1.7460 West German marks, up from 1.7241; 1.4615 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4424; 5.8840 French francs, up from 5.7265;
1.9600 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9345; 1,292.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,281.75; and 1.2162 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2203.
   Gold dropped about $4 an ounce immediately after the release of
the trade numbers, but recovered toward the end of the day in
reaction to strength in oil prices and commodity indexes, said
Brian Donohue, a trader for Midland Montagu Metals in New York.
   In Hong Kong, where the market closed before the release of the
U.S. trade numbers, gold closed at a bid $452.58, down from $457.99.
   The late gold bid price in London was $448 a troy ounce, down
from $449 an ounce late Monday. The late bid price in Zurich was
also $448 an ounce, down from $448.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $450.60 a troy ounce from $449.60 an ounce late
Monday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.91 a troy
ounce, down from $7.02 an ounce. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $7.040 a troy ounce from
$7.025 an ounce late Monday.
</TEXT>
