<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PhonyJuice     06-14 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Juice,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Asks Prison Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors are seeking a
``substantial'' prison sentence for the former head of Beech-Nut
Corp., who was convicted of distributing phony apple juice for
babies, according to court papers filed Tuesday.
   Former Beech-Nut Chief Executive Neils Hoyvald, 54, was found
guilty in February of 351 counts of violating the Food, Drug and
Cosmetic Act. Each count carries a maximum sentence of three years
in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   He and his co-defendant, John Lavery, a former Beech-Nut vice
president, are scheduled for sentencing Thursday in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn.
   The government has urged U.S. District Judge Thomas Platt to
impose a ``substantial'' prison sentence for Hoyvald because he has
not shown remorse and because he allegedly gave false testimony,
according to a response letter from Hoyvald's attorney, Brendan
Sullivan Jr., who said the arguments had no merit.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Roche said the government's
pre-sentencing memorandum would not be made public until the day of
sentencing.
   Sullivan has asked that Hoyvald be spared a prison term and that
he instead receive probation and community service or home
detention.
   In his pre-sentencing memo, Sullivan suggested that Hoyvald
could lecture to business students so they could learn from his
mistakes.
   ``Mr. Hoyvald has been branded as a convicted felon and will
bear the stigma of his convictions for as long as he lives,''
Sullivan said in his letter. ``This prosecution has already `sent a
message' to the food industry that economic adulteration will not
be overlooked and may result in criminal liability.''
   Hoyvald and Lavery were charged in an indictment that accused
Beech-Nut of shipping adulterated and misbranded juice made from
phony concentrate throughout the United States and overseas from
1978 to 1983.
   The juice, labeled 100 percent apple juice for babies, was
actually made from a flavored concentrate that had little or no
apple juice, prosecutors charged. There has been no evidence that
the phony juice caused any health problems.
   Beech-Nut, the corporation, pleaded guilty in November to 215
counts of violating federal food and drug laws and agreed to pay a
$2 million fine.
   Lavery, who oversaw the upstate manufacturing where the juice
was made, was convicted conspiracy, 18 counts of mail fraud and 429
counts of violating federal food and drug laws.
   Beech-Nut, based in Fort Washington, Pa., is a subsidiary of
Nestle S.A. of Switzerland.
</TEXT>
