<HEAD>Kodak Introduces New Batteries, Cameras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. on Tuesday introduced a
line of batteries that are designed to last longer in cameras and
other photographic equipment, a company spokesman said.
   Kodak also introduced two new cameras, including an $11.95 model
for young children called the ``Mickey-Matic,'' and two new color
slide films.
   The line of ``Photolife'' alkaline batteries was made to perform
best in devices such as point-and-shoot 35 mm cameras and flash
attachments that frequently demand short, repeated bursts of energy.
   ``We have created these premium, high-performance energy cells
to meet the special demands of picture-taking consumers,'' said
Martin Adams, vice president for marketing of Ultra Technologies,
the Kodak subsidiary that oversees the battery business.
   The batteries come in either AA-size or AAA-size and will be
available in September.
   Kodak has been struggling to gain a share of the market that is
dominated by Duracell and Eveready.
   Kodak is not the first to launch a special battery for a
specific purpose. Several months ago, Eveready introduced a line of
batteries called ``The Conductor'' which are designed for use in
audio equipment, such as portable stereos.
   Duracell Inc., the leader in the sale of AA and AAA batteries,
hasn't gotten into the specific-use market because its batteries
perform ``as well or better'' than any other akaline battery in all
categories, said James Donahue, a company spokesman.
   The other new Kodak products announced Tuesday are: another
easy-to-use 35 mm camera, at $89.95, to go with Kodak's eight other
35 mm models released in the past two years; the ``Mickey-Matic,''
a 110-format camera; new Kodachrome film that is the first slide
film available at 200 ISO; Ektachrome 100 HC film, which will
provide more saturated colors in a versatile, general-purpose slide
film.
