<HEAD>Northwest Joins With MCI In Frequent-Flier Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Northwest Airlines' Worldperks
program will receive frequent-flier mileage credit if they use MCI
Communications Corp.'s long-distance telephone service, Northwest
announced Tuesday.
   Starting Sept. 1, Worldperks members will be awarded one bonus
mile for each dollar they spend on MCI service, Northwest said. As
an incentive to apply for the free MCI-Northwest card, the airline
will give each applicant a free upgrade to first class on a
Northwest domestic flight.
   A.B. Magary, Northwest's executive vice president of marketing,
said MCI joins Northwest's hotel and rental car partners and the
Worldperks Visa card as non-flying ways of earning Worldperks miles.
   ``The demographics of frequent-flier program members tracks very
closely with large long-distance phone users,'' said Brian
Thompson, executive vice president of MCI.
   ``This program represents a unique marketing opportunity for
both MCI and Northwest to broaden and enhance the value brought to
their respective customers.''
