<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MazdaReorganizes     06-14 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mazda Reorganizes,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mazda Combining Two U.S. Sales Companies Into One, Laying Off 75
Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. will combine its two
U.S. sales and importing companies into one July 1, eliminating 70
jobs at one of the companies' headquarters in Jacksonville, Fla.
   Mazda is combining Mazda Motors of America Central and Mazda
Motors of America East into Mazda Motor of America Inc. About 20 of
the 330 workers at the Mazda East headquarters will be laid off by
the end of June, Yoshinori Taura, president of the new Irvine,
Calif.-based company, said Tuesday.
   In the next three to six months, 45 to 50 other Jacksonville
workers will be laid off. But those workers were given bonuses to
stay through the transition and all 70 will be assisted in finding
jobs, Taura said.
   ``I feel very sorry for those workers. It is not our desire to
have to ask them to leave. We will help them,'' Taura said, adding
that the consolidation would improve Mazda's efficiency in the U.S.
market.
   ``We believe the improved efficiency and services that will
result from this reorganization of our U.S. marketing activity will
be reflected in an enriched product line, one which more closely
reflects the needs and desires of our customers here,'' Taura said.
   The use of two sales companies by a foreign company in the
United States was unique to Mazda. Mazda Central, which included 31
states, and Mazda East, which included 18, were formed 11 years
ago, when Mazda was suffering financially. A company that imported
into Hawaii also will be folded into the new company.
   Each company was half-owned by Mazda. The other partner in Mazda
Central was C. Itoh and Co. Ltd., a big Japanese trading company,
which will own 20 percent of Mazda Motor of America. The Mazda East
partner was Sumitomo Corp., Mazda's banker, which will own 30
percent of the new company.
   Taura was president of Mazda Central, which will keep all its
workers. About 15 Americans and 10 Japanese Mazda East workers will
be transferred from Jacksonville to Irvine, he said.
   Taura will report to Keiji Asano, a senior managing director of
the parent company, who was named chairman of Mazda Motor of
America and who is based in Japan.
   Mazda has three other companies in the United States. The newly
formed Mazda Research and Development of North America Inc. will
handle product testing and evaluation and development of new
materials and other research.
   Hiroshi Moriyoshi was named president of that company, which is
based in Irvine, where it has a new $23 million design center. MRA
also has operations in Ann Arbor and Flat Rock, Mich., and in
Washington, D.C. It is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Mazda (North
America) Inc.
   Mazda Motor Manufacturing (USA) Corp. builds cars at Mazda's new
assembly plant in Flat Rock. The plant began production in
September, building the Ford Probe and the Mazda MX-6, both sporty
coupes.
   The Flat Rock plant also will begin building the Mazda 626 sedan
in 1989.
   Mazda (North America) Inc., also based in Irvine, will ship cars
from the Flat Rock plant, supply parts and accessories to the plant
and to Mazda Motor of America and provide other parent-company
support.
</TEXT>
